<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Museveni Advises Public to Fight Corruption </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
KAMPALA, August 24 (Xinhua) -- Ugandan President Yoweri
Museveni has advised the general public to know and assert their
rights against corrupt government officials and encouraged them
to report cases of corruption to the inspectorate of government.
</P>
<P>
He made the call in a speech read for him by the Minister of
the Presidency Ruhakana Rugunda at the opening of a three-day
regional ombudsman conference for west, south and eastern Africa
here Monday morning, Uganda News Agency reported.
</P>
<P>
Museveni said the inspectors-general from the participating
countries can contribute to popular democracy if they execute
their work with impartiality, professionalism and courage.
</P>
<P>
The ombudsmen from more than 18 countries were urged to show a
common resolve to stamp out corruption, bad governance and lack
of accountability which led to siphoning out hard earned meager
resources by corrupt elements in the government.
</P>
<P>
He said he hopes the ombudsmen can play a vital role in
nurturing the young democracies in Africa to ensure justice is
guaranteed for all.
</P>
<P>
Ugandan Inspector-General Jotham Tumwesigye said the meeting
will compare notes on how to uproot corruption and dictatorship
from member countries.
</P>
<P>
Marten Oosting, president of the International Ombudsman
Institute and also the ombudsman of the Netherlands, hailed
Uganda's rapid progress in this field, adding that over the past
12 years, Uganda's leadership has been remarkable in defense of
human rights. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
