<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Bonn to Seek New Sanctions against Belgrade </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
BONN, August 24 (Xinhua) -- The German government has decided
to seek new sanctions against Belgrade along with its European
Union partners in order to force an end to the conflict in
Yugoslavia's province of Kosovo, a German government spokesman
said Monday.
</P>
<P>
At a meeting on the Kosovo situation on Monday, the German
cabinet expressed "extreme concern" over the escalation of
violence in Kosovo, and especially from the Yugoslav side, German
government spokesman Otto Hauser said.
</P>
<P>
"If the situation worsened further, a military intervention
could become necessary," Hauser warned.
</P>
<P>
He also said that the German government had decided to seek
along with its EU partners a new package of sanctions against
Belgrade, which includes:
</P>
<P>
-- Freezing the bank accounts of all Yugoslav banks and
companies in which the Yugoslav state has a majority holding.
</P>
<P>
-- Introducing visa restrictions for Yugoslav businessmen and
travellers.
</P>
<P>
-- A ban on all Yugoslav airlines at airports in all EU
countries.
</P>
<P>
-- Strengthening EU efforts to pass on information regarding
criminal actions in Kosovo to the International Court of Justice
for Yugoslavia in the Hague, the Netherlands.
</P>
<P>
-- Monitoring Kosovo-Albanian associations in Germany to
prevent them from purchasing weapons with funds raised in Germany.
</P>
<P>
"The world community must make it clear that they will not
tolerate the violence policy and will act with determination,"
said Hauser.
</P>
<P>
According to a spokesman of the German Foreign Ministry, German
Foreign Minister Klaus Kinkel would call for a special meeting of
EU foreign ministers to discuss the sanctions.  
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
