<HEADLINE> Women Smokers More Likely to Suffer from Heart Attacks </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
GENEVA, August 24 (Xinhua) -- Women smokers in the 35-64 age
group in many countries are more likely to suffer from heart
attacks, said the world Health Organization (WHO) in a press
release here Monday.
</P>
<P>
Men are faring better while heart disease rates for women are
receding more slowly and the increasing numbers of daily smokers
in many countries do not augur well for the future, according to a
WHO study.
</P>
<P>
The WHO launched its MONICA Project in 1982 when investigators
from 38 centers in 21 countries started working together using
standardized methods to study trends in heart disease and
associated risk factors.
</P>
<P>
The finding is part of preliminary analysis of the final
10-year results of the largest collaborative study of heart
disease ever undertaken.
</P>
<P>
WHO experts revealed the results drawn from examining 150,000
heart attacks and 180,000 risk factor records at the European
Congress of Cardiology in Vienna, Austria.
</P>
<P>
"Over the years, the project generated an enormous amount of
high quality data which helps us to understand better the
relationship between trends in cardiovascular disease and major
risk factors," said Dr Ingrid Martin who is in charge of the
cardiovascular diseases program.
</P>
<P>
The WHO study has also found some good news: heart disease
rates are declining in general, with exceptions in some eastern
European countries and China.
</P>
<P>
At the present time, the study said, there is a much better
chance of surviving a heart attack than in the past, due to a
range of effective treatments.
</P>
<P>
The global death toll directly attributed to cardiovascular
disease is 15 million a year. Heart disease alone is responsible
for seven million deaths in the world each year.  
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
