<HEADLINE> Five Die in Flooding in Southwestern Texas </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
WASHINGTON, August 24 (Xinhua) -- Five deaths were reported in
flooding in southwestern Texas after heavy rains that also forced
people to flee homes and riverside parks Sunday.
</P>
<P>
The Tropical Storm Charley has inundated the region with more
than 30 centimeters of rain on Sunday and more rain fell Monday,
forcing a neighborhood in the border city of Del Rio to evacuate
early in the morning.
</P>
<P>
Tropical Storm Charley rolled ashore from the Gulf of Mexico
late Friday and early Saturday. It then weakened into a tropical
depression but the remnants of the system have sat nearly
stationary over Del Rio, pouring water on a region.
</P>
<P>
"All the rivers are out of their banks," Chris Steinbruck, a
dispatcher for police in Uvalde, was quoted by the Associated
Press as saying.
</P>
<P>
The National Weather Service said Del Rio got a record 11.87 30
centimeters of rain on Sunday to accumulate a total of 37
centimeters in the month, surpassing the city's previous record
for the entire month of of 15.5 centimeters.
</P>
<P>
Nearly 2.5 meters of water in part of Garner State Park,
located along the Frio River in Uvalde County, drove people to
move some 100 campsites to higher ground. 
</P>
</TEXT>
