<HEADLINE> Museveni Returns From Pretoria Meeting </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
KAMPALA, August 24 (Xinhua) -- Ugandan President Yoweri
Museveni has returned from a regional summit in S. Africa which
called for an immediate cease-fire between the warring sides in
the Democratic Republic of Congo (DRC).
</P>
<P>
On arriving at Entebbe International Airport Monday, the
president who was accompanied by the Minister of State for
Foreign Affairs in charge of Regional Cooperation Amama Mbabazi
was greeted by senior government officials, Radio Uganda said.
</P>
<P>
The regional summit, called by S. African President Nelson
Mandela, were attended by presidents of Uganda, Rwanda and some
others, was followed by a summit meeting of the Southern African
Development Community (SADC).
</P>
<P>
President of Zimbabwe, who strongly supports sending troops to
Congo to help President Laurent Kabila, and Kabila himself, did
not turn up at the regional summit.
</P>
<P>
The SADC meeting on Sunday called for a cease-fire and troop
standstill in Congo.
</P>
<P>
Since August 2, Tutsi-led soldiers in Congo have been fighting
against the army loyal to Kabila. Recently rebels claimed that
they had occupied one third of the country and are advancing
toward capital Kinshasa.
</P>
<P>
Uganda and Rwanda were accused of formenting the revolt, a
charge both countries immediately denied.
</P>
<P>
Recently, Zimbabwe and Angola are reported to have sent troops
to help stabilize Kaliba's shaky position. BBC said Angolan
troops took control of an airport in Kitona, a military base in
the west, which used to be used to transport supplies for rebels.
</P>
</TEXT>
