<DOCNO> XIE19980825.0012 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1998-08-25 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> ILO, UNICEF Launch Program to Eliminate Child Labor </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
KATHMANDU, August 24 (Xinhua) -- The International Labor
Organization (ILO) and the United Nations Children's Fund (UNICEF)
announced Monday the launching of a joint program entitled "Toward
the Elimination of Bonded Child Labor in Nepal."
</P>
<P>
The program will be implemented in nine of the 75 districts in
Nepal, where children are toiling as bonded labor in brick-kilns,
stonequarries, hotels, restaurants and carpet factories, the
Kathmandu office of ILO said in a press release.
</P>
<P>
The Italian Trade Unions in collaboration with the
Confederation of Italian Industry has raised over one million U.S.
dollars to support the efforts of ILO and UNICEF in eliminating
child labor in Bangladesh, Nepal and Pakistan, the press release
said.
</P>
<P>
In Nepal, different components of the program will be
implemented by workers, employers and non-governmental
organizations (NGOs) with the assistance of ILO and UNICEF, it
said.
</P>
<P>
It said that the program aims to increase the capacity of
employers, workers and NGOs to prevent and combat child labor,
prevent bonded child labor, withdraw children from bonded labor
and provide them and their families with alternatives.
</P>
<P>
In 1995, ILO launched the international program on the
elimination of child labor to help the country build capacity to
address the problem of child labor, foster the development of an
effective partnership between government services, employers
organizations, trade unions, NGOs, universities and media, the
press release said.
</P>
<P>
It said that UNICEF's child protection program in Nepal will
concentrate for the coming four years on building societal concern
and responsibility for children especially in difficult
circumstances, and on measures at the family, community and other
levels to prevent child exploitation, abuse and neglect.
</P>
<P>
UNICEF
ill assist in providing educational opportunities for working
children and bonded child labor in Nepal, the press release said.
</P>
<P>
Furthermore, UNICEF will disseminate the findings of a national
situational analysis of child labor in Nepal and assist in the
formulation of policies and programs, it added.
</P>
<P>
Statistics show that child laborers in Nepal have doubled in
the past four years to one million.
</P>
<P>
The South Asian countries -- Bangladesh, Bhutan, India, the
Maldives, Nepal, Pakistan and Sri Lanka, have decided to eliminate
the evil of child labor from the region by the year 2010. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
