<BODY>
<HEADLINE> 2 Foreign Journalists Detained in Congo Freed </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
LUSAKA, August 24 (Xinhua) -- Two foreign journalists detained
by border guards in the Democratic Republic of Congo (DRC) last
week were released Monday, according to Zambia News Agency ZANA.
</P>
<P>
Lara Santoro, an Italian working for the Christain Science
Monitor of the United States and New Zealander Hugh Nevill of
Agence France Presse (AFP), both based in Nairobi, Kenya were
released Monday morning.
</P>
<P>
Both Congolese and Zambian immigration officers at the
Kasumbalesa border post confirmed the freedom of the two
journalists in separate interviews with ZANA.
</P>
<P>
The immigration officers said that the Congolese border guards
did not find any credible offense to warrant continued
incarceration of the journalists.
</P>
<P>
After their release, Santoro and Nevill crossed the
Zambian-Congolese border into Zambia and joined their companion,
Odd Andersen, a Norwegian photo journalist also of AFP but based
in Johannesburg, South Africa.
</P>
<P>
Andersen had remained behind on the Zambian side of the check
point when Santoro and Nevill sauntered to the Congolese side
where they were detained last Wednesday.
</P>
<P>
The three intended to enter the troubled former Zaire to cover
the war situation in that country when some border guards pounced
on them.
</P>
<P>
Since conflicts broke out on August 2, Congolese officials are
said to be reluctant to allow foreign journalists to enter their
country on allegations of unfavorable coverage of the war
situation by foreign media. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
