<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Sudanese Opposition Backs Egypt's Call for World </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
CAIRO, August 24 (Xinhua) -- A Sudanese opposition leader
expressed support Monday for the Egypt's call for an international
anti-terrorism conference to define principles and strategies in
regional and global terrorism fighting.
</P>
<P>
Sadeq Mahdi, head of the Sudanese opposition Ummah Party, made
the remarks here after a meeting with Egyptian Foreign Minister
Amr Moussa, Egypt's Middle East News Agency said.
</P>
<P>
In its response to Thursday's U.S. missile attacks on what it
described as "terrorist-related" targets in Sudan and Afghanistan
following the twin bombings of U.S. embassies in Kenya and
Tanzania, Egypt on Friday renewed its call for an international
conference on combating terrorism.
</P>
<P>
Egypt, which did not openly condemned the U.S. attacks, said
Friday that terrorism should be dealt with within international
legitimacy and it does not approve any unilateral measure in this
regard.
</P>
<P>
The U.S. missile flattened a pharmaceutical plant, which it
said was producing ingredients for chemical weapons.
</P>
<P>
Mahdi along with other major Sudanese opposition leaders came
to Cairo early this month to attend a conference of the National
Democratic Alliance (NDA), the umbrella group of all Sudanese
opposition factions in the north and south.
</P>
<P>
The opposition has released a statement in Cairo, urging the
U.N. to send a fact-finding mission to determine whether the plant
was involved in terrorist activities as claimed by the U.S., or it
was a civil target as insisted by Khartoum.
</P>
<P>
Egypt, which has disputes over border and other hanging issues
with Sudan, has changed its low-profile policy in Sudan's civil
war recently by hosting for the first time the NDA conference, for
fear that the escalating fighting in Sudan can lead to the
division of the country and affect the control of the Nile River,
the water source of Egypt.
</P>
<P>
The Sudanese People's Liberation Army has been fighting since
1983 for greater autonomy for the Christian and Animists in the
south from the Islamic north.
</P>
<P>
The war and the consequent famines have claimed over 1.5
million lives in the poor African country. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
