<DOCNO> XIE19980825.0017 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1998-08-24 17:18 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Arab League Strongly Condemns U.S. Bombing Against </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
CAIRO, August 24 (Xinhua) -- The Arab League (AL) condemned
Monday the U.S. missile attack against Sudan as an aggression
against an Arab country's sovereignty and territorial integrity.
</P>
<P>
In a resolution following an emergency meeting, the AL
Ministerial Council also pledged strong support for the Sudanese
government.
</P>
<P>
The emergency meeting was held at the request of Sudan to seek
Arab support in its confrontation with the U.S., whose attack
flattened a pharmaceutical plant near Khartoum Thursday with the
claim that the factory produces ingredients for chemical weapons.
</P>
<P>
U.S. officials claimed the plant has link to Osama Bin Laden,
the Saudi billionaire it blames for the twin bombings of
U.S. embassies in Kenya and Tanzania on August 7.
</P>
<P>
In the resolution, the council urged the U.S., as a permanent
Security Council member and a major superpower, to "show respect
for international legitimacy and refrain from such actions that
constitute an assault on sovereignty of a nation and instigate a
vicious cycle of violence and counter-violence to the detriment of
world peace and security."
</P>
<P>
The council also appealed to the international community to
stand firm against the use of force in solving problems between
countries.
</P>
<P>
After Thursday's air strike, Sudan has received strong backing
from some of Washington's staunch Middle East opponents, including
Iraq, Libya and Iran, which roundly condemned the U.S. military
raid. But some other Arab countries remained silent. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
