<DOCNO> XIE19980825.0018 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1998-08-25 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> U.S. Agrees to Try Libyan Suspects in Netherlands </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
WASHINGTON, August 24 (Xinhua) -- The United States, Britain
and the Netherlands had agreed on a plan to set up a Scottish court
in the Hague to try two Libyan suspects charged for blowing a Pan
Am flight over Lockerbie, Scotland, in 1988, U.S. Secretary of
State Madeleine Albright announced on Monday.
</P>
<P>
"We have decided to go forward with a trial of the two
suspects before a Scottish court with Scottish judges applying
Scottish law" in the Netherlands, a third country, Albright told
reporters at a special briefing.
</P>
<P>
"We thank the Netherlands government for indicating its
willingness to host this proceeding," she added.
</P>
<P>
"After consultations with the Netherlands, we have concluded
that such a trial is indeed possible," she said.
</P>
<P>
Albright said the step "is fully consistent with U.N.
Security Council resolution," calling it "a way to bring the
fugitives into court at long last."
</P>
<P>
The Pan Am bombing killed all 259 passengers and crew, and 11
people on the ground in Lockerbie, Scotland. Among the dead were
189 Americans.
</P>
<P>
But Albright made no mention of the possibility of lifting the
sanctions.
</P>
<P>
The U.S. position has been that the two Libyans should be
turned over to American or British authorities for trial, but
Libyan leader Moammar Gadhafi has refused, saying the two men
would not receive a fair trial in the United States or Britain.
</P>
<P>
The Libyan government proposed in 1994 that the two men be
tried in a third country.
</P>
<P>
President Bill Clinton confirmed in July that the United
States and Britain were considering the Libyan offer.
</P>
<P>
Now a compromise came after diplomatic maneuvering by the
Organization of African Unity, the Arab League and former U.S.
President Jimmy Carter. But Washington and London agreed on the
compromise only on the condition that the court be set up in a
third country with Scottish judges under the Scottish law.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
