<HEADLINE> UK, US Agree to Stage Lockerbie Trial in Holland </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
LONDON, August 24 (Xinhua) -- British Foreign Secretary Robin
Cook announced Monday that the British and U.S. governments had
agreed that the two Libyans accused of undertaking 1988 Lockerbie
bombing should be tried in the Netherlands.
</P>
<P>
Cook said in a statement issued here Monday afternoon that he
had spoken to U.N. Secretary-General Kofi Annan and asked Annan to
help in arranging the transfer of the two Libyans named Abdel
Basset Ali Megrahi and Lamen Khalifa Fhimah.
</P>
<P>
Cook also made it clear: "As soon as they are handed over for
trial, we will support action in the (U.N.) Security Council to
suspend the international sanctions against Libya."
</P>
<P>
However, Cook noted that the trial, due to be held in The
Hague, would be "a Scottish court administering Scottish law under
Scottish procedures and Scottish rules of evidence."
</P>
<P>
This particular trial would be one without jury as it was not
practical to ask 15 ordinary citizens to spend many months in a
foreign country, cook added.
</P>
<P>
Some 270 people were killed when a Pan AM airliner exploded
over the Scottish town of Lockerbie on December 21, 1988, and the
U.N. imposed international sanctions against Libya in 1992 after
the Libyan government refused to hand over the allled bombers.
</P>
</TEXT>
