<HEADLINE> Peaceful Solution, Only Way Out for Congo Crisis: </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
LUANDA, August 24 (Xinhua) -- U.S. President Bill Clinton's
special envoy, Howard Wolpe, said here Monday that the U.S.
government has ruled out the possibility of resolving the crisis
in the Democratic Republic of Congo (DRC) militarily.
</P>
<P>
Wolpe said his government believes that political and
diplomatic solution is the only way out for the Congo crisis,
ruling out the possibility of resolving it in a military way.
</P>
<P>
"We desire to find a solution which will not make any country
in the region uneasy and in a way that it will help resolve the
internal issues in Democratic Congo, for instance, granting
citizenships to the (ethnic Tutsi) Banyamulunge and including all
political forces in the government," said the U.S. envoy.
</P>
<P>
He added that the United States hopes such a solution will
delay or pre-empt a human catastrophe in the central African
country.
</P>
<P>
Angolan President Jose Eduardo dos Santos had talks with the
U.S. envoy, exchanging views on the developments in Congo crisis.
During the talks, Wolpe conveyed to President Dos Santos a letter
from U.S. President Bill Clinton.
</P>
<P>
"We discussed how to resolve the Congo crisis peacefully,
including the withdrawal of all foreign troops from the country,"
the U.S. envoy noted.
</P>
<P>
At the joint press conference after the meeting, Wolpe
described his talks with the Angolan president as "positive and
constructive." 
</P>
</TEXT>
