<DATE_TIME> 1998-08-24 17:31 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Nicosia Calls for National Unity to Solve Cyprus </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
NICOSIA, August 24 (Xinhua) -- Cypriot Foreign Minister Ioannis
Kasoulides called for national unity in dealing with the
protracted Cyprus problem.
</P>
<P>
"What we need now is unity among the political ranks to tackle
issues of national interests in the best possible manner,"
Kasoulides said.
</P>
<P>
Kasoulides' appeal came amid calls by local politicians for
President Glafcos Clerides' resignation should the Russian
missiles the Cypriot government has contracted to buy can not be
deployed on the island as planned.
</P>
<P>
"President Clerides is not abandoning his responsibilities,"
Kasoulides told reporters.
</P>
<P>
He noted that the decision to deploy the missiles remains in
force unless there is sufficient progress toward a solution of the
Cyprus problem or moves leading to the demilitarization of the
island.
</P>
<P>
Cyprus has been divided into Turkish Cypriot-controlled north
and Greek Cypriot-dominated south since 1974 when Turkey landed
its troops and took over the north third of the island in the wake
of a pro-Athens coup.
</P>
<P>
The Turkish Cypriots unilaterally declared a breakaway state in
northern Cyprus in 1983, which is recognized only by Turkey.
</P>
<P>
Cyprus clinched a deal with Russia in January last year to buy
the surface-to-air S-300 missiles, which are expected to be
deployed on the island in November.
</P>
<P>
The deal has drawn strong protest from Turkey, which has
threatened to launch pre-emptive strikes if Cyprus insists on the
deployment of the missiles on the island.
</P>
<P>
The U.N.-sponsored peace talks have been deadlocked since last
summer when Turkish Cypriots opted out of the negotiations to
protest against the European Union's decision to begin membership
talks with Cyprus, but not their close ally Turkey.
</P>
<P>
Asked if the Athens talks between Clerides and Greek Premier
Costas Simitis Wednesday will deal with a possible postponement of
the missiles deployment, Kasoulides only said "we shall examine
defense and arms acquisition issues in general." 
</P>
</TEXT>
