<HEADLINE> Annan Welcomes U.S., U.K. Decision on Lockerbie </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
UNITED NATIONS, August 24 (Xinhua) -- U.N. Secretary-General
Kofi Annan on Monday said he welcomed a U.S.-UK decision to set up
a Scottish court in the Netherlands to try two Libyans accused of
blowing up a U.S. airline over Scotland in 1988.
</P>
<P>
Annan, who was informed of the decision in Monday morning by
the U.S. and UK governments, said that he "is extremely pleased
with" the joint decision. Earlier Monday, U.S. Secretary of State
Madeline Albright announced the decision in Washington.
</P>
<P>
The U.N. chief, in a press statement issued here via his
spokesman Fred Eckhard, also voiced his hope that "all sides
will cooperate in order to reach an early solution of this
long-standing issue."
</P>
<P>
The airline bombing, which took place over Lockerbie,
Scotland, killed all 259 passengers and crew, and 11 people on
the ground.
</P>
<P>
Libya has long been locked in a dispute on where to try the two
Libyan suspects. The United States and Britain insisted on the use
of Scottish judges rather than an international panel. The
proposed court will be chaired by three Scottish high court judges
and the trial will proceed under normal Scottish law.
</P>
<P>
The United States and Britain asked the U.N. chief to convey to
the Libyan Government a letter, which has elaborated the U.S. and
British proposal, the spokesman said.
</P>
<P>
Annan, currently on vocation in his home country Ghana, was
also asked "to provide to the Libyan Government any assistance it
might require with regard to the physical arrangements for the
transfer of the two accused directly to the Netherlands, the
statement said.
</P>
<P>
Over the past months, the Secretary-General has been
following this issue very closely and has been in contact with
Governments of the United States, Britain and the Netherlands
and other interested parties, the statement added.  
</P>
</TEXT>
