<HEADLINE> Sudan to Take Steps Facing Possible </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
KHARTOUM, August 24 (Xinhua) -- Sudanese President Omar
Al-Bashir said here Monday that his government would take
necessary legal steps to counter potential U.S. strike on his
country.
</P>
<P>
Speaking at a press conference, the Sudanese leader lashed out
at the United States for attacking a plant in north Khartoum that
produces human and veterinary medicines.
</P>
<P>
Five U.S. fighter planes attacked Al-Shifaa pharmaceutical
plant in the industrial zone in north Khartoum on Thursday night
and left it completely destroyed. The material losses amount to
100 million U.S. dollars apart from a number of casualties,
officials said.
</P>
<P>
The U.S. claimed that the plant is a terrorist-related factory
where chemical weapons were produced.
</P>
<P>
Western media circulated reports that the United States was
planning to launch another strike on an underground plant for
chemical weapons also in Khartoum.
</P>
<P>
However, Al-Bashir did not go into details on what steps his
government would take.
</P>
<P>
He accused U.S. President Bill Clinton of trying to cover up
the alleged affairs with Monica Lewinsky, a former White House
intern.
</P>
<P>
Sudan has requested that the U.N. Security Council send a
fact-finding committee to investigate the attack.
</P>
<P>
The Saudi billionaire Osama Bin Laden, the owner of the plant
and No.1 terrorist wanted by the U.S. for a series of terrorist
attacks, has no relation to the plant that the U.S. thought as a
terrorist base.
</P>
<P>
Al-Shifaa Company used to be owned by Ba-Aboud Co. for Trade
and Navigation which is registered with the Jeddah Chamber of
Commerce under relevant Saudi laws, said the president.
</P>
<P>
Bashir Hassan Bashir, a Sudanese national, used to own 60
percent of its shares till March, 1998. Then it moved to the hands
of the Sudanese businessman Salah Ahmed Idris, he said.
</P>
<P>
He added that Laden was expelled from Sudan in 1996 in response
to a request from the United States. Laden left Sudan to
Afghanistan where he lives up till now.
</P>
<P>
The type of fighters that attacked the plant can not take off
from anywhere other than a neighboring country, he said, without
identifying the country.
</P>
<P>
Commenting on Egyptian Foreign Minister Amr Moussa's denial of
rumors on the take-off of the U.S. fighters from Egyptian
territories, Bashir said "we hope that is true."
</P>
<P>
He stressed that all the U.S. allegations and calculations were
untrue and baseless, citing the British and U.S. engineers who
took part in construction of the plant as saying that "the plant
is technically unable to produce chemical weapons."
</P>
<P>
On the recent U.S.-Sudanese contacts, Al-Bashir said that the
U.S. welcomed the return to Washington of Sudanese Ambassador
Al-Fateh Bin-Orwa who was withdrawn following Thursday's attack.
</P>
<P>
He made it clear that the United States based its calculation
of the attacks on erroneous information from Sudanese opposition
elements who seek money by any means.
</P>
<P>
He underlined that if the plant were able to produce chemical
weapons, the strike on the plant would have caused a great
catastrophe. However, no one was affected by any gas although the
plant was at a residential zone, he noted.
</P>
<P>
He asked Clinton to apologize to the Sudanese people and
compensate the owners and workers of the plant. 
</P>
</TEXT>
