<HEADLINE> U.S. Threatens Oil Sanctions if Libya Withholds Suspects </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
WASHINGTON, August 24 (Xinhua) -- The United States would
press for international oil sanctions against Libya if it failed to
hand over two men charged for the bombing of a Pan Am flight
over Lockerbie, Scotland, in 1988, a senior U.S. official said
on Monday.
</P>
<P>
The threat came after U.S. Secretary of State Madeleine
Albright announced earlier on Monday that Washington and Britain
agreed under the agreement of the Netherlands to set up a court
in the Hague with Scottish judges applying Scottish law for a
trial of the two suspects.
</P>
<P>
If Libya turned down the offer by the United States and
Britain, "We think we are capable of building a much stronger
international consensus around further steps that must be
taken," said the senior official, asked not to be identified.
</P>
<P>
Albright told a special briefing that the United States and
Britain "have decided to go forward with Scottish judges
applying Scottish law" in the Netherlands for the trial of the
two Libyans.
</P>
<P>
"America is determined to see that the perpetrators of
terrorism are brought to account," Albright said.
</P>
<P>
The senior official said Albright "made it very clear that
she is obviously extremely interested and supportive of moving
on, particularly in the direction of oil sanctions."
</P>
<P>
The United States has banned American imports of Libyan oil,
but has so far been unable to persuade other countries to follow
suit. The official said if Libya failed to come to terms with
the United States and Britain, he believed other countries would
now be more willing to join in the ranks with the United States
and Britain in imposing oil sanctions against Libya.  
</P>
</TEXT>
