<HEADLINE> Iranian President Hopes Pakistan to Help Release </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
TEHRAN, August 24 (Xinhua) -- Iranian President Mohammad
Khatami Monday expressed the hope that the Pakistani government
would use its influence to persuade the Afghan Taliban militia to
release the captured Iranian diplomats.
</P>
<P>
In a meeting with visiting Pakistani Minister of State for
Foreign Affairs Sidique Khan Kanju, Khatami said there is no
doubt that the Iranian diplomats are in hands of the Taliban and
Iran will never remain indifferent toward the fate of the
Iranians, the official news agency IRNA reported.
</P>
<P>
"We decisively expect our friends in Pakistan to inform us of
the fate of the Iranian captives" and "to make the
Taliban ...immediately release them all," he said.
</P>
<P>
Iran has said that the Taliban forces kidnaped 11 Iranian
diplomats and an IRNA reporter earlier this month when the
fundamentalist group seized the northern town of Mazari Sharif,
the main stronghold of the Iran-backed opposition. However,
Taliban denied the capture.
</P>
<P>
The Iranian president expressed concern that outside hands are
at work to hindering improvement of situation in the region.
</P>
<P>
He said that the joint enemies of Iran and Pakistan have a role
in this crisis by perpetrating provocative acts. He expressed the
hope that the officials of the two countries would overcome the
crisis through wisdom and vigilance.
</P>
<P>
Khatami called on Pakistan, a strong supporter of the Taliban,
to launch satisfactory efforts in this respect and said "our
friendship is very fundamental and has not been gained at a low
price."
</P>
<P>
He warned that "the malignant factors" are working hard to
disrupt the friendly relations between the two countries.
</P>
<P>
The Iranian president said he believes that the Taliban's rule
over Afghanistan would be a shaky one and constantly prone to
attacks by other ethnic groups and would create problems for
Pakistan in the long run.
</P>
<P>
During the meeting, Kanju handed over a message from Pakistani
Prime Minister Nawaz Sharif to Khatami and said the Pakistani
government and nation would spare no effort to alleviate the
anxiety in the region and help release the Iranian diplomats.
</P>
<P>
The Pakistani official arrived here Sunday night and held
talks with Iranian Foreign Minister Kamal Kharrazi who expressed
dissatisfaction with Islamabad's performance over the issue of
captured Iranians. Kanju has left Tehran for home. 
</P>
</TEXT>
