<HEADLINE> CIS Countries on Dismissal of Russian Government </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
MOSCOW, August 24 (Xinhua) -- Russian President Boris Yeltsin
dismissed the government headed by Sergei Kiriyenko and named
former premier Viktor Chernomyrdin as acting Prime Minister last
Sunday, to which many member-states of the Commonwealth of
Independent States made responses.
</P>
<P>
According to the Itar-Tass news agency, Georgian President
Eduard Shevardnadze expressed hope that the Russian president's
decision would enhance stability in Russia. "For Georgia the most
important thing is that Russia preserve and strengthen its
stability," he stressed.
</P>
<P>
The Tajik president's press secretary Zafar Saidov told Tass
that Yeltsin's decision is an "entirely internal affair of Russia,
it will in no way affect the traditionally friendly relations
between our countries."
</P>
<P>
The Kirgiz president's press secretary Kanybek Imanaliyev also
told a briefing on Monday that the Russian government's
resignation is Russia's internal affair, that everything that
happens in Russia is important for them.
</P>
<P>
In Minsk, Ivan Korotchenya, first deputy executive secretary of
the commonwealth, expressed confidence that "Viktor Chernomyrdin's
return to the Russian government will boost the structural reform
to the CIS."
</P>
<P>
He also expressed hope that Chernomyrdin's reappointment would
help restore the weakened ties between the CIS and the Russia
government.
</P>
<P>
Moldavian President petru Luchinschi expressed hope that
"Chernomyrdin's experience and influence will overcome the severe
financial crisis that hit the Russian Federation this Summer."
</P>
<P>
Lithuanian President Valdas Adamkus' spokeswoman said the
replacement of the Russian government "will not impair the
developing good-neighborly relations" between the two countries,
that the new Russian government headed by experienced politician
Chernomyrdin will succeed in rescuing the country from the current
economic and financial difficulties.  
</P>
