<HEADLINE> U.S. Effort on Cyprus to Continue: Ambassador </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
NICOSIA, August 24 (Xinhua) -- U.S. ambassador to Cyprus
Kenneth Brill, assured Cyprus Monday that Washington will continue
its efforts for a settlement to the protracted Cyprus problem.
</P>
<P>
Emerging from a meeting with President Glafcos Clerides, Brill
said "we will continue to work on all the issues that relate to
Cyprus and ways to make progress."
</P>
<P>
He dismissed a report that the U.S. efforts on Cyprus have
reached a dead end, noting "there are opportunities to find
constructive ways."
</P>
<P>
Cyprus has remained divided into Greek Cypriot-dominated south
and Turkish Cypriot-controlled north since 1974 when Turkey landed
its troops and took over the northern third of the island in the
wake of a failed pro-Athens coup.
</P>
<P>
The Turkish Cypriots declared unilaterally a breakaway "Turkish
Republic of Northern Cyprus" in 1983, which is recognized only by
Turkey.
</P>
<P>
The U.N.-sponsored peace talks have been stalled since last
summer when Turkish Cypriots walked out of the negotiations to
protest against a European Union (EU) decision to start accession
talks with Cyprus, but not their strong supporter Turkey.
</P>
<P>
Turkish Cypriot leader Rauf Denktash said that he will not
return to the talks unless his self-styled regime is
internationally recognized and Cyprus withdraws its application
for an EU membership.
</P>
<P>
Both the U.S. Presidential Emissary Richard Holbrooke and State
Department Special Coordinator for Cyprus Thomas Miller have
failed to convince the two sides to go back to negotiating table
during their shuttle over the past few months. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
