<HEADLINE> Mozambican Grain Output to Exceed 1.9M Tons: </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
MAPUTO, August 24 (Xinhua) -- The Mozambican Ministry of
Agriculture and Fishery has predicted that the grain output in
the country in 1998/99 will reach 1.936 million tons, a 15
percent increase against 1997/98.
</P>
<P>
The prediction was made at the three-day meeting of the third
Coordination Council of the Ministry of Agriculture and Fishery
which ended Saturday in suburban Maputo, the Noticias newspaper
reported Monday.
</P>
<P>
The council said the output of maize in 1998/99 will go up by
25 percent over the previous year's to 1.405 million tons while
that of rice will increase by 13 percent to 215,000 tons.
</P>
<P>
The output growth of these two crops has been attributed to an
expansion of planting acreage by 468,000 hectares to 2.432
million hectares.
</P>
<P>
However, the output of sorghum and millet will decrease by 17
percent and four percent respectively, said the agriculture
ministry.
</P>
<P>
The ministry predicted that the output of sorghum will drop
from 318,000 tons in 1997/98 to 265,000 tons due to the decreased
planting acreage and that the millet output will be only 51,000
tons.
</P>
<P>
For the harvest year 1998/99, the ministry also forecast that
the output of peanuts will go up by 62 percent, reaching 231,000
tons thanks to the increase of planting acreage.
</P>
<P>
Beans will witness an increase of 23 percent, topping 234,000
tons while the output of cassava will also go up by 23 percent,
harvesting 6.934 million tons.
</P>
<P>
The ministry said that the total planting acreage in the
country next year will be 4.833 million hectares, a one-third
rise over the previous year.
</P>
<P>
The Mozambican National Bureau of Agriculture has decided to
carry out a supplementary plan for maize and rice planting.
</P>
<P>
In line with the plan, some high quality seeds of maize and
rice will be chosen for use throughout the country according to
the conditions of soil, climate and transportation. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
