<HEADLINE> Britain Remains Opposed to S-300 Missiles' </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
NICOSIA, August 24 (Xinhua) -- British High Commissioner to
Cyprus David Madden Monday expressed the hope that the
Russian-made S-300 missile system ordered by the Cypriot
government will not be deployed on the island.
</P>
<P>
Speaking after a meeting with Cypriot President Glafcos
Clerides, Madden said "we are hoping that conditions will be such
that the S-300 does not need to come to the island of Cyprus. That
is what we are working for."
</P>
<P>
The Cypriot government ordered the surface-to-air S-300
missiles from Russia in January 1997 in a bid to boost the
country's air defense as against a possible Turkish offensive. The
missiles are scheduled to be delivered and deployed in November
this year.
</P>
<P>
The deal has sparked strong protests from Turkey, which has
vowed to block the delivery of the missiles and threatened to
launch preemptive strikes if they are deployed.
</P>
<P>
The British diplomat said there are various ways of achieving
the cancellation of the deployment of the missiles, noting that
"the question of a moratorium is still very much on the agenda and
we will see what progress can be made on that."
</P>
<P>
"If progress can't be made on that, we will try to make
progress in other areas as well," he added.
</P>
<P>
The U.S. has put forward a proposal for a moratorium of
flights by Greek and Turkish military planes over Cyprus, but
Turkey has rejected the idea.
</P>
<P>
The Cypriot government has said it will agree to the creation
of a no-fly zone over the island, provided there are sufficient
international guarantees.
</P>
<P>
Cyprus has remained divided into the Greek Cypriot-dominated
south and the Turkish Cypriot-controlled north since 1974 when
Turkey landed its troops and took over the northern third of the
island in the wake of a short-lived coup by some Greek Cypriots
seeking union with Greece.
</P>
<P>
Turkey maintains 35,000 troops in northern Cyprus, claiming to
protect the Turkish Cypriot minorities, who unilaterally declared
in 1983 the breakaway "Turkish Republic of Northern Cyprus,"
recognized only by Ankara. 
</P>
</TEXT>
