<HEADLINE> Security Council Calls for Immediate Ceasefire </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
UNITED NATIONS, August 24 (Xinhua) -- The U.N. Security Council
on Monday adopted a presidential statement, calling for "an
immediate ceasefire" in Kosovo, and urging all parties concerned
to strive for a political solution to the issue.
</P>
<P>
The presidential statement also urged the authorities of the
Federal Republic of Yugoslavia and the Kosovo Albanian leader to
"enter immediately into a meaningful dialogue" to find a
negotiated political solution to the issue of Kosovo.
</P>
<P>
Meanwhile, the Security Council said in the statement that it
welcomed the announcement of the formation of a negotiating team
to represent the interests of the Kosovo Albanian community,
saying that the establishment of such a panel should be conducive
to the early commencement of a substantial dialogue.
</P>
<P>
The 15-member Security Council adopted the presidential
statement as efforts are being made to bring the two parties to a
negotiation table. On August 18, the talks did not kick off as
scheduled after the Kosovo Albanian team failed to turn up in the
venue.
</P>
<P>
The statement was adopted after the Security Council discussed
a report by Secretary-General Kofi Annan on the issue of Kosovo.
</P>
<P>
The report, the fourth one by the U.N. chief since the conflict
broke out in February, said that the situation in Kosovo was
worsened in July by the failure of the Federal Republic of
Yugoslavia and the Kosovo Albanians to begin serious talks on the
future status of Kosovo.
</P>
<P>
Fighting in Kosovo, Serbia's southernmost province, has
recently been intensified and resulted in an increase of refugees
and displaced persons.
</P>
<P>
With the onset of the Balkan Winter, the situation of Kosovo
refugees "has the potential to become an even greater
humannitarian disaster," the statement added.
</P>
<P>
Ethnic Albanians made up 90 percent of the population in
Kosovo, which has an area of 10,000 square kilometers and a
population of 2 million.
</P>
<P>
Over the past six months, the conflict in Kosovo has caused
more than 500 deaths and created about 200,000 displaced people.
</P>
</TEXT>
