<HEADLINE> Cooking Gas Price Soars in Nigeria </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
LAGOS, August 24 (Xinhua) -- The price of cooking gas has more
than doubled in the last one month in Nigeria, just as acute
shortage of fuel and other petroleum products began to ease.
</P>
<P>
Investigations found that a 12.5-kilogram-cylinder of cooking
gas is now sold between 1,200 to 1,500 Naira (one U.S. Dollar
equals to about 85 Naira), compared with about 6,00 Naira a month
ago, the News Agency of Nigeria (NAN) said Monday.
</P>
<P>
Retailers and energy industry analysts have attributed the
high price to poor supply from the refineries.
</P>
<P>
"It is not our fault, we don't readily get gas to buy and when
we get we pay highly, and have to make our own profit," Emeka
Agu, a retailer was quoted by the NAN as saying.
</P>
<P>
Nigeria, a top African oil producer with a daily crude oil
output of about two million barrels, has been suffering from
persistent fuel shortage in the last few years, due to ailing
refineries.
</P>
<P>
The country's four refineries are either shut or not
functioning properly and consequently have not been producing
enough petroleum products, forcing the government to resort to
massive imports.
</P>
<P>
The latest fuel shortage which started several months ago is
only beginning to ease in the last few days.
</P>
<P>
A ray of hope is now in sight as it has been announced the
110,000-barrel-per-day refinery in Kaduna will resume normal
operation in early September after a major repair carried out by
the French oil firm Totol. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
