<HEADLINE> Security Council Discusses Iraqi Disarmament </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
UNITED NATIONS, August 24 (Xinhua) -- Support for diplomatic
efforts to solve the U.N.-Iraq standoff on arms inspections is
still dominating the Security Council while the United States is
trying to exert more pressure on Iraq for it to comply with U.N.
resolutions, diplomatic sources said on Monday.
</P>
<P>
At the council's informal consultations after the briefing of
Secretary-General Kofi Annan's special envoy to Iraq Prakash Shah,
many council members, such as China, France, Brazil and others,
expressed their view that Annan's initiatives are worth
considering or being put into action, the sources said.
</P>
<P>
They stood behind Annan's ideas for a comprehensive review of
the Iraqi issue since sanctions were imposed on Iraq because of
its invasion of Kuwait in 1990, by engaging Iraq more closely to
find ways of solving its differences with U.N. inspectors.
</P>
<P>
Chinese Deputy Representative to the U.N. Shen Guofang noted
that there can be no other solutions to the Iraqi issue except
through dialogue and negotiations. China has been backing Annan's
and others' diplomatic efforts in finding solutions, he said.
</P>
<P>
Meanwhile, the United States and Britain are mulling a draft
council resolution calling on Iraq to resume cooperation with U.N.
inspectors, warning that if Iraq fails to call off the suspension
of cooperation, the Security Council would be urged to stop the
periodic review of sanctions on Iraq, the sources said.
</P>
<P>
This may represent a step further toward prolonging the
eight-year sanctions, the sources added.
</P>
<P>
The sanctions won't be lifted until the council is convinced
that Iraq has no longer long-range missiles and chemical,
biological and nuclear weapons.
</P>
<P>
Iraq on August 5 decided to suspend cooperation with UNSCOM,
U.N. Special Commission for disarmament in Iraq, requesting a
restructure of UNSCOM to reduce what it calls the American
influence.
</P>
<P>
Iraq charges that the U.S. is using the arms inspection to
prolong sanctions on it.
</P>
<P>
"Unless this restructuring takes place, Iraq finds it very
difficult, almost impossible, to keep any meaningful cooperation
with UNSCOM," said Iraq's ambassador to the U.N. Nizar Hamdoon on
Monday.
</P>
<P>
The Security Council sees the Iraqi suspension of cooperation
as totally unacceptable.
</P>
<P>
Shah's latest meetings with Iraqi Deputy prime Minister Tariq
Aziz did not change Iraq's position.
</P>
<P>
He told reporters after today's briefing: "Basically, they (the
Iraqis) felt that since I had come there only with a message (for
them) to comply (with U.N. resolutions) and that I had no
proposals to negotiate with them, they had no reason to change the
decision taken August 5th."  
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
