<TEXT>
<P>
MOSCOW, August 24 (Xinhua) -- Russia's blue chips witnessed
their first rally in 10 days Monday amid thin trading as the
market awaited the terms of a conversion plan for the
ruble-denominated GKO Treasury bills.
</P>
<P>
A change of government had little effect on the stock market
except that shares of Gazprom shot up 24.2 percent on news that
its former head, Viktor Chernomyrdin, had been reinstated as the
prime minister.
</P>
<P>
Overall, the RTS-Interfax Composite Index rose 6.3 percent at
23.11 on Friday's close. The narrower RTS1-Interfax Index, which
does not include Gazprom, inched up 4.73 percent at 85.63.
</P>
<P>
The Federal Securities Commission twice suspended trading on
the Moscow Stock Exchange as Gazprom prices soared.
</P>
<P>
However, the slim volume of trading, at a mere 760,000, was too
low to consolidate the price rises, the Interfax news agency
reported.
</P>
<P>
According to the Russian Trading System, volume as of 17:00
local time (13:00 GMT) stood at only 4.28 million dollars.
</P>
<P>
Prices ended the day up 3 percent from Friday's close for
Unified Energy Systems at 0.053/0.055 dollar on volume of 20.72
million shares. Lukoil rose 6 percent at 5.22/5.34 dollars on
volume of 485,000 shares. Moscow power utility Mosenergo was up
1.5 percent at 0.029/0.025 dollar on volume of 12.6 million. Share
price for Russian long-distance carrier Rostelecom rose 12.5
percent at 0.844/0.9 dollar on volume of 200,000, Interfax
reported.  
