<HEADLINE> Middle East Economic Briefs </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
CAIRO, August 24 (Xinhua) -- The following are economic briefs
from Middle East countries.
</P>
<P>
BEIRUT -- Lebanon's national carrier, Middle East Airlines,
signed a cooperation agreement with Air France here Saturday to
improve services of the two airlines, the Daily Star reported
Monday.
</P>
<P>
Under the agreement, which will be in effect as of the summer
of 1999, passengers will be offered a wide choice of links between
Paris and Beirut, cooperation on information technology,
purchasing, catering and flight operation will also be enhanced.
</P>
<P>
KUWAIT CITY -- Kuwait's exports in July were nearly 6 million
Kuwaiti dinars (19.8 million U.S. dollars), according to official
statistics issued Monday.
</P>
<P>
Exports to Gulf Arab nations amounted to 4.1 million Kuwaiti
dinars (13.53 million U.S. dollars), accounting for 68 percent of
the total.
</P>
<P>
Items exported to the Gulf countries mainly were foodstuffs,
auto oil, paper, plastic and metal products, transport equipment,
textiles, furniture, chemicals and cables, the statistics showed.
</P>
<P>
And the exports to non-Arab countries included polyethylene,
cloths, beverages, insulation materials, biscuits and towels.
</P>
<P>
AMMAN -- Jordan will hold the first national meeting of
businessmen on September 7 to promote dialog between public and
private sectors, Jordan's official PETRA news agency reported on
Monday.
</P>
<P>
The meeting comes when Jordan is exerting efforts to make the
kingdom a regional center for medical services, higher education,
tourism, telecommunication and investment, the agency quoted Hamdi
Taba'a, head of the meeting's preparatory committee, as saying.
</P>
<P>
About 50,000 businessmen around the country will participate in
the five-day meeting, the agency said. 
</P>
