<HEADLINE> Hurricane Bonnie Churning Toward U.S. East Coast </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
WASHINGTON, August 24 (Xinhua) -- As Hurricane Bonnie was
churning up in the Atlantic with 185 kph winds, people in the East
Coast of the United States are busying on preparation for the
worst.
</P>
<P>
From Florida to North Carolina, local residents are stocking up
on emergency supplies while the governor of South Carolina, David
Beasley, called on 1,000 National Guard to get ready for Bonnie.
</P>
<P>
The National Hurricane Center reported the 720-kilometer-wide
storm was 1,040 kilometers southeast of Savannah, Georgia, at 2
p.m. EDT Monday.
</P>
<P>
The hurricane has been wobbling northwest. The center said a
hurricane watch may be issued for part of the southeastern U.S.
coast later Monday.
</P>
<P>
It was not clear exactly where, when or even if Hurricane
Bonnie would strike the U.S. mainland. But the hurricane center
officials said it could be as far west as northern Florida.
</P>
<P>
Two weather computer models indicated the hurricane could move
slowly northwest toward Georgia or South Carolina, but another
predicted the hurricane would pass 160 kilometers off North
Carolina's Outer Banks.
</P>
<P>
However, hurricane-force winds extended 135 kilometers out from
Bonnie's center and tropical storm force winds could be felt 360
kilometers out.
</P>
<P>
The Atlantic basin typically has nine tropical storms each
year, with six of them becoming hurricanes. In 1997, there were
seven named storms, three hurricanes and one intense hurricane.
</P>
</TEXT>
