<HEADLINE> U.S. Scientists Work On Memory Development </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
WASHINGTON, August 24 (Xinhua) -- Neuroscientists at Harvard
and Stanford universities have identified for the first time
specific parts of the brain that play a key role in determining
what we remember and what we forget.
</P>
<P>
The scientists reported their findings in the August 21 Science
that they asked volunteers to view words or photographs and
watched what was happening in their brains. When certain parts
of their brains -- the prefrontal lobes and the parahippocampal
cortex -- were most active, the subjects were much more likely
to remember what they had seen or read.
</P>
<P>
Meanwhile scientists at University of California in Irvine
have found a clue to why memory can fail during stressful moments.
</P>
<P>
24 hours after training laboratory rats to find a platform in
a tank of water, the scientists stressed the rodents by applying
small jolts to their feet. When the rats where placed in the
tank again 30 minutes later, they swam around randomly and could
not retrieve the memory of where the platform was located.
</P>
<P>
They found in rats levels of the hormone corticosterone peak
about 30 minutes after a stressful incident. The rats were able
to find the platform if two minutes or four hours had passed
after the stress-inducing shock. Rats injected with the hormone
also forgot how to find the target. However rats that were
stressed but given a drug to block corticosterone did fine.
</P>
<P>
Now the U.S. scientists are conducting similar experiments in
humans, who release a similar hormone--cortisol during stress.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> XIE19980825.0052 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1998-08-25 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Panel of Judges Rules Census Bureau can't Use Sampling </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
WASHINGTON, August 24 (Xinhua) -- In a victory for
congressional Republicans, a federal court panel Monday ruled that
the government cannot use statistical sampling to help count
Americans in the 2000 census.
</P>
<P>
The nation's founding fathers really meant it when they said
America must have "actual enumeration" of its populace, and a
modern statistical tool called "sampling" is not an acceptable
substitute, the three judges said in a unanimous ruling.
</P>
<P>
The 71-page opinion puts a stop to Census sampling, which is
favored by the Clinton administration, and means the delicate
issue of how Americans are counted will likely head to the Supreme
Court this fall.
</P>
<P>
"The use of statistical sampling to determine the population
for purposes of apportioning representatives in Congress among the
states violates the Census Act," the judges ruled.
</P>
<P>
The count, conducted every 10 years, is the basis for drawing
the boundary lines for congressional districts and other elected
offices and in determining how 180 billion dollars in federal
money is distributed.
</P>
<P>
The Clinton administration and congressional Democrats defended
the Census Bureau plan to use statistical sampling to reduce the
undercount of hard-to-reach minorities and the poor, often in
urban areas.
</P>
<P>
Republicans, who control Congress, said in their suit that the
plan was flawed and violated the Constitution's requirement for an
"actual enumeration." They also argued that Democrats would use
sampling for political gain.
</P>
<P>
The Justice Department and lawyers for the House argued in June
before a special panel of Appeals Court Judge Douglas Ginsburg and
District Court Judges Royce Lamberth and Ricardo Urbina -- two
Reagan appointees and one Clinton appointee.
</P>
<P>
The unusual combination of appellate and district judges was
created to put the lawsuit by one branch of government against
another on the fast track to the Supreme Court by removing the
intermediate step of review by a federal appeals court.
</P>
<P>
At the Justice Department, spokeswoman Chris Watney said
lawyers have 10 days to decide whether to appeal.
</P>
<P>
House Speaker Newt Gingrich, R-Ga., argued during debate in
Congress earlier this month that Americans should not have to
"rely on politicians controlling pollsters to invent virtual
people to get a grossly inaccurate count on behalf of some
political party." 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
