<HEADLINE> Chernomyrdin Outlines Government Priorities </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
MOSCOW, August 25 (Xinhua) -- Russian Acting Prime Minister
Viktor Chernomyrdin has set as top priority for the Russian
government the removal of the negative influence of the world
financial crisis on the economy of Russia.
</P>
<P>
In an interview published by the newspaper, Komsomolskaya
Pravda, on Tuesday, Chernomyrdin said the government would take
measures to prevent the world financial crisis from affecting the
country's economy and people's lives.
</P>
<P>
Illustrating his plans, Chernomyrdin emphasized two priorities,
the protection of social interests and the payment of wages and
pensions. Another was the drawing up of a state industrial policy.
</P>
<P>
In his opinion, monetary measures could not overcome Russia's
hardship.
</P>
<P>
Appraising the work of the previous cabinet, the acting prime
minister said he very much appreciated its measures to obtain
income tax by different approaches.
</P>
<P>
Responding to a question about the future line-up of his
government, Chernomyrdin said: "The Kiriyenko government included
fine professionals, some of whom worked with me. Those who want to
work, and, the main thing, can work, will stay on."
</P>
<P>
He said he was ready to hold consultations with "anyone who had
any sound ideas".
</P>
<P>
Chernomyrdin was appointed as the acting prime minister of
Russia by Russian President Boris Yeltsin, who sacked the entire
cabinet led by Sergei Kiriyenko on Sunday. 
</P>
</TEXT>
