<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Doctors Helping People Recover Sight In Tibet </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
LHASA, August 25 (Xinhua) -- Chinese doctors implanted an
artificial lens onto the left eye of a Tibetan farmer at Lhasa's
People's Hospital this afternoon and the patient is expected to
recover his eyesight gradually, according to the doctor who did
the operation.
</P>
<P>
"I feel very happy when I think that I will be able to see
things tomorrow," the Tibetan patient, whose name is Aqiong, said.
</P>
<P>
Aqiong, who lives on the outskirts of Lhasa, the capital of the
Tibet Autonomous Region, was the first person to benefit from a
sight recovery program sponsored by the China Disabled Persons'
Federation and Lion's Club International.
</P>
<P>
The program, "China Sight First Operation", is the largest
program of its kind in China and some 1,000 Tibetan cataract
sufferers are expected to benefit from the operations they will
receive free of charge.
</P>
<P>
Tibet is reported to have the largest number of cataract
sufferers in the world because of the intensity of its sunlight at
that altitude.
</P>
<P>
The doctors will also go to 3 other Tibetan towns, according to
Wang Chengquan, vice president of the federation and head of the
medical team. 
</P>
</TEXT>
