<HEADLINE> Thousands Ordered to Evacuate Before "Bonnie" </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
WASHINGTON, August 25 (Xinhua) -- About 200,000 residents and
visitors were ordered to evacuate North Carolina's low-lying Outer
Banks Tuesday as Hurricane Bonnie churned towards the East Coast
of the United States, the Associated Press reported Tuesday
morning.
</P>
<P>
The National Weather Service forecast that Bonnie's center will
be near the Outer Banks by Wednesday afternoon. By mid-morning
Tuesday, the storm's eye was centered about 720 kilometers south
of Cape Hatteras, North Carolina.
</P>
<P>
Even when the storm was still hundreds of kilometers away,
three meter waves were already reported on the North Carolina
beach. Surf hit the New Jersey shore in breakers one to two meters
high.
</P>
<P>
Hurricane warnings were posted from the south edge of the
coastal areas in South Carolina to the North Carolina-Virginia
state line, telling local residents that dangerous winds and heavy
rain could hit the area within 24 hours. Hurricane watches
extended south to Savannah, Georgia, and north to Cape Henlopen,
Delaware.
</P>
<P>
Before the hurricane warnings were posted for North Carolina,
South Carolina Governor David Beasley had already told 1,000 of
his state's National Guardsmen to get ready. Officials estimated
there were 125,000 tourists in the state's beach towns.
</P>
<P>
People along the East Coast were buying emergency
supplies. Plywood, batteries and gas cans were hot items at Bame
Ace Hardware in Carolina Beach, North Carolina. 
</P>
</TEXT>
