<HEADLINE> Dhaka Urges India to Stop Deporting "Indian Citizens" </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
DHAKA, August 25 (Xinhua) -- Bangladesh on Tuesday formally
requested India to stop pushing Bengali-speaking "Indian citizens"
into Bangladesh in the interest of the two countries, the official
new agency BSS reported.
</P>
<P>
The news agency quoted "a competent source" of the Foreign
Ministry as saying that India made a series of attempts in the
last eight days to push what India called "illegal Bangladeshi
nationals" into the country.
</P>
<P>
"The government of India has been requested to take necessary
action to stop such attempts of pushing Indian citizens into
Bangladeshi territory in the mutual interest of both the
governments," the source said.
</P>
<P>
Indian High Commissioner to Bangladesh Deb Mukharji was
summoned to the Foreign Ministry Tuesday afternoon and conveyed of
the message.
</P>
<P>
Foreign Secretary Mustafizur Rahman, while delivering the
message to Mukharji, said the Bangladeshi government feels that
the attempts to push "Indian citizens" into Bangladesh are "likely
to affect the excellent relations so happily existing between the
two countries."
</P>
<P>
He said India's Border Security Forces (BSF) began to push
"Indian citizens" into Bangladeshi territory at least through four
points since early last week.
</P>
<P>
He said the Foreign Ministry has got information that a group
of 60-70 people had been kept at a temporary camp near the border.
</P>
<P>
Foreign Minister Abdus Samad Azad, when contacted by the news
agency, reiterated Prime Minister Sheikh Hasina's assertion that
"no Bangladeshi nationals are staying illegally in India."
</P>
<P>
"We want to continue the present excellent relations with
India," he said.
</P>
<P>
"We have succeeded in resolving many outstanding issues with
India in the spirit of cooperation and understanding," he said,
adding that the two sides should avoid issues that might create
misunderstanding. 
</P>
</TEXT>
