<DATE_TIME> 1998-08-25 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Chinese Companies Become Main Supplier for Boeing Aircraft </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
XIAMEN, August 25 (Xinhua) -- The Boeing Company has some 8,500
aircraft flying all over the world, but few people know that about
3,000 of those aircraft have parts that were built in China.
</P>
<P>
Since the 1980s, Chinese manufacturers have produced thousands
of parts for Boeing aircraft, and assembled 35 McDonnell Douglas
MD-80s, according to Raymond Bracy, president of Boeing China.
</P>
<P>
Bracy told a seminar on the Boeing 717, the company's newest
family member, in Xiamen in Fujian Province that this shows that
China is not only Boeing's largest market outside the United
States, but also its main supplier.
</P>
<P>
Boeing is the world's largest manufacturer of passenger
planes. In 1997, it produced 374 aircraft. Its annual sales
amounts to 27 billion U.S. dollars.
</P>
<P>
Since 1972, China has bought about 300 Boeing aircraft,
accounting for 72 percent of the country's plane imports. In 1985,
China began to assemble MD-80s and to manufacture major parts. In
1992, China signed an agreement with McDonnell Douglas, which
merged with Boeing last year, to assemble 20 MD-90s in the cities
of Shanghai, Chengdu, Shenyang and Xi'an.
</P>
<P>
The first Chinese-assembled MD-90 is scheduled to be put into
use by November this year, according to Mr. Bracy. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
