<DATE_TIME> 1998-08-25 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Effort To Contain Floodwaters Continues (1) </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
BEIJING, August 25 (Xinhua) -- The 7th flood crest of the
Yangtze River is moving towards Yichang in central China's Hubei
Province, while the 3rd flood crest of the Songhua River in
northeast China reached the city of Jiamusi in Heilongjiang
Province today.
</P>
<P>
A State Flood Control Headquarters official says that they can
not give up in the fight against the floods, with water levels
still very high and a new flood crest on the Yangtze, and the
danger of embankments that have been water-logged for nearly two
months.
</P>
<P>
The flood season will end in October if weather conditions are
normal, the official told a press conference of the State
Council's Information Office today, and that the Yangtze will
remain high for about 20 days and the Nen and Songhua rivers will
take two weeks to recede -- if there are no torrential rains on
the upper reaches.
</P>
<P>
On August 23, the water level at Jiamusi was up more than 30
centimeters. It is now 80.27 meters, 1.27 meters above the danger
level. At Yichang it is 53.28 m., at Shashi, 44.32 m., and at
Jianli 37.6 m. at 10 a.m. today. These were up 0.79 m., 0.44 m.,
and 0.07 m. from yesterday.
</P>
<P>
The 7th flood crest of the Yangtze formed at 4 p.m. Sunday in
Chongqing, where the water level at the Cuntan measuring point was
183.21 meters and the flow rate 58,000 cubic meters per
second. This was 1.1 meters higher and 3,100 cubic meters more
than the previous flood crest.
</P>
<P>
The new peak could cause more difficulties downstream, but
water levels on the middle and lower reaches are not very likely
to break records.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
