<DATE_TIME> 1998-08-25 14:40 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Russia Not An Advocate for Iraq: Ambassador </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
KUWAIT CITY, August 25 (Xinhua) -- Although Moscow supports an
early lifting of the eight-year-old U.N. sanctions on Iraq,
Russian Ambassador to Kuwait Vladimir Shishov has said "Russia is
not an advocate for Iraq."
</P>
<P>
Speaking in an interview with the Arabic daily Al-Qabas
published here Tuesday, Shishov said Moscow and Washington share
views with regard to Iraq, adding a united stance is always
interpreted into the voting process in the U.N. Security Council
at the end of every discussion over Iraq.
</P>
<P>
The Russian ambassador said Moscow is also committed to all
U.N. Security Council resolutions concerning Iraq's 1990 invasion
of Kuwait.
</P>
<P>
He said Russia denounced Iraq's invasion and took part in all
activities exerted to remove the traits of the aggression, and
action is still going on to push Iraq to carry out all Security
Council resolutions.
</P>
<P>
Asked how to prevent Iraq from threatening its neighboring
countries when the U.N. sanctions imposed on Baghdad are lifted,
the Russian ambassador said a follow-up regime would be
established, adding that lifting the embargo "does not mean the
United Nations would leave Iraq do whatever easily, as some
believes."
</P>
<P>
Russia strongly supports an early lifting of the sanctions
which were imposed after Iraq's invasion of Kuwait. Russia has
suffered a loss of at least 10 billion U.S. dollars due to the
block of trade and economic activities with Iraq.
</P>
<P>
Shishov said Russia is committed to Kuwait's security,
stability and territorial safety. "This is Russia's stance in
principle that was reflected in the signing of a defense
agreement" in November 1993 with a term of 10 years, he added.
</P>
<P>
During the interview, Shishov also underlined the "extremely
special" relations, historic ties and cooperation between Russia
and Kuwait. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
