<TEXT>
<P>
The death toll and losses are still being figured,
Vice-minister of Water Resources Zhou Wenzhi said, and it takes
time to get accurate figures. China's summer floods had claimed
more than 2,000 lives by August 6.
</P>
<P>
He said that the collapse of dykes in Jiayu County in Hubei had
claimed the lives of 44 people by August 23.
</P>
<P>
Flooding on the Yangtze since this summer had caused more than
38.4 billion yuan (4.6 billion U.S. dollars) in losses to Hubei by
the 20th of this month, according to Yang Yongliang,
Deputy-secretary of the Hubei Provincial Communist Party Committee.
</P>
<P>
The floods have been the worst since 1954 and have affected
4.47 million people, damaged 2.54 million ha. of cropland, and
forced 9,769 enterprises to suspend or reduce production.
</P>
<P>
In Heilongjiang, the Nen and Songhua rivers caused 17.81
billion yuan in losses, according to Ma Shujie, deputy-governor of
the province.
</P>
<P>
The flooding affected 622 towns and townships and 52 cities and
counties, more than 8.5 million people, nearly a quarter of the
population of the province. It destroyed 750,000 houses, caused
2.16 million people to be evacuated, covered 3.12 million hectares
of farmland, and disrupted service on more than 2,480 kilometers
of highways and a number of railway sections. The flooding also
affected 1,342 oil wells in the Daqing Oilfield, causing 447 to
stop.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
