<HEADLINE> African Ministers in Angola on Congo (K) Crisis </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
LUANDA, August 25 (Xinhua) -- South African foreign and
defense ministers as well as envoys sent by Gabonese and
Congolese (B) presidents arrived here Tuesday to coordinate their
stands with the Angolan government on the situation in the
Democratic Republic of Congo (DRC).
</P>
<P>
South African Foreign Minister Alfred Nzo and Defense Minister
Joe Modise arrived here Tuesday morning. They are followed by
Jean Ping, the Gabonese Minister of Planning, Environment and
Tourism, Congolese Foreign Minister Adolf Adada and Defense
Minister Pierre Oba, who are envoys of their respective
presidents, the Angolan Foreign Ministry revealed..
</P>
<P>
Diplomatic sources here believed that ministers are here to
coordinate their positions on the DRC crisis in view of the
current differences among the Southern African Development
Community (SADC) countries in terms of military interference and
political and diplomatic resolution.
</P>
<P>
A SADC mini-summit was held over the weekend in Pretoria, the
economic capital of South Africa in the absence of presidents of
Angola, Zimbabwe and the DRC.
</P>
<P>
The meeting called and presided by South African President
Nelson Mandela concluded with a joint communique, calling on a
ceasefire between the warring sides in the DRC.
</P>
<P>
Angolan government issued a declaration Monday night to
support military assistance to the Laurent Kabila government.
</P>
<P>
Angola firmly supports the repulse of rebels by the Kabila
government and has reportedly sent a 1,000-strong army with tanks
and fighter planes to the DRC. Last Friday, the army helped
Kabila snatch back Kitona, a strategic air force base in
southwest of the DRC.
</P>
<P>
U.S. President Bill Clinton sent a special envoy to Angola
last Saturday and made it clear that only through political and
diplomatic means could the crisis in the DRC be settled. He also
asked all foreign countries to move out of the vast central
African country. 
</P>
</TEXT>
