the Taliban about Saudi dissident Osama bin Laden and issues
relating to international terrorist threats.
</P>
<P>
The spokesman, Richard Hoagland, quoting sources from the State
Department, said Washington has urged the Taliban to honor the
internationally recognized norms on terrorism including the need
to restrain Laden.
</P>
<P>
The U.S. has also urged the Taliban militia to restrain Laden
from using Afghan territory for alleged terrorist activities.
</P>
<P>
"The U.S. has urged the Taliban militia to honor
internationally recognized norms on human rights, narcotics and
terrorism including the need to restrain bin Laden from using
Afghan territory to plan, organize and launch terrorist attacks,"
Hoagland was quoted by the Associated Press of Pakistan as saying.
</P>
<P>
The U.S., he said, is of course interested in talking with the
Taliban about Laden and other international terrorist threats.
</P>
<P>
"We have long had contact with the Taliban, with other Afghan
factions and with other prominent Afghans who are not affiliated
with any faction," he said.
</P>
<P>
Hoagland said that Washington has also called upon the Taliban
to protect the rights of all Afghans including women and girls.
