<HEADLINE> Russia, Vietnam Agree on Cooperation </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
The two countries advocate, in the statement, the construction
of a new and more perfect world in political, economic and legal
respects.
</P>
<P>
The statement also praised the role played by the Treaty on the
Fundamentals of Friendly Relations between Russia and Vietnam,
signed between the two countries on June 16, 1994.
</P>
<P>
The document notes that the presidents of both countries
agreed to strengthen the mutual contact mechanisms between their
heads of state, government and foreign ministers.
</P>
<P>
The two presidents believed, said the statement, that there
were possibilities for a considerable increase in the trade volume
between the two countries.
</P>
<P>
They favored cooperation in the power industry and in other
fields, including the construction of the Shonla hydropower and
other hydropower or fueled power plants in Vietnam.
</P>
<P>
Both countries also voiced support for their military technical
cooperation, which the two presidents said, "is not directed to
against a third country and does not undermine the regional
balance of forces."
</P>
<P>
In addition to the joint statement, the two countries signed,
in the presence of the two presidents, a treaty on legal
assistance and legal relations in civil and criminal affairs.
</P>
<P>
The two governments also reached an agreement on setting up and
jointly running an oil refinery on Vietnamese territory.
</P>
<P>
Several other documents are expected to be signed on Tuesday,
including agreements on cooperation between the two countries'
justice ministries and on cooperation in narcotics control,
reports said. 
</P>
