<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Russian Ruble Slumps 10 Percent </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
MOSCOW, August 25 (Xinhua) -- The Russian ruble's exchange rate
dropped an alarming 10 percent Tuesday on the Moscow Interbank
Currency Exchange (MICEX), to 7.86 rubles against the U.S. dollar.
</P>
<P>
This was the steepest drop since October 11, 1994, the
so-called Black Tuesday, when the dollar moved up 27.43 percent,
from 3,081 old rubles to 3,926 old rubles.
</P>
<P>
So far, the ruble has shed 24 percent since last Monday, when
the former government and central bank raised the ceiling of the
ruble's exchange corridor from 6.3 to 9.5 rubles to the dollar.
</P>
<P>
The steep rise in the dollar prompted the MICEX to suspend
trading twice.
</P>
<P>
Traders believe that the central bank on Tuesday launched a
serious intervention at the end of the trading session on the
MICEX, and plugged almost all unsatisfied demand for dollars, the
Interfax news agency reported.
</P>
<P>
The agency quoted a source with the central bank that the great
demand for the dollar had been fueled by Russian banks eager to
change their rubles into dollars.
</P>
<P>
The source expressed concern that the banks were using central
bank loans, intended for them to maintain current solvency, to
purchase foreign currency.
</P>
<P>
"We can't help being worried by the fact that banks are
spurring the market virtually at the expense of Central Bank
resources, instead of channeling the finances they receive to the
fulfillment of their obligations to clients," he said. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
