<DOCNO> XIE19980825.0092 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1998-08-25 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Nigeria to Hold Presidential Election on February </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
LAGOS, August 25 (Xinhua) -- Nigeria will hold its
presidential election on February 27, 1999 to usher in an elected
civilian government, the Independent Electoral Commission (INEC)
announced Tuesday.
</P>
<P>
Addressing a news conference in capital Abuja, INEC chairman
Ephraim Akpata said elections to the National assembly would take
place on February 20.
</P>
<P>
Elections of state governors and legislators will be held on
January 9, Akpata said, quoted by the official News Agency of
Nigeria.
</P>
<P>
The INEC also released the guidelines for the registration of
political parties, which require all political associations to
first contest the local government council elections scheduled
for December 5, 1998.
</P>
<P>
Only those that score 10 percent of votes cast in at lease 24
of the country's 36 states will be registered as political
parties, the INEC said.
</P>
<P>
According to the new transition to civil rule program
announced by the Nigerian Head of State General Abdulsalam
Abubakar, the military will withdraw to barracks on May 29, 1999,
when the newly-elected civilian president assumes office.
</P>
<P>
Abubakar, who came to power on June 9 following the sudden
death of late military leader General Sani Abacha, announced his
own transition program in a national broadcasting on July 20.
</P>
<P>
He scrapped all the political parties as well as the electoral
commission of the Abacha time on the ground that the transition
program has lost its credibility and acceptability due to massive
rigging.
</P>
<P>
Abubakar's new policy, including dialog with the opposition
and the release of political detainees has won him the trust of
many people both at home and abroad, particularly in the West,
which have had a strained relations with the Abacha government.
</P>
<P>
South Africa, Nigeria's powerful rival on the continent which
has been critical of the Abacha military government, is currently
hosting a three-day official visit by Abubakar, the first
Nigerian leader ever to do so.
</P>
<P>
Scores of new political associations have emerged in Nigeria
in the last one month. In a recent meeting of the INEC, the
associations have refused registration by the government as it
was done in the Abacha time.
</P>
<P>
Nigeria, Africa's most populous nation, has been under
military rule for most of its time since its independence in
1960.
</P>
<P>
All the military rulers had announced their transition to
civil rule programs, but only General Olusegun Obasanjo actually
handed over to a civilian government in 1979.
</P>
<P>
Nigeria's latest transition experience started in 1985, after
General Ibrahim Babangida took over power in a coup.
</P>
<P>
His transition ended in a national disaster when he annulled
the June 1993 presidential election, in which Moshood Abiola, a
businessman from the south, was believed to have won.
</P>
<P>
When General Abacha took the power in 1993 from the interim
government led by Earnest Shonekan, he kept to tradition by
announcing his own transition program, which was expected to
usher in an elected civilian government in October this year.
</P>
<P>
But as God would have it, he died a sudden death of heart
attack in June, after he was chosen the sole presidential
candidate by all the five political parties registered by him.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> XIE19980825.0093 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1998-08-25 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> S. Korea Bolsters Security of Foreign Embassies </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
SEOUL, August 25 (Xinhua) -- South Korean police have stepped
up their alert on potential terrorist actions against United
States and other foreign missions here, after the bombings of
U.S. embassies in Kenya and Tanzania early this month.
</P>
<P>
The National Police Administration (NPA) Tuesday said it held
an emergency meeting with the U.S. embassy here to map out
anti-terror steps immediately after the terrorist attacks on the
two East African countries.
</P>
<P>
Police had strengthened the guards on foreign missions here,
including the U.S. Embassy, consul and information service, said
the police administration.
</P>
<P>
The administration had also ordered its stations to strengthen
their patrolling of foreign business firms in their areas of
jurisdiction.
</P>
<P>
On August 8, two bombs blew up at the two U.S. embassies,
killing more than 250 people, including 12 U.S. citizens.
</P>
<P>
Retaliating 13 days after the bombings, U.S. forces launched
cruise missile strikes against alleged terrorist camps in
Afghanistan and a chemical plant in Sudan.
</P>
<P>
United States President Bill Clinton vowed to lead an all-out
fight against terrorism, even as threats of retaliation were made
for U.S. missile attacks in Afghanistan and Sudan. 
</P>
</TEXT>
