<DOCNO> XIE19980825.0094 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1998-08-25 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> South Pacific States Agree on Whale Sanctuary Plan </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
CANBERRA, August 25 (Xinhua) -- A last-minute Japanese-inspired
bid to scuttle support for a whale sanctuary in the South Pacific
was Tuesday rejected by Australia, New Zealand and 14 South
Pacific island nations.
</P>
<P>
As a joint Australia-New Zealand initiative, the sanctuary was
backed at the two-day annual summit meeting of the South Pacific
Forum, which concluded Tuesday in the Federated States of
Micronesia (FSM), despite a proposal by Palau which would have
allowed Japan to veto the plan, the Australian Associated Press
(AAP) reported.
</P>
<P>
The forum groups Australia, New Zealand and 14 South Pacific
island states, including Cook Islands, FSM, Fiji, Kiribati, Nauru,
Niue, Palau, Papua New Guinea (PNG), Marshall Islands, Samoa,
Solomon Islands, Tonga, Tuvalu and Vanuatu.
</P>
<P>
The prime ministers from Australia, New Zealand, PNG, Solomon
Islands and Samoa were absent from the meeting because of domestic
politics or illness.
</P>
<P>
Palau's move shocked the forum delegates who had expected no
opposition to a ban on commercial whaling in the South Pacific.
</P>
<P>
Palau has no history of commercial whaling, and many blamed its
surprise intervention on its close ties with Japan, the biggest
aid donor to the island nation, the AAP said.
</P>
<P>
Palau wanted the forum's support for the sanctuary to be
subject to a veto by outside nations including Japan, who are
dialogue partners with the forum.
</P>
<P>
Japan is one of the few countries still practicing whaling and
if accepted, such a move would have meant an automatic veto of the
forum's backing for a whale sanctuary.
</P>
<P>
However, Australian Foreign Minister Alexander Downer said it
was totally unacceptable for the forum members to be handing
control of their affairs to outside countries.
</P>
<P>
A communique released Tuesday by the forum urged developed
nations to stick to their targets for reducing greenhouse gases as
global warming poses threat to many island nations. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
