<DATE_TIME> 1998-08-25 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Chinese Corruption Cases Through July </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
BEIJING, August 25 (Xinhua) -- China's anti-corruption drive
this year has resulted in 67,842 cases of corruption and
dereliction of duty from January to July, according to Han Zhubin,
the procurator-general of the Supreme People's Procuratorate.
</P>
<P>
Procurators have investigated 24,131 cases and opened legal
proceedings in 11,852, Han told a conference of provincial
prosecutors here today.
</P>
<P>
There were 7,743 cases each involving more than 50,000 yuan
(6,000 U.S. dollars) or more, and 618 that were major cases of
dereliction of duty, and 1,126 officials at or above the
county-head level involved.
</P>
<P>
Han said that the anti-corruption fight will continue in
accordance with President Jiang Zemin's directives, and prosecutor
offices have been told to be more diligent in dealing with
smuggling cases because of China's fight against these crimes.
</P>
<P>
Some government employees are involved in smuggling, he said,
or in letting smugglers go free or even sheltering them, and this
is a crime of dereliction of duty and corruption.
</P>
<P>
He said that prosecutors need to focus on corruption among
government employees and important officials in the following ways:
</P>
<P>
-- government officials and judicial officers seeking personal
gain by ignoring the law;
</P>
<P>
-- employees of finance, taxation and foreign currency
management offices breaking rules and causing losses to the state;
</P>
<P>
-- officials abusing their power to steal state property; and
</P>
<P>
-- misappropriation, diversion, or theft of disaster relief
funds and materials or dereliction of duty in the fight against
flooding.  
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
