<HEADLINE> European Bank's Profit Will Rise 10 Percent </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
GENEVA, August 25 (Xinhua) -- Europe's biggest bank, UBS,
forecast Tuesday that its after-tax profit in 1998 would be around
10 percent higher than the consolidated 1997 result of 4.8 billion
Swiss francs (about 3.2 billion U.S. dollars).
</P>
<P>
The bank said its net profit in the first half of 1998 rose
five percent to 3.02 billion Swiss francs (about 2.01 billion
U.S. dollars), but it expected financial results to slow in the
second half.
</P>
<P>
The total assets of UBS, a merger of the Union Bank of
Switzerland and Swiss Bank Corp., was 1.084 trillion francs at the
end of June.
</P>
<P>
"UBS is maintaining the targets it announced in December 1997,"
said the bank.
</P>
<P>
"By the year 2002 it expects a net profit after tax of 10
billion to 11 billion francs, a return on equity of 20 percent and
a cost-to-income ratio of around 60 percent." 
</P>
