<HEADLINE> Lebanese Guerilla Killed in Israeli Air Raids </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
BEIRUT, August 25 (Xinhua) -- A Lebanese guerrilla was killed in
south Lebanon on Tuesday by the Israeli air raids, the National
Broadcast Network radio reported.
</P>
<P>
Hossam al Amin, an officer of the Shiite Muslim Amal movement
led by the country's House Speaker Nabih Berri, was killed when
his car was hit by the missile fired by the Israeli warplane in
the Jezzine area, north of the Israeli occupied south Lebanon.
</P>
<P>
At the same time, five Lebanese civilians, including a boy,
were also wounded by the Israeli air raids which covered the
villages of Mashgara, Ain al Tinin and Suhmur in the area.
</P>
<P>
The air assault brought to 26 the number of guerrillas killed
in south Lebanon so far this year. Some 15 Lebanese civilians were
killed during the same period.
</P>
<P>
Besides the Iranian-backed Hezbollah, or Party of God, Amal is
the country's another active group to fight against Israeli
occupation of south Lebanon.
</P>
<P>
Israel carved out a 1,200-square-kilometer self-declared
security zone in south Lebanon in 1985 to protect its north from
cross-border attack by Lebanese guerrillas. 
</P>
