<BODY>
<HEADLINE> S. Korea to Further Streamline Military </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
SEOUL, August 25 (Xinhua) -- South Korea's First and Third
Field armies will be merged and reduced in size for a ground
operations command next year, the Defense Ministry announced
Tuesday.
</P>
<P>
The Third Field Army is now stationed in Seoul and its
surrounding Kyonggi Province, while the First Field Army is
deployed in adjacent Kangwon Province.
</P>
<P>
The Second Field Army will also be disbanded and elements
restructured, with the two army corps under its command to be
de-activated.
</P>
<P>
The ministry said that under the reforms a total of 12,000
soldiers, 25 generals ranking from one to four stars, and 565
field-grade officers would be retired in the coming years. South
Korea has 655,000 troops now.
</P>
<P>
Some mechanized divisions will be scaled down to brigade-level
units while brigades of the Special Warfare Command will be
reorganized for effective war preparedness.
</P>
<P>
Under the reform formula, the defense ministry and the joint
chiefs of staff will also be streamlined with offices of similar
functions merged or closed down. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
