<HEADLINE> Russia, Vietnam Move to Bolster Cooperation </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
MOSCOW, August 25 (Xinhua) -- Vietnam has agreed to intensify
cooperation with Russia in power and other industries in a bid to
bolster ties with Moscow.
</P>
<P>
The agreement was announced in a joint statement Tuesday by
Russian President Boris Yeltsin and visiting Vietnamese President
Tram Duc Luong, the Itar-Tass news agency reported.
</P>
<P>
The two presidents believed bilateral cooperation would enhance
major joint projects in prospecting for and in production of oil
and gas.
</P>
<P>
They favor cooperation in the power industry, including the
construction of the Shonla hydropower station in Vietnam, and in
the engineering, chemical, iron and steel, light industries and
food industries.
</P>
<P>
The two presidents also agreed to strengthen the mechanism of
high-level exchanges of visits by the heads of state, heads of
government and the foreign ministers.
</P>
<P>
The two sides voiced support for the development
military-technical cooperation, which they said "is not directed
against third countries and does not undermine the regional
balance of forces."
</P>
<P>
They also praised the role played by the Treaty on the
Fundamentals of Friendly Relations between Russia and Vietnam, of
June 16, 1994.
</P>
<P>
At the same time, the Treaty between Russia and Vietnam on
legal assistance and legal relations in civil and criminal affairs
was also signed.
</P>
<P>
The two governments also reached an agreement on cooperation in
the construction and running of an oil refinery in Vietnamese
territory.
</P>
<P>
Several other documents are also expected to be signed on
Tuesday, including an agreement on cooperation between Russian and
Vietnamese justice ministries, and an agreement on cooperation in
control over narcotics and psychotropic substances. 
</P>
</TEXT>
