<DATE_TIME> 1998-08-25 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Delegates Exchange Views on Rehabilitation for Disabled </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
HONG KONG, August 25 (Xinhua) -- Delegates to the 11th
Rehabilitation International Asia and the Pacific Regional
Conference exchanged views and experience on further improving
the rehabilitation work for the people with disabilities here
Tuesday.
</P>
<P>
This is the third day meeting since the conference cum
Campaign'98 for the Asian and Pacific Decade of Disabled Persons
1993-2002 was opened on Sunday.
</P>
<P>
Now there are about 300 million people with disabilities in
this region. The Economic and Social Commission for Asia and the
Pacific (ESCAP) will focus its contribution on the training of
people with disabilities in social mobilization of eliminating
barriers to disabled persons' participation in society.
</P>
<P>
During Tuesday's meeting, Yasuhiro Oyama, president of the
Japan Association of Employers of the Severely Disabled, put
forward a suggestion to make good use of the workplace of private
companies for vocational training in order to achieve better
results in the system of vocational rehabilitation.
</P>
<P>
This will "make it possible for persons with severe
disabilities to live and work in their community, as aimed at by
the international community," he said.
</P>
<P>
Arturo A. Borjal, a representative from the Philippines, urged
the media of the country to conduct a strong lobby for causes
affecting persons with disabilities after briefing the
participants on its specific laws and provisions in general laws
directly or indirectly focused on the welfare of persons with
disabilities.
</P>
<P>
Zhuo Dahong, a representative from China, told the meeting
about the measures that the country has taken in carrying out the
projects of disability prevention.
</P>
<P>
Major tasks of the projects include the reduction of the
incidence of hereditary disabilities and congenital defects,
control of infectious diseases, severe malnutrition and cerebral
vascular diseases, reduction of incidence of drug-induced deafness
and incidence of iodine deficiency and endemic fluorosis and
prevention of disabling injuries caused by traffic and worksite
accidents, Zhuo said.
</P>
<P>
According to an estimation in 1996, the number of people with
disabilities in the Chinese mainland was 60 million.
</P>
<P>
Zhuo said that in the next decade, at least 30 million people
can be saved from disability through preventive action.
</P>
<P>
Leonie Exel, executive officer of the National Employment and
Psychological Services Center of Australia, gave an overview of
the Australian disability employment sector; its political
influences, structure, funding sources, lobbying mechanisms,
target clients and challenges.
</P>
<P>
Delegates from some other countries including the United States
 as well as the Hong Kong Special Administrative Region also
delivered speeches at Tuesday's meeting. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
