<HEADLINE> Middle East Economic Briefs </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
CAIRO, August 25 (Xinhua) -- The following are economic briefs
from Middle East countries.
</P>
<P>
DAMASCUS -- Syrian exporting companies have welcomed a recent
decision taken by President Hafez Assad on the accession to the
Customs Accord for International Truck Transport.
</P>
<P>
By entering the accord, which was signed in 1975 in Geneva,
Syrian vehicles will be provided with registers by the guarantor
authority "which is the liaison between the U.N. international
land transport organization and local authorities," Arabic daily
Al Hayat reported Tuesday.
</P>
<P>
Trucks carrying the registers will be immunized from paying
duties or import-export taxes when entering or crossing the member
states of the accord.
</P>
<P>
RIYADH -- The Gulf Cooperation Council (GCC) signed a technical
assistance agreement with the Islamic Development Bank Sunday to
help a survey over shrimp in regional waters of the GCC member
states.
</P>
<P>
The Arabic daily Al Hayat reported Tuesday, the survey, to be
carried out by Gulf experts, is aimed at examining the shrimp
reserves, define the optimum management, train local research
workers on data gathering and analysis.
</P>
<P>
AMMAN -- Civil aviation officials of Jordan and Egypt will meet
here next month to discuss the opening of regular flights between
the two countries' major tourism sites, Jordan's official PETRA
news agency reported Tuesday.
</P>
<P>
Both sides are keen to open daily flight between Jordan's Red
Sea port city of Aqaba and Egypt's tourist attractions of Sharm Al
Sheikh and Hurgoda, and four flights each week between Aqaba and
Cairo to boost tourism and encourage business travel, the agency
said. 
</P>
</TEXT>
