<HEADLINE> China's Insurance Business Reforms </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
BEIJING, August 25 (Xinhua) -- China plans to reform its
insurance business by ending the People's Insurance Company of
China's monopoly of more than 40 years, according to Outlook
Weekly.
</P>
<P>
The PICC (group), which was established three years ago, will
be disbanded and its three subsidiaries in life insurance, property
insurance and reinsurance are expected to be independent, and
China will establish a state insurance regulatory commission.
</P>
<P>
China will also develop a policy-oriented agriculture insurance
company.
</P>
<P>
Premiums in China amount to 108.7 billion yuan and have a
year-on-year increase of 40 percent, much higher than the growth
of the GNP. According to the World Bank, the figure is expected to
reach 240 billion yuan by the end of this century.
</P>
<P>
China agrees with the World Bank that commercial insurance can
be an important part of a social security system and will make
individual security a common thing.
</P>
<P>
With the grain distribution reforms and the increase in
farmers' incomes, Chinese farmers have come to accept insurance
and life insurance companies are expected to pay more attention on
the rural market, where 80 percent of China's people live. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
