<HEADLINE> Australian Stocks Boosted by Overseas Markets </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
CANBERRA, August 25 (Xinhua) -- The Australian share market
partially rebounded from Monday's 33-point loss, with stronger
overseas markets inspiring the bourse Tuesday.
</P>
<P>
The benchmark all ordinaries index finished 25.9 points or one
percent higher at 2627.7, off its intra-day peak of 2632.4.
</P>
<P>
In New York overnight, the Dow Jones Industrial Average index
picked up 32.96 points to 8,566.61, overcoming concerns for the
Russian and Latin American markets.
</P>
<P>
And Japan's Nikkei 225 index ended 84.57 points stronger at
15,072.93 on futures-led buying coupled with modest
bargain-hunting.
</P>
<P>
"Hong Kong rebounded four percent after our market had closed,"
Shaw Stockbroking's Jamie Spiteri said.
</P>
<P>
"Then all overseas markets were better overnight, albeit not
significantly in some areas," he said.
</P>
<P>
The all industrials index gained 48 points to 4644.4 and the
all resources index climbed 7.7 to 995.6.
</P>
<P>
Media heavyweight News Corp slipped one cent, its preferred
scrip eased 1.3, publisher Rural Press surged 22 after signing an
agreement to buy Kerry Stokes' Canberra Times newspaper.
</P>
<P>
Retailer Woolworths ended three cents better, Coles Myer
improved six, Coca-Cola Amatil forfeited two cents.
</P>
<P>
BHP climbed 11 cents, Rio Tinto added 47, MIM edged up one
cent.
</P>
<P>
The gold index slipped 3.9 points to 960.6, as the spot price
for bullion was selling in Sydney 20 cents softer at 284.00 U.S.
dollars per ounce.
</P>
<P>
Three of Australia's big four banks closed up, pushing the
industry index to a close of 5843.6, up 59.1 points.
</P>
<P>
National turnover was 220.49 million shares valued at 764.09
million Australian dollars (443.17 million U.S. dollars), with
rises just outpacing falls by 487 to 484 and 401 stocks were
steady. 
</P>
