<DATE_TIME> 1998-08-25 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Philippine Senate May Not Approve VFA This Year </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
MANILA, August 25 (Xinhua) -- The Philippine Senate has not
included the approval of the proposed Visiting Forces Agreement
(VFA) with the United States in its 1998 legislative agenda,
Senate majority leader Franklin Drilon said here Tuesday.
</P>
<P>
He said that despite the urgency attached to the agreement by
both the Philipppine and the U.S. governments, the VFA does not
figure in the Senate legislative program for this year.
</P>
<P>
The Senate, Drilon said, has committed itself to passing four
of 79 priority measures submitted by the Presidential Palace
before the end of this year.
</P>
<P>
The four bills are the 1999 budget proposal, amendments to the
General Banking Act, amendments to the Retail Trade Law and an act
empowering local governments in the administration and operation
of the Philippine National Police.
</P>
<P>
Drilon said the Senate sees no connection between the VFA and
the Philippine economy and dismissed speculations that delayed
approval of the agreement will have adverse economic and security
effects on the country.
</P>
<P>
He added that the VFA has to be similarly ratified by the U.S.
Congress for it to be constitutionally valid and binding.
</P>
<P>
On the same day, Senate President Marcelo Fernan also said that
the four priority measures are considered "very urgent" and the
VFA, by implication, does not figure in such urgency.
</P>
<P>
The Philippine and the U.S. governments are urging the
Philippine senate to ratify the VFA as soon as possible to pave
the way for joint military exercises between the two countries.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
