<HEADLINE> EU Finances New Energy Projects </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
BRUSSELS, August 25 (Xinhua) -- A total of 236 energy-related
projects will get funding from the European Commission, commission
officials said on Tuesday.
</P>
<P>
The commission fund, amounting to 110.5 million ECU (121.55
million U.S. dollars), will finance 116 energy technology
demonstration projects and 120 associated measures.
</P>
<P>
The commission, the executive body of the 15-nation European
Union, is supporting these projects with an aim of developing new
technologies and applications in the rational use of energy,
renewable energy sources and fossil fuels, so as to meet the
challenges originated from the constant growth in global energy
demand.
</P>
<P>
European Commissioner Christos Papoutsis, who is responsible
for energy policy, said: "In view of the 21st century, we need to
define an integrated approach to technological development,
covering the research, development, promotion and wider market
deployment of new energy technologies.
</P>
<P>
"This approach needs to be one which works hand-in-hand with
various market factors in industry, finance and the public sector,
and which responds to the real needs of the consumer."
</P>
<P>
Under the JOULE-THERMIE program that provides support for
research and development of non-nuclear energy technologies, the
commission is supporting two types of energy projects --
demonstration projects and associated measures.
</P>
<P>
The associated measures are aimed at the promotion of new
energy technologies, overcoming barriers and obstacles to market
penetration and the dissemination of information on the benefits
of new energies. 
</P>
</TEXT>
