<DOCNO> XIE19980825.0125 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1998-08-25 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> 10 Percent Tree Species on edge of Extinction </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
GENEVA, August 26 (Xinhua) -- Three international organizations
warned on Tuesday that 10 percent of the world's known tree
species are facing extinction.
</P>
<P>
The World Conservation Monitoring Center (WCMC), the World
Conservation Union (IUCN) and the World Wide Fund for Nature (WWF)
said more than 8,750 of the 80,000 to 100,000 tree species known
were found to be threatened with extinction
</P>
<P>
The three organizations are launching the World List of
Threatened Trees, a report compiled by the WCMC, for a United
Nations Intergovernmental Forum on Forests.
</P>
<P>
The forum, which aims to tackle the crisis facing the world's
forests, began on August 24 in Geneva and will last 10 days.
</P>
<P>
The threats to tree species include overuse of timber as fuel
and as a construction material, the uncontrolled expansion of
human settlements and agriculture, widespread forest fires,
invasive alien species and unsustainable forest management, said a
report of the forum.
</P>
<P>
Trees, as an intrinsic part of the world's ecosystem, provide
such valuable services to mankind as climate control, water
catchment, medicine, food and timber.
</P>
<P>
The majority of the Earth's animal species depends upon the
survivability of trees. Tropical forests are home to about 90
percent of the world's terrestrial species.
</P>
<P>
The World List of Threatened Trees advocates urgent actions by
the international community in sustainable forest management,
restoration of forest habitats and control of alien invasive
species.It also calls for such supplementary measures as the
establishment of botanic gardens, arboreta and seed banks. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> XIE19980825.0126 </DOCNO>
