<HEADLINE> Australian Dollar Hit by Heavy Selling </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
CANBERRA, August 25 (Xinhua) -- The Australian dollar was
knocked to a new 12-year low when the currency was hit by heavy
selling at European markets Tuesday morning.
</P>
<P>
The local dollar had been holding up around the 58-U.S.-cent
foothold for most of Tuesday before trading in London got
underway.
</P>
<P>
The wave of selling there took the Australian dollar to its
lowest level since July 1986 at 57.63 U.S. cents, surpassing
Monday's fall to 57.79 U.S. cents.
</P>
<P>
The Australian dollar was trading at 57.68 U.S. cents, from
58.01 U.S. cents, and edging closer to its post-float low of 57.10
U.S. cents.
</P>
<P>
The late fall follows a stressful local trading session with
offshore investment banks keeping up the pressure up on the unit,
preventing it from breaking away from its 58.00-U.S.-cent
foothold.
</P>
<P>
The crises in Asia and Russia have resulted in a bearish
outlook for the local currency and market participants responded
by continuing the selling.
</P>
<P>
Dealers said that whenever the local currency looked to rise
above the 58.00-U.S.-cent mark, U.S. investment banks were on hand
to sell off large orders.
</P>
<P>
Speaking at a superannuation briefing in Sydney Tuesday, former
Reserve Bank of Australia (RBA) governor Bernie Fraser shied away
from commenting on the falling Australian dollar.
</P>
<P>
Asked whether the RBA should intervene to support the
Australian dollar, Faser replied that what was evident at present
was that the current volatility should be looked at on a longer
term, not short term view.
</P>
<P>
The Australian dollar closed trading here at 83.71 yen, from
83.42 yen and 1.0426 German marks from 1.0449 marks. 
</P>
</TEXT>
