<DATE_TIME> 1998-08-25 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Thai Cabinet Approves Fifth Letter of Intent to IMF </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
BANGKOK, August 25 (Xinhua) -- The Thai cabinet Tuesday
approved the latest quarterly economic review, better known as the
fifth letter of intent to the International Monetary Fund (IMF),
which forecasts that the economy will contract 7 percent in 1998.
</P>
<P>
The letter predicted that Thailand's economic downturn will
stabilize by year-end, with slight growth in 1999.
</P>
<P>
"A supportive regional environment will be important to this
respect," a press release regarding the letter issued by the
Finance Ministry Tuesday said.
</P>
<P>
The review will be sent to the IMF board for final approval
early next month before Thailand withdraws an additional 494
million U.S. dollars from the IMF's 17.2-billion-dollar rescue
package.
</P>
<P>
Under the fifth letter of intent, the 1999 fiscal budget, which
begins October, will have a deficit target of 3 percent of gross
domestic product (GDP), the same as the 1998 budget.
</P>
<P>
This will include a central budget of 1 percent of GDP, with
the remainder from state enterprises.
</P>
<P>
The budget deficit target excludes the 1.5 percent of GDP
budgeted for financial restructuring costs, including domestic
bond issues and other costs from the reform package announced on
August 14.
</P>
<P>
On monetary policy, the release said money market interest
rates have already declined substantially from 20 percent earlier
this year to a 10-12 percent range. The government expects that
banks' lending rates should fall further and liquidity conditions
improve.
</P>
<P>
The international reserves are expected to remain within the
26-28 billion dollar range by the end of this year.
</P>
<P>
Reflecting the deeper recession, the government expects
inflation to decline to 9.2 percent and the external current
account surplus be higher to 10 percent of GDP.
</P>
<P>
Thai government and IMF officials have agreed to revise
policies on financial and corporate debt restructuring, social
security and market opening.
</P>
<P>
Finance Minister Tarrin Nimmanhaeminda said Tuesday that the
economic downturn is worse than it was expected three months ago,
which is mainly due to the unfavorable external environment.
</P>
<P>
Domestic purchasing power and investments in Thailand also
recorded significant falls, he added. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> XIE19980825.0134 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1998-08-25 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> India's Auto Registers recession </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
NEW DELHI, August 25 (Xinhua) -- Recession has hit India's
automobile industry with car sales plummeting by over 50 percent
between April-July this year, according to the latest figures of
the Association of Indian Automobile Manufacturers (AIAM) here
Tuesday.
</P>
<P>
Sales of luxury carmakers General Motors, Mahindra Ford and Pal
Peugeot plummeted over 55 percent during the first four months
this year against the same period last year.
</P>
<P>
The heavy commercial segment's sales nose-dived by over 45
percent with market leader Telco alone suffering a massive
negative 49 percent growth. Multi-utility vehicles plunged by
about 19 percent and passenger cars recorded a negative growth of
over three percent during the first four months this year.
</P>
<P>
Economic slowdown in the country has been the main cause of
recession in the automobile industry. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
