<HEADLINE> Israeli, Palestinian Youths Hold Peace Rally </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
JERUSALEM, August 25 (Xinhua) -- A total of 1,750 Israeli and
Arab teenagers on Tuesday gathered at the Israeli-Jordanian border
to mark the fifth anniversary of the historical Oslo Accords.
</P>
<P>
Israel Radio said some 1,500 teenagers came from the youth wing
of Israeli United Kibbutz Movement (UKM), which organized the
event.
</P>
<P>
And the other 250 youngsters came from Jordan, Gaza Strip and
South Lebanon.
</P>
<P>
A statement issued by the UKM said that the rally was to mark
the mutual recognition agreement between Israel and the Palestine
Liberation Organization signed in September 1993.
</P>
<P>
It said the aim of the gathering was to express support to the
Israeli-Palestinian peace talks, which have been deadlocked for 17
months.
</P>
<P>
Tuesday's peace rally was held in the Naharayim boder area
despite Israel Education Ministry's order forbidding the
participation of school pupils for reasons of security.
</P>
<P>
In March last year, seven Israeli schoolgirls were killed
by a Jordanian soldier during a school outing in the area.
</P>
<P>
Yoel Marshak, head of UKM's youth and settlement section, said
that there would be proper security arrangements provided by
Israeli and Jordanian border troops.
</P>
<P>
He also noted that " peace is our best security belt and it is
also our future, and it is the desire of our youth." 
</P>
