<DATE_TIME> 1998-08-25 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> China Disciplining, Firing Public Prosecutors </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
BEIJING, August 25 (Xinhua) -- In an unprecedented shake-up of
China's procutorial offices, 756 prosecutors were disciplined in
accordance with government and Party rules and thousands fired by
the end of July.
</P>
<P>
The announcement was made by the Procurator-General of the
Supreme People's Procuratorate Han Zhubin at a national meeting
of provincial procurators here today.
</P>
<P>
During the process, 1,255 cases that had been mis-handled were
re-examined by prosecutors. An "educational rectification
movement" was begun during the central government's new term in
March in response to criticism by members of the top legislature,
the National People's Congress (NPC).
</P>
<P>
NPC members were invited to explain their dissatisfaction with
prosecutors and comment on their work and notoriously illegal
practices were halted to keep practices in accordance with the
law.
</P>
<P>
The judiciary have checked up on 1,337 prosecutors suspected of
being involved in illegal activities in their official duties and
legal proceedings were opened against 73 of them.
</P>
<P>
Wrongful verdicts were re-examined in about 500,000 cases that
have been repeatedly appealed, causing debates among the public.
</P>
<P>
Prosecutor's offices were also examined for prolonged detention
of suspects, 675 people were released in accordance with the law.
</P>
<P>
The illegal practices are still hard to deal with, but they
relate to whether the confidence of the public can be won, Han
said. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
