<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Experts Meet to Discuss Crime Prevention </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
SEOUL, August 25 (Xinhua) -- More than 1,000 criminology
experts from 70 countries began meeting here Tuesday to discuss
crime prevention and new criminal policies.
</P>
<P>
The 12th International Congress on Criminology (ICC), co-hosted
by the Korean Institute of Criminology and the International
Society of Criminology, is the first of its kind held in an Asian
country and will last six days.
</P>
<P>
The participants presented more than 500 papers and began
debates on issues such as anti-corruption policies, correctional
treatment, juvenile delinquency, organized crime, computer and
credit card fraud and school violence.
</P>
<P>
Five plenary sessions are under way with a focus on crime
causes and prevention in the 21st century.
</P>
<P>
The sessions will deal with subjects ranging from sociological
studies to empirical criminology methods and crime policy.
</P>
<P>
In addition, dozens of round-table sessions will be held for
free discussion among participants with interest in similar
fields, while special addresses are to be given by 12 renowned
scholars.
</P>
<P>
The ICC conference has been held every five years since its
inaugural meeting in Rome in 1938. 
</P>
</TEXT>
