<DATE_TIME> 1998-08-25 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Nigeria Government Earns More From Gas Flaring </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
LAGOS, August 25 (Xinhua) -- The Nigerian government made
about 58.64 billion Naira (about 689.9 million U.S. Dollars) in
the first quarter of this year from gas flaring penalty.
</P>
<P>
A major national newspaper This Day Tuesday quoted figures
from the Central Bank of Nigeria and the recently scrapped
Ministry of Petroleum Resources as saying that the figure is 270
percent up from that of the same period in 1997.
</P>
<P>
The drastic rise is attributed to the increase of the penalty
from 50 Kobo (0.006 Dollars) to 10 Naira (0.12 Dollars) per 1,000
standard cubic feet of gas flared, starting from the beginning of
the year.
</P>
<P>
Nigeria, the top African oil producer, is rich in natural gas
resources estimated between 110 and 350 trillion cubic feet.
</P>
<P>
It was estimated that Nigeria's oil fields are currently
producing 2.2 billion cubic feet of natural gas a day, but 75
percent of them are flared into the air, incurring a loss of
several millions of Dollars.
</P>
<P>
To encourage the utilization of the resources, the Nigerian
government raised the penalty for each 1,000 cubic feet flared
from two Kobo in the 1970s to 50 Kobo in 1996, further to 10
Naira in 1998.
</P>
<P>
The government also provides various incentives for investment
into gas utilization. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
