<HEADLINE> Australian Expert Warns of Terrorism on Internet </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
CANBERRA, August 25 (Xinhua) -- Terrorism on the Internet was
increasing at an alarming rate and threatening businesses and
governments around the world, an Australian computer expert warned
Tuesday.
</P>
<P>
Organizations should review their security to protect
themselves against cyber-terrorist attacks, Deakin University
computing expert Matthew Warren said in an interview in Melbourne
with the Australian Associated Press.
</P>
<P>
He said many organizations were at present so preoccupied with
the millennium bug that they had become lax on computer security.
</P>
<P>
"Terrorist groups have difficulty in relaying their political
messages to the general public without being censored and they can
now use the Internet for this purpose," he said.
</P>
<P>
He said some groups were even using the Internet for
fund-raising purposes, adding it was now possible to make a direct
donation to a certain group by using your credit card.
</P>
<P>
Terrorist groups could also use other methods such as E-mail
bombs where thousands of E-mails are sent to a particular computer
system until that system crashed, he said.
</P>
<P>
Most companies were preoccupied with the millennium bug and
viruses and were too relaxed in their attitude toward computer
security, leaving themselves open to Internet terrorism, he said.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> XIE19980825.0150 </DOCNO>
