<HEADLINE> Malaysia Willing to Pay High Rates on Foreign Loans </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
KUALA LUMPUR, August 25 (Xinhua) -- Malaysian Prime Minister
Mahathir Mohamad said Tuesday his government is willing to pay
high interest rates on foreign loans in efforts to revive the
national economy.
</P>
<P>
"We guarantee that we will repay our loans and even pre-pay
them," the Malaysian leader said at a meet-the-people gathering
in Shah Alam near here.
</P>
<P>
However, he said his government would not force foreigners to
lend money to the country if they were not confident.
</P>
<P>
Malaysia would toil on its own to set the economy on the
recovery path, Mahathir said, adding "our country is our
responsibility."
</P>
<P>
Mahathir said some foreigners still felt that the economic
turmoil in Malaysia was because of the government's inefficiencies
like what had happened in Indonesia, Thailand and South Korea.
</P>
<P>
He said the real culprits were the speculators who depressed
currencies and share prices.
</P>
<P>
Mahathir said the Kuala Lumpur Stock Exchange has lost some 600
billion ringgit (about 142.517 billion U.S. dollars) in market
value to only 300 billion ringgit (about 71.258 billion U.S.
dollars) at present.
</P>
<P>
He said Malaysia could still manage the economy and if it had
not managed the economy well, the country would have sought IMF
(International Monetary Fund) aid a long time ago.
</P>
<P>
"We are still free. This shows that the government knows how to
manage the country," he said, adding that Malaysians must believe
in the capability of the government in managing the economy.
</P>
<P>
He said that sooner or later, Malaysia would see the end of the
economic turbulence and the country has to sacrifice a little but
this is not as much as the sacrifices made by the people in
countries which had sought IMF aid. 
</P>
