<HEADLINE> Bus Accident Aftermath Properly Handled in Gansu Province </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
LANZHOU, August 25 (Xinhua) -- The provincial government of
Gansu in northwest China is making every effort in dealing with
the aftermath of a bus accident last weekend which killed six
tourists from Taiwan and injured others.
</P>
<P>
According to local sources, the injured are receiving
first-class medical treatment at Jiuquan Hospital and the hospital
attached to the Jiuquan Iron and Steel Company. They were
transferred to those hospitals hours after receiving emergency
care at a hospital near Jiuquan County where the accident occurred.
</P>
<P>
The seriously injured include a Taiwan woman who is being
treated by specialists from Lanzhou, the provincial capital. She
is said to be out of danger now.
</P>
<P>
The accident took place at 4:30 p.m. on August 22 when a
tourist bus carrying 17 people, 14 of them from Taiwan,
collided head-on with a truck. The bus driver and five of the
Taiwan tourists were killed instantly and another Taiwan resident
died later.
</P>
<P>
The Beijing-based Association for Relations Across the Taiwan
Strait has sent a senior official to Gansu to help handle the
aftermath.
</P>
<P>
The remains of the dead have been carefully kept and made ready
for possible transport to Taiwan, and the local government has
made proper arrangements for relatives of the victims who are
expected to come to Gansu, according to local sources. 
</P>
</TEXT>
