<HEADLINE> Angola Supports SADC Move on Congo (K) </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
LUANDA, August 25 (Xinhua) -- Angolan government has announced
to join the Southern African Development Community (SADC) efforts
in supporting the Democratic Republic of Congo (DRC) President
Laurent Kabila.
</P>
<P>
This is a political solution to the crisis now facing the
central African country, according to a brief statement by the
Angolan government issued Monday night.
</P>
<P>
Angola supports the move proposed by SADC security and defense
organ led by Zimbabwean President Robert Mugabe, which asked SADC
members to offer military assistance to Kabila's government to
repel armed rebellion.
</P>
<P>
The move is in line with the effort for peace and stability in
the DRC, said the statement which did not mention whether Angola
has sent army to the DRC to help Kabila's government.
</P>
<P>
The Banyamulungue soldiers in the DRC started rebellion on
August 2 against Kabila. And the fighting has since spread to
the east and southwest of the country.
</P>
<P>
The Kabila government has accused Rwanda and Uganda of backing
the rebels which was denied by the two countries.
</P>
<P>
However, foreign media reports said earlier that Angola has
sent a 1,000-strong army with tanks and fighter planes to the DRC
which helped the Kabila army snatch back the Kitona air force
base 20 kms away from the mouth of the Congo river last Saturday.
</P>
