<DATE_TIME> 1998-08-25 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> hke082554 -Malaysian Opposition Leader Jailed After Losing Appeal </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
KUALA LUMPUR, August 25 (Xinhua) -- Malaysia's opposition
Democratic Action Party (DAP) Deputy Secretary-General Lim Guan
Eng was sent to prison Tuesday after his appeal against his
18-month jail sentence on charges of publishing false news and
sedition was dismissed by the Federal Court.
</P>
<P>
The Federal Court Tuesday upheld the 18-month jail sentence
passed by the Court of Appeal on Lim Guan Eng who is also a member
of Parliament.
</P>
<P>
When announcing the decision, Chief Justice Mohammed Eusoff
Chin said, "We find that the Court of Appeal had considered
thoroughly the principles of sentencing, and had given the reasons
for interfering with the sentence passed by the trial judge. We
find no good reason why we should interfere with the Court of
Appeal's decision that the appellant should stand convicted of the
two charges."
</P>
<P>
Eusoff said the Federal Court had given "anxious consideration"
to the submission of Lim's counsel, Karpal Singh, that an
imprisonment sentence of not less than one year would disqualify
Lim from being an MP.
</P>
<P>
He said an MP should always act in a responsible manner and, in
particular, should not break the law because he was likely to face
charges in court and leave his constituency without a
representative in Parliament.
</P>
<P>
"When such a situation happens, the people should not put the
blame on the police, the attorney-general or the court because the
blame lies entirely on the Member of Parliament who breaks the
law," Eusoff said.
</P>
<P>
Eusoff also said that a written judgment would be given in due
course.
</P>
<P>
Lim Guan Eng, 38, looked calm when the verdict was announced
and hugged his family members after the court adjourned. Present
were his father, Lim Kit Siang, who is the opposition leader in
Parliament and DAP Secretary-General, his mother and his wife.
</P>
<P>
Lim was fined 15,000 ringgit (about 3,562 U.S. dollars) by the
Malacca High Court on April 28 last year for maliciously printing
false news and uttering seditious words under the Printing Presses
and Publications Act 1984 and the Sedition Act 1984.
</P>
<P>
The Court of Appeal dismissed Lim's appeal on April 1 this year
and upheld an 18-month jail sentence on each offense with the
sentences to run concurrently. 
</P>
</TEXT>
