<HEADLINE> More Relief Supplies Ensure Flood Victims' Daily Lives </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
BEIJING, August 25 (Xinhua) -- A senior official with the
Ministry of Civil Affairs said today that the flood situation
still remains China's major concern, and more donations and relief
materials continue to be sent to flood victims.
</P>
<P>
Fan Baojun, vice-minister of Civil Affairs, said at a news
conference held by the Information Office of the State Council
this afternoon that the central government has repeatedly asked
local officials to take greater care of homeless people, as top
leaders themselves went to the flooded areas to direct flood
control.
</P>
<P>
So far, the central government has allocated 3.029 billion yuan
(366 million U.S. dollars) and distributed huge amounts of relief
materials, Fan said, and more than 100 work teams have also been
sent to flood-ravaged regions.
</P>
<P>
East China's Jiangxi Province has been one of the hardest-hit
regions, and the provincial government has provided more than 100
million yuan in disaster relief funds and distributed 100,000 tons of
grain, 1.87 million items of clothing, quilts and blankets,
100,000 tons of fuel and 21,000 tons of fiber and nylon cloth.
</P>
<P>
To prevent epidemic outbreaks, central China's Hubei Province
has sent nearly 1,245 medical teams with 5,783 people to provide
check-ups and distribute medicine valued at 3.48 million yuan.
</P>
<P>
Northeast China has also suffered the worst flooding since the
founding of new China in 1949. Heilongjiang Province has used 100
million yuan in flood control and disaster relief funds, and Jilin
Province has distributed 8,500 tons of instant food, 258,000
quilts and clothing items, and 2,700 cases of medicine.
</P>
<P>
The two provinces have helped more than one million flood
victims resettle in safe places, said Fan, adding that heavy
flooding has drawn great concern both at home and abroad.
</P>
<P>
To date, China has received 1.746 billion yuan in donations
including relief materials, and the Ministry of Civil Affairs has
allocated 824 million yuan to flood-stricken areas.
</P>
<P>
He said the Ministry of Civil Affairs had issued three
emergency circulars urging that donations be handled openly,
fairly, and in an orderly fashion to ensure that money and goods
get to the the people they are intended for.  
</P>
</TEXT>
