<HEADLINE> Netanyahu Vows to Expand Settlements in Hebron </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
JERUSALEM, August 25 (Xinhua) -- During a condolence call to
the family of a slain settler in Hebron, Israeli Prime Minister
Benjamin Netanyahu vowed Tuesday to build more housing for the
settlers in this flashpoint West Bank city.
</P>
<P>
Due to security reasons, Netanyahu's visit to the family of
late Rabbi Shlomo Ra'anan was previously unannounced.
</P>
<P>
Ra'anan was stabbed to death by a Palestinian perpetrator at
his home in the Tel Rumeida neighborhood Thursday night, prompting
setter leaders' call on the government to expand the existing
settlements in retaliation.
</P>
<P>
"The new housing construction plan will be finalized soon," he
said.
</P>
<P>
He told the family members of Ra'anan that he had nothing to
say about the peace process, but would insist that the Palestinian
side take measures to fight terrorism.
</P>
<P>
Before Netanyahu, Israeli President Ezer Weizman and Defense
Minister Yitzhak Mordechai had already visited the divided city,
where 450 Jewish settlers living among 12,000 Palestinians, to
express condolences to Ra'anan's family.
</P>
<P>
During their visits, Mordechai was blamed by Jewish settlers
for not providing proper security to the settlers, and Weizman
accused of being a "spy" of Israel's enemies.
</P>
<P>
Netanyahu's visit to Hebron showed that he is doing everything
he could to appease the right-wing Jewish settlers, who helped
sweep him to power in the 1996 elections.
</P>
<P>
Seven Jewish families are living in caravans at Tel Rumeida,
which is surrounded by Palestinian residents. Israeli security
forces have found it difficult to protect the safety of these
settlers.
</P>
<P>
Hebron is the only West Bank city where there remains a Jewish
presence. Under the January 1997 agreement, Israel hand over 80
percent of the city to the Palestinian control but has been
retaining control over the rest of the city, where 450 Jewish
settlers are living in isolated neighborhoods. 
</P>
</TEXT>
