<HEADLINE> NZ to Film Trilogy Based on "Lord Of The Rings" </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
WELLINGTON, August 25 (Xinhua) -- New Zealand film director
Peter Jackson is to make a 264-million-New Zealand-dollar (133
million U.S. dollars) trilogy based on Tolkien's fantasy classic
"Lord of The Rings," the local TV station reported Tuesday
evening.
</P>
<P>
"The project is believed to be the biggest cinema production
ever undertaken in the southern hemisphere," the TV station said.
</P>
<P>
Jackson is one of the most famous film directors in New
Zealand, whose previous films include the Oscar-nominated Heavenly
Creatures and The Frighteners made in New Zealand with Hollywood
money.
</P>
<P>
It was reported that half of the filming for the trilogy will
be in Wellington and the cast will require 15,000 extras.
</P>
<P>
Casting will be done later this year and at least 50 of the 65
speaking roles in the cast, and almost all of the film crew will
be New Zealanders.
</P>
<P>
The principal photography would take about a year, with 18
months set aside for post-production.
</P>
<P>
The first film of the trilogy, "The Fellowship of The Ring," is
due to be released at Christmas time in 2000. The sequels, "The
Two Towers" and "The Return oF The King," would be released either
four or six months apart. 
</P>
</TEXT>
