<HEADLINE> Aqsa Mosque Closed to Visitors Due to Protest </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
JERUSALEM, August 25 (Xinhua) -- The Muslim holy shrine Aqsa
Mosque in East Jerusalem was closed to visitors Tuesday morning
because of a protest against the arrest of two Palestinian youths.
</P>
<P>
The two youths were arrested by Israeli police Tuesday morning
near the entrance to the Mosque, the third holiest Muslim shrine
in the world.
</P>
<P>
No reason was given by the Israeli police for the arrests.
</P>
<P>
After the news of the arrests spread, a large number of
Palestinian protesters gathered inside the Mosque to demonstrate
against the Israeli moves, forcing the officials of the Mosque to
close the Mosque to visitors.
</P>
<P>
Aqsa Mosque is jointly managed by Jordanian and Palestinian
religious personnel and tens of thousands of visitors visit it
everyday.
</P>
<P>
The Arab East Jerusalem was captured from Jordan by Israel in
the 1967 Mideast War, and Israel has since claimed its sovereign
control on the whole city.
</P>
<P>
Talks are going on between Aqsa Mosque officials and Israeli
Jerusalem police, but no agreement has been reported so far on
when the shrine would be reopened. 
</P>
</TEXT>
