<HEADLINE> Afghan Peace Could Only Be Achieved Through Peaceful </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
ISLAMABAD, August 25 (Xinhua) -- A durable peace in Afghanistan
"can only be achieved through an indigenous Afghan peace process
leading to the establishment of a multi-ethnic government."
</P>
<P>
The remarks were made Tuesday by Pakistani Foreign Minister
Sartaj Aziz in his first foreign policy statement presented at the
Senate.
</P>
<P>
Aziz said Pakistan's policy on Afghanistan is impelled by its
vital interest in the restoration of a durable peace in that
country.
</P>
<P>
Immediately after assuming his premiership in February last
year, Prime Minister Nawaz Sharif took new initiatives for the
promotion of peace in Afghanistan, he noted.
</P>
<P>
Sharif reached out to the Afghan leaders on both sides of the
political divide as a consequence of which, leaders of the Taliban
militia and the opposition Northern Alliance visited Islamabad,
said Aziz.
</P>
<P>
He noted that these efforts culminated in the meeting of a
Steering Committee early May to work out the modalities for an
Ulema (religious scholar) Commission to seek a solution to the
Afghan issue.
</P>
<P>
"This was a significant breakthrough which unfortunately was
derailed because of the intransigence of one of the component
parties of the Northern Alliance," the Foreign Minister said.
</P>
<P>
He said that Pakistan is also making efforts internationally to
promote a peaceful solution to the Afghan conflict which led to
the formation of the "Six plus Two" group comprising the six
countries with common borders with Afghanistan plus the U.S. and
Russia.
</P>
<P>
The group has been meeting regularly under U.N. auspices in New
York, Aziz said, adding Pakistan has also fully supported the U.N.
and the OIC (Organization of Islamic Conference) in their efforts
to promote peace in Afghanistan.
</P>
<P>
He said the dissension and discord within the Northern Alliance
not only derailed the peace process but weakened them to the
extent that some of their commanders defected from the Northern
Alliance and invited the Taliban to take over the territory.
</P>
<P>
The event of the past few weeks in Afghanistan show that the
Taliban have met with only minor resistance and most of the places
fell to them with little or no fighting, Aziz said. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
