<DOCNO> XIE19980825.0167 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1998-08-25 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Mozambique Loses $1M for Smuggled Sugar: Official </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
MAPUTO, August 25 (Xinhua) -- Mozambique has lost nearly one
million U.S. Dollars in revenue in five months due to the
smuggled sugar, according to an official with the Mozambican
National Association of Sugar.
</P>
<P>
Arnaldo Ribeiro, director of the association, Monday told the
third Coordination Council of the Ministry of Agriculture and
Fishery in Maputo that "from last November when additional
tariffs were imposed upon the imported sugar to the end of April
this year, Mozambique has lost nearly one million U.S. Dollars
due to sugar smuggling and overpriced invoices."
</P>
<P>
In five and a half months, more than 20,000 tons of sugar were
smuggled into Mozambique, Ribeiro said, adding that all of the
legitimate importers escaped additional tariffs through
overpricing in the invoices.
</P>
<P>
He pointed out that the illegal activities have forced the
sugar producers in Xinavane and Mafambisse to reduce the prices
of their products.
</P>
<P>
If the situation is sustained, Ribeiro noted that it will
endanger the investment of 220 million U.S. Dollars under way or
in pipeline and some 25,000 jobs, let alone the achievement of
the goals in the growth of sugar industry, the development of
rural areas and the increase of export.
</P>
<P>
The industry leader disclosed that in May this year his
association sent some administrators to the customs to help
monitor all legal importation of sugar, greatly pre-empting the
forgeries in the receipts.
</P>
<P>
However, Ribeiro also voiced his concern because the customs
in Mozambique cannot monitor and curb sugar smuggling because no
governmental measures were taken in the respect.
</P>
<P>
In order to curb sugar import, crack down on smuggling and
encourage domestic producers to resume and develop sugar
production, the Mozambican government imposed additional tariffs
upon imported sugar at the end of last year.
</P>
<P>
Approximately, 120,000 tons of sugar are consumed in
Mozambique per annum, the Noticias newspaper reported Tuesday.
</P>
<P>
It is expected that sugar output in the southern African
country will reach 32,000 tons this year. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
