<HEADLINE> Pak Continues to Accord Importance to Ties with Iran: FM </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
In his first policy statement since assuming his portfolio
early August, Aziz said Pakistan's relationship is based on common
historical, religious and cultural links.
</P>
<P>
Pakistan and Iran also have mutually beneficial cooperation in
trade, commercial and cultural fields, he said.
</P>
<P>
"Pakistan also appreciates Iran's position on the Kashmir
issue, and its offer of mediation which we have accepted but India
has rejected," the Foreign Minister added.
</P>
<P>
He said Pakistan's relations with Iran are marked by frequent
contacts at the leadership level. Prime Minister Nawaz Sharif has
already visited Iran twice during his current term of office, he
noted.
</P>
<P>
"It remains our constant endeavor to preserve the special
nature of the abiding and time-tested Pakistan-Iran ties and to
particularly guard against any negative fall-out on it of the
Afghan situation," the Foreign Minister said.
</P>
<P>
On the Pak-U.S. relations, Aziz said that the Pakistani
government is working with the U.S. for upholding human rights,
promoting privatization and a liberal market economy, and fighting
against drug trafficking and global terrorism.
</P>
<P>
"A common objective that Pakistan continues to share with the
U.S. is maintaining peace and stability in the region," Aziz said.
</P>
<P>
He said Pakistan is currently engaged in a bilateral dialogue
with the U.S. on security and non-proliferation issues in South
Asia.
</P>
<P>
"Pakistan has made it clear that on these critical issues
Pakistan's position would be dictated by its supreme national
interests and that under no circumstances would it be coerced into
compromising its position," Aziz stressed.
</P>
<P>
He also said Pakistan hopes that "the U.S. administration will
show an understanding of its eminently reasonable stance and play
a positive role in easing tension in South Asia."  
