<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Asian Elephant Home In Southwestern China (1) </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
KUNMING, August 25 (Xinhua) -- Pu Yunchang, 50, who used to be
a crack elephant hunter of the ethnic Jino people, is now head of
a model village for elephant protection in southwestern Yunnan
Province.
</P>
<P>
Pu's Baihua Village is situated at the fringe of a nature
reserve with 99,000-hectare of tropical forest in the
Xishuangbanna Prefecture of ethnic Dai group, home to endangered
animals including Asian elephants.
</P>
<P>
Pu said, "The forests are the last habitat of the wild
elephants, so our folks should become their good neighbors."
</P>
<P>
Pu and his villagers used to lived by hunting in the primitive
forests. But when the nature reserve was established, they moved
their village out of the reserve and handed their hunting rifles
over to the local government.
</P>
<P>
Experts say that with efforts from the villagers and local
governments, the number of wild elephants in Xishuangbanna has
increased to some 250 from 197 just 14 years ago.
</P>
<P>
Baihua Village and the adjacent areas are the haunt of about 50
wild elephants. During the harvest season, herds of elephants will
come by on the sly to eat the maize, soybeans and other grain
crops.
</P>
<P>
Some bold elephants even ramble into the village. Last fall, an
elephant slipped into the village at midnight, used its trunk to
steal the maize hanging under the eaves, and swaggered away until
it was finally stopped by the villagers.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> XIE19980825.0174 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1998-08-25 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Home to Asian Elephants in Southwest China's Xishuangbanna (2) </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
Wild elephants often come to drink in the river in front of the
village, fearless of the villagers who wash their clothes nearby.
</P>
<P>
Last August, a wounded elephant was found in the
river. Villagers looked after it and reported the matter to the
local government immediately. The elephant was saved under the
care of the villagers and medical staff.
</P>
<P>
The frequent elephant visits have added spice to village life,
but at the same time it can also be a big headache for the local
farmers during harvest season. Satistics show that elephants eat
more than 30,000 kg of grain from Baihua Village
annually. Although the government offered some compensations to
the farmers, Pu Yunchang, head of the village, said that it was
only an amount worth one-third of the losses.
</P>
<P>
Yan Zhuang, commissioner of the Xishuangbanna Prefecture, said
that the local government will increase the compensation this
year. He added that there are plans to move the villages back from
the fringe of the nature reserve backwards so that villagers and
elephants can co-exist in harmony.  
</P>
</TEXT>
