<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Official: No Major Epidemic Diseases in Flooded Areas </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
BEIJING, August 25 (Xinhua) -- A senior Health Ministry
official said today at a news conference that there is no
prevalence of major epidemic diseases in China's seven
flood-stricken provinces and one autonomous region.
</P>
<P>
Yin Dakui, vice-minister of health, said at a news conference
held by the Information Office of the State Council this afternoon
that the incidence of infectious diseases in the flooded areas has
maintained the same level as last year.
</P>
<P>
The official said that 22,728 medical teams and approximately
125,600 health workers have been sent to the flood-stricken areas
to offer their services in preventing and control epidemics.
Cooperating with the grass-roots health organizations, the medical
teams have provided timely treatment for people have been injured
or have fallen ill while fighting the floods.
</P>
<P>
The incidence of diseases spread by water or food poisoning
have been curbed in those areas, Yin said.
</P>
<P>
To prevent epidemic diseases, leading disaster relief and
disease prevention groups have been founded as part of the flood
control headquarters at various levels.
</P>
<P>
As millions of people have been surrounded by the floods or
become homeless, he noted, many of them are living in crowded
makeshift tents. The hot and humid weather in the south and
polluted drinking water have presented major problems for health
workers.
</P>
<P>
Colds, intestinal diseases and dermatitis have become common in
the flooded areas.
</P>
<P>
The vice-minister went on to say that central China's Hubei
Province has adopted effective measures to prevent snail fever
among the one million local residents and armymen.
</P>
<P>
President Jiang Zemin has urged local governments at various
levels and health departments to enhance disease prevention and
epidemic monitoring in the flooded areas.
</P>
<P>
Premier Zhu Rongji presided over a State Council meeting to
deploy the disease and epidemic-prevention units.
</P>
<P>
Central China's Hubei and Hunan, east China's Jiangxi, Anhui
and Jiangsu provinces, and northeast China's Heilongjiang and
Jilin provinces, as well as the Inner Mongolia Autonomous Region,
have been suffering from serious flooding since late June.
 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> XIE19980825.0178 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1998-08-25 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> China Maps Out Plan for Post-Flood Epidemic Control </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
BEIJING, August 25 (Xinhua) -- China has announced an overall
plan to prevent and control major epidemic diseases in the flood
stricken areas. The plan will be implemented as soon as the floods
recede.
</P>
<P>
Yin Dakui, vice-minister of health, said today at a news
conference held by the Information Office of the State Council
that sanitation workers will launch a large-scale "carpet"
cleaning and disinfection campaign in those areas where the floods
have receded and the flood victims formerly lived.
</P>
<P>
He said the resettlement areas, garbage disposal areas, and
other places which could most easily trigger an outbreak of
epidemic diseases will also be the focus of repetitive cleanings.
</P>
<P>
The vice-minister said that additional medical teams will be
sent in when the floods recede, and their duties will be disease
prevention and environmental cleansing aimed to eliminate
conditions which could lead to the spreading of epidemic and
infectious diseases.
</P>
<P>
He emphasised that health workers will also help flood victims
to choose their drinking-water sources and monitor its quality.
</P>
<P>
Meanwhile, health departments at various levels are also urged
to monitor the incidence of diseases and curb the spreading of
epidemics as soon as one case is reported.
</P>
<P>
The focus of disease prevention will be on villages, towns,
neighborhoods and households to ensure that each individual takes
preventative measures.
</P>
<P>
The vice-minister said he believes that so long as the leaders
and people in the flooded areas insist on this disease-prevention
campaign, China will see no outbreaks of major epidemic diseases
after the current flooding subsides.  
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
