<HEADLINE> British PM Set to Recall MPs over Omagh Explosion </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
LONDON, August 25 (Xinhua) -- British Prime Minister Tony Blair
is expected to use Tuesday's visit to Northern Ireland to announce
the emergency recall of parliament to push through anti-terrorist
legislation, The Daily Telegraph said on Tuesday.
</P>
<P>
The paper said that during his visit, Blair would outline tough
new security measures in hopes to bring the Omagh bombers to
justice.
</P>
<P>
The blast killed 28 people and injured 220 nine days ago, the
deadliest atrocity in 30 years of violence in Northern Ireland
between the rival Catholics and Protestants.
</P>
<P>
But parliament speaker Betty Boothroyd has the final say on
whether to reconvene the session. If she approves, the likely
dates for the recall will be on next Wednesday and Thursday.
</P>
<P>
It would be only the fourteenth time since World War II that
members of parliament have been brought back for an emergency
session.
</P>
<P>
One of the main planks of the new security package is a
proposal that terrorists could be convicted of membership of a
banned organization on the sworn testimony of a senior police
officer.
</P>
<P>
Irish Prime Minister Bertie Ahern has announced a series of
draconian anti-terrorist measures to crack down on terrorist acts
in the wake of the Omagh bombing.
</P>
<P>
Blair is also expected to meet Ahern on Wednesday for talks
over joint actions against terrorism and over the historic
Northern Ireland peace accord signed last April. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
