<HEADLINE> China to Use Grain Reserves to Control Prices if Necessary </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
BEIJING, August 25 (Xinhua) -- China will use grain reserves to
keep down grain prices in flooded areas when necessary, Zhao
Qizheng, director of the Information Office of the State Council,
said here today at a press conference.
</P>
<P>
"China has huge reserves of grain, which will not cause price
hikes," he said.
</P>
<P>
In the 1991 flooding, the United States, based on satellite
surveys, predicted that China's grain production would go down. As
a matter of fact, this didn't happen, because satellites couldn't
figure out the depths of floodwaters and the extent of flood
damage, nor the accurate grain output reduction.  
</P>
</TEXT>
