<HEADLINE> Heilongjiang Suffers Severely From Floods </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
BEIJING, August 25 (Xinhua) -- Floods of the Nenjiang and
Songhua rivers caused direct economic losses of 17.81 billion yuan
(2.15 billion US dollars) in northeast China's Heilongjiang
Province.
</P>
<P>
The floodings affected 622 towns and townships in 52 cities and
counties, involving more than 8.5 million people, nearly a quarter
of the total population of the province; some 750,000 houses were
collapsed; 2.16 million people were evacuated to safe places, Ma
Shujie, vice-governor of the province, told a press conference
held by the Information Office of the State Council this afternoon.
</P>
<P>
A total of 3.12 million hectares of farmland were inundated;
more than 2,480 kilometers of highways and 209 railway sections
were blocked, Ma said, adding that a total of 1,342 oil wells were
submerged in Daqing oilfield, the largest of its kind in China,
with 447 being closed. 
</P>
</TEXT>
