<DOCNO> XIE19980825.0200 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1998-08-25 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Yangtze River Flooding Causes Great Economic Losses </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
BEIJING, August 25 (Xinhua) -- Flooding of the Yangtze River
since early this summer had caused more than 38.4 billion yuan
(4.6 billion US dollars) in direct economic losses to central
China's Hubei Province by 20th of this month, an official source
said here this afternoon.
</P>
<P>
The flooding, the worst since 1954, has affected 4.47 million
residents, damaged 2.54 million ha of cropland, and forced 9,769
enterprises to suspend or reduce production, Yang Yongliang, deputy
Secretary of the Hubei Provincial Committee of the Communist Party
of China, said at a news briefing. Hubei has a population of 58.72
million.
</P>
<P>
The Yangtze River is more than 6,300 km long, the longest in
China. Its section that runs through Hubei is about 1,061-km
long.
</P>
<P>
Chinese President Jiang Zemin, Premier Zhu Rongji and several
other senior officials got, at different times, to the flooded
areas to direct the anti-flood effort.
</P>
<P>
Currently, more than 2.3 million people, including some 82,900
troops of the People's Liberation Army and the armed police, are
countering floods along the embankments of the Yangtze River.
</P>
<P>
Official statistics also show that the government at various
levels had, by August 20, issued 280 million yuan (33.7 million US
dollars) in relief funds and 47.3 million kg of relief grain to
flood victims in Hubei.
</P>
<P>
The flood-victims have been appropriately settled and their
basic living is effectively guaranteed, Yang said, adding that no
major epidemic diseases have been reported in the flooding areas.
</P>
<P>
Moreover, Yang told reporters, "the social order in the flooded
areas in stable and the people are calm,"
</P>
<P>
However, he said that the flood-control task remains gravely
arduous as the seventh flood crest of the Yangtze River, the most
ferocious this year, is expected to enter Hubei Province today.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> XIE19980825.0201 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1998-08-25 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Russian Soyuz TM-27 Returns to Earth </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
MOSCOW, August 25 (Xinhua) -- The Soyuz TM-27 spacecraft with
three Russian cosmonauts on board safely returned to the earth
after undocking from the orbiting station Mir on Tuesday.
</P>
<P>
The Itar-Tass news agency reported that the Soyuz TM-27 landed
near the Kazakh town of Arkalyk at 9.23 a.m. Moscow time (0623
GMT) on Tuesday morning.
</P>
<P>
All the cosmonauts felt well, said crew commander Talgat Musaba
after landing. "The landing spot is good, smooth, there is a swift
east wind blowing and the weather is fair," he added.
</P>
<P>
The Soyuz TM-27 headed for the earth following the successful
undocking from the orbiting station Mir at 6.05 a.m. (0605 GMT)
Tuesday morning.
</P>
<P>
Musabayev and Nikolai Budarin spent 207 days on board the
Mir station, while the former aid to the Russian president, Yuri
Baturin, spent 12 days in space.
</P>
<P>
Baturin carried out more than 20 experiments under his program
"visit mission," the results of which together with the results
of Russian and Kazakh programs were brought down to earth.
</P>
<P>
Crew commander Gennady Padalka and flight engineer Sergei
Avdeyev who will be on the Mir station till the end of February
1999, will also complete several dozens of experiments and will
make two spacewalks.
</P>
<P>
The report said that the main task of the crew is to maintain
Mir in a working condition till its destruction in June 1999.
</P>
<P>
The Soyuz TM-27 was blasted off from the Baikanur launching
pad together with Padalka and Avdeyev on August 13. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
