<HEADLINE> Turkey Welcomes Chernomyrdin's Reinstatement </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
ANKARA, August 25 (Xinhua) -- Turkey welcomes the
reappointment of Viktor Chernomyrdin as Russia's Prime Minister,
saying it would have positive impact on the Turkish-Russian ties,
the English-language newspaper Daily News reported Tuesday.
</P>
<P>
Senior officials of Turkish Foreign Ministry were quoted by the
paper as saying that the reinstatement of Chernomyrdin, a veteran
politician and ex-premier, was a positive development from
Turkey's point of view.
</P>
<P>
"For five years Chernomyrdin has been familiar with the
Turkish-Russian relations. He knows all the dimensions and
profound potentialities of the relations between the two
countries," said one official.
</P>
<P>
In a telephone interview with the paper, Turkish Ambassador in
Moscow Nabi Sensoy said that Chernomyrdin's return to the Russian
government was good news for Turkey.
</P>
<P>
Chernomyrdin became the prime minister in December 1992 and
was replaced by the 35-year-old Sergei Kiriyenko only five months
ago.
</P>
<P>
Kireyenko's ouster came one week after the Russian government
and the central bank raised the ceiling of the ruble's exchange
corridor from 6.3 to 9.5 rubles to the U.S. dollar, which
amounted to a devaluation of the national currency.
</P>
<P>
Turkish Foreign Ministry sources believed that the current
financial crisis in Russia, which is a major trade partner of
Turkey, would not have direct negative impact on the bilateral
political relations and the recently accelerated economic
cooperation. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
