<DATE_TIME> 1998-08-25 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> 7th Yangtze Flood Crest Taking Shape </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
BEIJING, August 25 (Xinhua) -- The 7th flood peak of the
Yangtze River has formed along the upper reaches and is expected
to pass Yichang in central China's Hubei Province tonight.
</P>
<P>
At the Cuntan Measuring Point in Chongqing Municipality in
southwest China, the water level reached 183.21 meters with a flow
rate of 58,000 cubic meters per second on Sunday at 16 pm, 1.1
meters higher and 3,100 cubic meters more than the previous flood
crest.
</P>
<P>
The new peak could bring more difficulties to flood-fighters in
downstream areas, an official of the State Flood Control and
Drought Relief Headquarters said here today at a related news
conference.
</P>
<P>
Water levels on sections of the Yangtze River between
Shashi-Luoshan and Wuxue-Jiujiang, at Dongting and Poyang lakes,
and on the Nenjiang and Songhua rivers are still raging above
all-time highs.
</P>
<P>
At present, more than 8 million civilians and soldiers are
working day and night to reinforce embankments in south and
northeast China, and some 5,000 danger spots have been dealt with.
</P>
<P>
"So far, we have achieved a great victory in anti-flood
control, and succeeded in minimizing losses," the official said,
adding that the Chinese people have the full confidence,
determination and power to win a complete victory over the
floods.  
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
