<DATE_TIME> 1998-08-25 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Boeing Hopes to Introduce New Aircraft to China </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
XIAMEN, August 25 (Xinhua) -- The Boeing company hopes that
China will accept its newly developed Boeing-717-200 passenger
aircraft, said Raymond Bracy, president of Boeing China Inc. here
today.
</P>
<P>
He told the "Boeing-717 China Conference" which opened here
today that this new model, which has been undergoing test flights,
will officially be put into operation in June, 1999.
</P>
<P>
According to Bracy, the Boeing company plans to sell China over
1,900 civil aircrafts worth over 120 billion U.S. dollars in the
next 20 years, making it the second largest Boeing market after
the United States.
</P>
<P>
Company representatives told Chinese aviation officials
attending the conference that the Boeing-717-200 is a 100-seater
equipped with the most advanced avionics technology and an engine
made by BMW/Rolls Royce. It features low noise and low
fuel-consumption.
</P>
<P>
The branch-line aircraft was previously the MD-95 model which
changed to its present name after the merger of the Boeing and
McDonnell Douglas companies.
</P>
<P>
A United State airline which has ordered 50 Boeing-717-200s is
expected to become the first to have the model.
</P>
<P>
Since 1972, Boeing has sold China about 300 Boeing aircraft of
seven series worth a total of 15 billion U.S. dollars. Over the
past three years, one in every ten Boeing planes has become part
of a Chinese airline.
</P>
<P>
According to estimates, China will need 2,000 new passenger
planes over the next twenty years with an annual growth rate of
9.5 percent.
</P>
<P>
Today's conference, sponsored by Boeing China Inc., focuses on
the development, function, and after-sale service of the new
model. 
</P>
</TEXT>
