<DOCNO> XIE19980825.0212 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1998-08-25 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Taiwan Authorities Should Demonstrate Sincerity With Action (1) </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
BEIJING, August 25 (Xinhua) -- Taiwan authorities should
demonstrate their sincerity for "seeking reunification of China"
with actual deeds, according to an official from the State
Council's Taiwan Affairs Office.
</P>
<P>
The official, speaking in today's exclusive interview with the
Xinhua News Agency, pointed out the Taiwan authorities continue to
lack sincerity in their pursuit of peaceful reunification. He
noted that recent speeches have vacillated between "the
reunification of China" and "an insistence on splittist
activities."
</P>
<P>
Taiwan authorities have advocated expanded cross-Straits
economic and cultural exchanges which would undoubtedly have a
positive effect, but have nonetheless used recent meetings as
forums to claim status as "an independent state" and attempt to
"explore expanded international living space" in an effort to
create "two Chinas" or "one China, one Taiwan."
</P>
<P>
Taiwan authorities recently demanded that some western nations,
especially the United States, increase arms sales to Taiwan in
order to ensure "the governments of Taiwan and the Chinese
mainland remain separate," and firmly rejected the "concept
of 'one country, two systems'" which has been successfully
implemented in Hong Kong.
</P>
<P>
The developing international situation and improving
cross-Straits relations have resulted in an increasing number of
Taiwan compatriots expressing their eagerness for a more friendly
and stable environment and hope for political negotiations between
the two sides at the earliest possible date.
</P>
<P>
The Chinese mainland has attempted to satisfy the common desire
of Taiwan compatriots by proposing initial discussions to outline
procedural arrangements for political negotiations, and subsequent
economic and practical negotiations between the Association for
Relations Across the Taiwan Straits (ARATS) and the Taiwan-based
Straits Exchange Foundation (SEF).
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> XIE19980825.0213 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1998-08-25 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Taiwan Authorities Should Demonstrate Sincerity With Action (2) </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
The recent reiteration Taiwan authorities made to "sign a
cross-Straits peace agreement through negotiations and end the
state of hostility" resulted from mounting internal and external
pressure and was ostensibly the premise for "negotiations."
</P>
<P>
However, the actual goal of the premise -- to "separate the
government of China on the existing basis" -- centers on defying
the "one China" principle and continuing to delay negotiations for
"ending cross-Straits hostilities."
</P>
<P>
The official said Taiwan authorities should exhibit their
sincerity by abandoning the "two Chinas" stand and removing
barriers hindering discussions concerning procedural arrangements
for political negotiations.
</P>
<P>
He said ARATS is seeking a common understanding based on
strengthening contacts with SEF, and is perfectly willing to
engage in political dialog with the latter so long as related
contacts will benefit the peaceful reunification of China and the
development of cross-Straits relations.
</P>
<P>
Leading officials from the State Council Taiwan Affairs Office
recently reiterated they welcome SEF Chairman Koo Chen-fu and his
delegation to visit the mainland in either mid-September or
mid-October. With the exception of those who stubbornly insist on
the "independence of Taiwan," the mainland side will be delighted
to exchange views with Taiwan residents from various parties and
all walks of life concerning cross-Straits relations and China's
peaceful reunification, according to the officials.
</P>
<P>
The ARATS official concluded the interview by noting that
Chinese people on both sides of the straits should join hands and
make new contributions to the cross-Straits relations and the
reunification of the motherland. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
