<HEADLINE> Yeltsin Asks Dismissed Cabinet Members to Work Further </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
MOSCOW, August 25 (Xinhua) -- Russian President Boris Yeltsin
signed a decree on Tuesday, asking members of the dismissed
cabinet to continue their work until a new Russian government is
formed.
</P>
<P>
The Itar-Tass news agency reported that under the decree deputy
prime ministers and federal ministers will continue performing
their duties until a new cabinet is formed.
</P>
<P>
Yeltsin dismissed ex-prime minister Sergei Kiriyenko and his
entire cabinet and named Viktor Chernomyrdin as acting prime
minister last Sunday, which brought a governmental crisis to the
country.
</P>
<P>
Kiriyenko had already turned down an offer by Yeltsin to be
the first deputy prime minister in the new cabinet.
</P>
<P>
Chernomyrdin made it clear on Monday that he won't form a new
Cabinet until the State Duma approves his nomination as prime
minister.
</P>
<P>
The State Duma declared that it will confirm the nomination of
Chernomyrdin as prime minister in 10 days instead of the seven
days stipulated by legislation. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
