<DATE_TIME> 1998-08-25 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> NZ Growth Strongly Linked With Asia: NZ Minister </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
WELLINGTON, August 25 (Xinhua) -- New Zealand Minister for
International Trade Lockwood Smith said here Tuesday evening that
New Zealand should not "turn its back on Asia" because of its
current economic crisis.
</P>
<P>
"New Zealand's growth and development will always be strongly
linked with Asia," he stressed.
</P>
<P>
He made the remarks when he was addressing the annual general
meeting of the Wellington Branch of New Zealand Institute of
International Affairs.
</P>
<P>
"No one in the New Zealand Government has ever underestimated
the seriousness of the turmoil in Asia. Asian economies account
for half our top 20 export destinations," Smith said.
</P>
<P>
He added that the effect of the Asian economic crisis so far
has been significant on New Zealand's key sectors, such as
forestry export.
</P>
<P>
But, he said, none of this is to suggest that New Zealand
"should turn its back on Asia" because of its current economic
crisis.
</P>
<P>
He said, "there continue to be good opportunities in services
such as tourism and education."
</P>
<P>
"Longer-term, Asian markets will continue to be our natural
trade, tourism and investment partners into the future.
</P>
<P>
"Even if they don't offer the levels of economic growth seen in
the past, they will offer strong, more sustainable rates of growth
in the future," Smith said.
</P>
<P>
The New Zealand minister noted that nothing is more certain
than that Asia will recover. "The only question is how long it
will take."  
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
