<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Chinese Army Plays Major Role in Combating Floods </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
BEIJING, August 25 (Xinhua) -- While combating the raging flood
waters of the Yangtze River, the People's Liberation Army and the
armed police force have so far dispatched some 175,000 soldiers to
participate in resue operations.
</P>
<P>
This is the largest military deployment in the Yangtze River
Basin since 1949, and the soldiers are playing a decisive role in
protecting people's lives and state and individual property, said
Ma Shukuan, a major-general of the PLA General Political
Department, at a news conference held by the Information Office of
the State Council here today.
</P>
<P>
According to Ma, another 95,000 soldiers have been sent to
fight the flooding along the Nenjiang and Songhua rivers in
northeast China.
</P>
<P>
The army has dispatched motor vehicles, ships, planes and
helicopters along with the soldiers who have saved and removed to
safe places 11.54 million people trapped by the floodwaters, and
reinforced dikes with a combined length of more than 5,900
kilometers.
</P>
<P>
These soldiers have also plugged breaches and eliminated
trouble spots at 5,690 places and helped transport goods totaling
78.37 million tons, said Ma.
</P>
<P>
The infinite loyalty to the country and the people, as well as
high sense of responsibility displayed by both men and officers of
the PLA have been highly praised by the Party and government
leaders and have won the admirations of the general public who
have provided easy accesses and material support to the army's
operations, Ma said.  
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
