<DOCNO> XIE19980825.0221 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1998-08-25 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Lower Tax Boosts Lake Victoria's Cargo Transport </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
NAIROBI, August 25 (Xinhua) -- Cargo transportation business
has picked up at Lake Vicoria's Kisumu Port in western Kenya in
the last week thanks to a 21 percent reduction of tariffs on
transit cargo taking effect on August 1.
</P>
<P>
A survey showed that a number of traders, who had shunned the
port due to what they termed as exorbitant charges, now resume
cargo business between Kisumu and Mwanza, Tanzania, the Daily
Nation newspaper reported Tuesday.
</P>
<P>
Cargo business between Kisumu and the Tanzanian ports of
Mwanza and Bukoba have not picked up since the Tanzanian giant
steamer, the motor vessel Bukoba, sank with more than 700 people
and about 100 tons of cargo in 1995.
</P>
<P>
Besides the alleged high tariffs, cargo business across the
lake had also been seriously hampered by the hyacinth weed, which
blocked the Kisumu pier, immobilizing smaller boats and forcing
larger ones to spend long hours and more fuel to dock.
</P>
<P>
At the peak of the hyacinth invasion, many traders opted to
transport goods from Kisumu's container depot and from the Kisumu
port to Mwanza by road.
</P>
<P>
Now with the weed cleared by strong winds and tariffs reduced,
the Kenya Railways Corporation (KRC), which manages the port, is
expecting a business boom.
</P>
<P>
With the revised charges, it will now cost 66,000 Shillings
(1,100 U.S. Dollars) to transport a container one way from Kisumu
to Mwanza, down from 84,000 Shillings (1,400 Dollars).
</P>
<P>
The new tariffs will especially benefit the importers of
cotton from Tanzania and coffee from Uganda, who use the Kisumu
port, said officials at the Kisumu port.
</P>
<P>
The KRC is also expected to take more measures to improve its
lake service and security of lake traveling. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> XIE19980825.0222 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1998-08-25 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Artificially-Induced Rainfall Relieves Hainan Drought </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
HAIKOU, August 25 (Xinhua) -- Hainan, China's southernmost
island province, has produced six artificially-induced rainfalls
in order to ease water shortage hindering agricultural production.
</P>
<P>
Cities and counties in western parts of the province have
experienced exceptionally hot and dry spring weather, with a rapid
drop in water levels in local reservoirs.
</P>
<P>
The drought has affected 72,000 hectares of cultivated land,
and more than 100,000 residents have been faced with a shortage of
potable water.
</P>
<P>
Changjiang, one most severely affected counties, reported 115
dry reservoirs and ponds are dry and disrupted water flow in 12
rivers and streams.
</P>
<P>
The artificially-induced rainfalls brought medium to heavy
precipitation to 30 towns and 10 farms, with related efforts
expected to ensure local agricultural production and the daily
activities of local residents. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
