<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Gonorrhoea Cases Increase Sharply in Wellington </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
WELLINGTON, August 25 (Xinhua) -- The number of Gonorrhoea
cases is increasing sharply in Wellington, capital of New Zealand,
according to a Wellington-based newspaper.
</P>
<P>
The Dominion Tuesday quoted Hilary Andrews, clinical director
of Wellington Sexual Health Service, as saying that 21 cases had
been diagnosed in the past six weeks, compared with 22 in the area
for all of last year.
</P>
<P>
Gonorrhoea is a sexually transmitted disease and is caught by
having sex without a condom with an infected person. The
incubation is from one to 10 days, so infection can spread
rapidly.
</P>
<P>
The symptom for men is a discharge from the penis while
urinating, but women usually have no symptoms and are diagnosed
only when their partner tests positive. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
