<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Cambodia's Opposition Vows to Continue Election Vigils </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
PHNOM PENH, August 25 (Xinhua) -- Cambodia's opposition parties
Tuesday vowed to maintain a 24-hour vigil in front of the National
Assembly which began from Monday until their complaints about
election irregularities are resolved and Second Prime Minister Hun
Sen steps down.
</P>
<P>
The sit-in protest is led by former Finance Minister Sam
Rainsy, head of the Sam Rainsy Party, and leaders of the Funcinpec
and some other small parties.
</P>
<P>
Funcinpec leader Prince Norodom Ranariddh, who returned from
Bangkok Monday, joined Sam Rainsy Tuesday and made an anti-Hun Sen
speech to the crowd.
</P>
<P>
About ten thousand opposition supporters are expected to take
part in Tuesday's vigil and protest.
</P>
<P>
In a Funcinpec-Sam Rainsy Party joint statement on Sunday, the
opposition threatened more mass demonstrations if their complaints
about election irregularities are not addressed by August 29, when
the official results of country's July 26 election are due to be
released.
</P>
<P>
It was reported that so far at least two violent attacks have
taken place by opposition supporters on bystanders perceived to be
Vietnamese during the march.
</P>
<P>
Analysts said the escalating violence and prolonged uncertainty
after the election would affect the establishment of a new
government and risk scaring away foreign investors.
</P>
<P>
Early results showed that Hun Sen's Cambodian People's Party
won the election, although it may not have enough parliamentary
seats to rule alone.
</P>
<P>
But the opposition parties, who accused Hun Sen of stuffing the
ballot box, refused to accept the preliminary official results or
the coalition offer proposed by Hun Sen. 
</P>
</TEXT>
