<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Bustling Markets in Lhasa Draw Businessmen </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
LHASA, August 25 (Xinhua)-- Travelers to Lhasa, capital of the
Tibet Autonomous Region, no longer need burden themselves with
bringing along articles for daily use, as they now can get almost
anything they need in the bustling markets in Lhasa on the "roof
of the world".
</P>
<P>
Shops and restaurants run by businessmen from Sichuan, Qinghai,
Shaanxi, Zhejiang and other provinces can be found everywhere on
the streets on the plateau city.
</P>
<P>
In the department store, sweaters made in Shanghai, cosmetics
from Guangdong, Japan-made electrical appliances, French perfumes,
and small articles from India and Nepal are readily available.
</P>
<P>
The night bazaar on the plateau, with a widen assortment
of goods, is even more charming.
</P>
<P>
A man from Henan sells about 10 kilograms of roasted sweet
potatos every night. He said that the sweet potatos are very cheap
in his hometown, and sell very well here.
</P>
<P>
A young man named Liu from Chengdu, capital of Sichuan
Province, runs a handicraft shop. His goods including photo frames
and music boxes from Shanghai, Guangzhou and Wenzhou all enjoy
popularity on the market.
</P>
<P>
Early in the 1980s, Lhasa had no marketplace except on Bargor
Street. Visitors to Tibet always complained that there was little
available to buy.
</P>
<P>
Businessmen from other provinces began to set up stalls in
Lhasa in 1985, but the market didn't take off until 1992 when a
set of policies were carried out to encourage businessmen to
invest in Tibet.
</P>
<P>
According to the Regional Department for Industry and Commerce,
thousands of enterprises from about 20 provinces and regions of
China are now doing business in Lhasa.  
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
