<DATE_TIME> 1998-08-25 07:52 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Lebanon to Clamp Down on Pirate Satellite </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
BEIRUT, August 25 (Xinhua) -- Lebanese government and state TV
stations are to launch a crackdown on pirate satellite TV stations
in the coming weeks, Lebanon's Daily Star newspaper reported on
Tuesday.
</P>
<P>
"We have decided to take action since the situation has become
intolerable and spread so quickly in a very harmful and chaotic
way," Naoum Farah, a lawyer hired by TV stations to sue the
illegal satellite operators, said.
</P>
<P>
Director-General of the Post and Telecommunications Ministry
Abdel Monem Youssef has also said that a crackdown on pirate TV
stations is on the way, the paper said.
</P>
<P>
"Written protests have been filed with the Ministry of Post
and Telecommunications by satellite channels, complaining of piracy
and abuse of intellectual property rights," he added.
</P>
<P>
There are about 600 to 700 pirate satellite TV stations, some of
whom even broadcast pornographic movies and advertisements to
their subscribers, the official said.
</P>
<P>
Farah estimated that over 1 million viewers in 200,000 homes
are subscribing to these illegal satellite TV stations, paying a
subscription fee of 6.6 to 10 U.S. dollars a month.
</P>
<P>
He said the lawsuits would be filed only against the "big and
known operators" across the country.
</P>
<P>
"We can not file against all the 600 or 700 illegal operators,
so we will target the big fish and the small ones will get the
message and stop their activities," he said. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
