<DATE_TIME> 1998-08-25 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Jiang Zemin Meets Associated Press Delegation </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
BEIJING, August 25 (Xinhua)-- Chinese President Jiang Zemin
said this morning that Chinese people are waging a united battle
against a serious flood rarely seen in the nation's history.
</P>
<P>
"The battle against flooding shows the cohesiveness of the
Chinese nation and the close friendship between the People's
Liberation Army and common citizens," said Jiang during a meeting
with a delegation from the board of directors of the U.S.-based
Associated Press (AP).
</P>
<P>
He said, "I also would like to take this opportunity to express
our thanks to the governments of various countries and their
people for their concern for and support to China which is
combating the floods."
</P>
<P>
AP Chairman Donald Newhouse and President and CEO
Louis Boccardi voiced the delegation's deep concern for the
suffering of Chinese citizens during this year's floods.
</P>
<P>
Jiang responded to questions concerning the future of
Sino-U.S. relations, the Taiwan issue and the Asian financial
crisis.
</P>
<P>
He pointed to Sino-U.S. relations and noted the highly
successful reciprocal visits by the presidents of the two nations
promoted bilateral relations to a new stage, and have opened even
greater prospects for exchanges and cooperation.
</P>
<P>
The summits, according to Jiang, not only helped deepen
understanding and strengthen friendship between peoples in the two
nations, but also resulted in major progress in building a
constructive and strategic Sino-U.S. partnership geared to the
21st century.
</P>
<P>
"We are approaching the turn of the century and healthy and
stable Sino-U.S. relations reflect the common aspirations of
peoples in both countries," said Jiang. "Close relations will also
promote peace, stability and prosperity in the Asia-Pacific
region and the world at large, and will comply with the trends and
requirements of the times."
</P>
<P>
Jiang expressed his belief that the two sides can remove all
obstacles and bring healthy and stable Sino-U.S. relations into
the next century so long as they proceed from the fundamental
interests of the people of China and the United States and of the
world at large, consider and handle the two countries' relations
from a strategic and long-term perspective, strictly abide by the
principles set in the three Sino-U.S. joint communiques, properly
deal with the differences between the two sides and, in
particular, properly handle the Taiwan issue.
</P>
<P>
Jiang praised the AP, which has exchanged news with the Xinhua
News Agency since the early 1970's, as one of the world's most
influential news agencies.
</P>
<P>
"I hope the two agencies will continue to strengthen
cooperation and communications in journalism and various other
fields," said Jiang.
</P>
<P>
The delegation, which arrived in Beijing on Sunday at the
invitation of the Xinhua News Agency, will also visit Xi'an,
Shanghai, Guilin and Hong Kong. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
