<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Journal on Uygur History and Culture Launched </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
URUMQI, August 25 (Xinhua) -- An academic journal on the
history and culture of the Uygur people has been launched in the
Xinjiang Uygur Autonomous Region.
</P>
<P>
The journal, which comes out twice a year, is expected to
contribute to the study of the Uygur nationality as well as the
history of Xinjiang.
</P>
<P>
With a population of more than seven million, the origin of
Uygurs can be traced back to nomadic tribes roaming in north China
in the third century BC. They mixed with Han and other
nationalities and settled in present-day Xinjiang in the middle of
the ninth century.
</P>
<P>
The journal, in both the Uygur and Chinese languages, is
published by a national society on the history and culture of the
Uygur people. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> XIE19980825.0249 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1998-08-25 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Reporting System Helps Stamp Out Corruption in Beijing </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
BEIJING, August 25 (Xinhua) -- Procuratorial organs in the
Chinese capital of Beijing have handled 49,714 cases of official
corruption since a reporting system was introduced in 1988.
</P>
<P>
By using a hotline, correspondence and interviews, the public
has provided tips in over 60 percent of the cases involving graft,
dereliction of duty and the violation of people's rights which
have been accepted and handled by procuratorial organs during the
past decade.
</P>
<P>
To date, more than 52 million yuan (about 6.3 million U.S.
dollars) have been retrieved for the state as a result of these
cases.
</P>
<P>
The People's Procuratorate in Beijing's Western District
opened the first hotline for reporting economic crimes on January
1, 1988, and the Beijing Municipal People's Procuratorate set up a
corruption-reporting center in August of the same year, with
branch offices around the city.
</P>
<P>
Since 1995, 210 senior officials above the bureau chief level
have been reported as being corrupt, among which 195 cases
involved at least one million yuan.
</P>
<P>
Recently exposed cases include one involving an official with
the People's Construction Bank who, when he worked as a top
officer in one of the bank's Beijing branch offices, accepted
bribes and embezzled funds totaling more than one million yuan.
</P>
<P>
Yan Zhengguo, head of the Installation Management Department
of Air China, was recently found guilty of dereliction of duty by
the reporting system, which led to losses of over 8 million yuan.
</P>
<P>
The presence and force of the reporting system have caused 523
law-breakers to turn themselves in to authorities during the last
ten years, according to local sources. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> XIE19980825.0250 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1998-08-25 06:21 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Khatami Rejects Resignation of Envoy on Afghan </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
TEHRAN, August 25 (Xinhua) -- Iranian President Mohammad
Khatami has rejected the resignation of Iran's special envoy on
Afghan affairs Alaeddin Boroujerdi, local daily Tehran Times
reported on Tuesday.
</P>
<P>
Boroujerdi submitted his resignation last week after his
efforts failed to find out the whereabouts of 11 Iranian diplomats
allegedly kidnapped by the Afghan Taliban militia.
</P>
<P>
Iran has alleged that the Taliban forces kidnapped these
Iranian diplomats and a reporter of the official news agency IRNA
in Mazari Sharif of northern Afghanistan on August 8 when the
militia took control of the city.
</P>
<P>
However, the Taliban rejected Iran's claim, saying that the
Iranian consulate in the city was evacuated when their forces
reached there and they have no information about the whereabouts
of these Iranian diplomats.
</P>
<P>
Iranian Foreign Ministry has been widely accused of failing to
acquire advance information about the fall of Mazari Sharif, the
main stronghold of the Tehran-backed opposition Northern Alliance
led by President Burhanuddin Rabbani, who is still recognized by
the international community as the legal ruler of the country.
</P>
<P>
Last Thursday, President Khatami summoned Foreign Minister
Kamal Kharrazi and his deputies to discuss the situation in
Afghanistan.
</P>
<P>
Kharrazi criticized Boroujerdi for his inefficient role on the
Afghan affairs, but Boroujerdi contended that he was not provided
necessary facilities for performing his duties properly.
</P>
<P>
Boroujerdi, former deputy foreign minister for Asia-pacific
affairs, was named as Iran's special envoy on Afghan affairs
after President Khatami took office in August last year. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
