<HEADLINE> China Set to Retire Power Station Loan on Schedule </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
PANZHIHUA, August 25 (Xinhua) -- Chinese experts said today
that the China is fully capable of retiring World Bank loans for
the nation's largest hydropower station constructed this century
on schedule.
</P>
<P>
The agreement calls for China to pay 1.75 billion US dollars in
principal and interest on the loans by the year 2015. The loans
are being used to construct the Ertan Hydropower Station which
entered partial operations two weeks ago.
</P>
<P>
Liu Junfeng, general manager of the Ertan Hydropower
Development Co. Ltd., said the Ministry of Finance has guaranteed
the loan repayment.
</P>
<P>
The stations, located on the Yalong River, a tributary of the
Yangtze River, in Panzhihua, Sichuan Province, will have six
generators with a combined generating capacity of 3.3 million
kilowatts/hour.
</P>
<P>
The plant, which will be constructed at a cost of 28.55 billion
yuan (3.44 billion US dollars), will mainly supply power to
Sichuan Province and Chongqing Municipality prior to entering
full-scale operations.
</P>
<P>
"World Bank inspections carried out in recent years have
granted Class-A ratings to all the Ertan projects involving
related loans," said Liu Junfeng
</P>
<P>
The general manager attributed the success of the project to
the introduction of international financing and bidding, and the
extensive use of advanced technology and management methods.
</P>
<P>
However, unnamed sources indicated that bank officials
conducted a recent inspection and expressed some concern
concerning the future marketing of power.
</P>
<P>
Wang Keming, deputy chief engineer in charge of the loan
project, expressed certainty the plant will have adequate users
and that rates will easily ensure that both principal and interest
will be paid on schedule.
</P>
<P>
Wang pointed out that the annual per capita power consumption
in Sichuan stands at a mere 600 kWh, or less than 10 percent of
that in developed countries.
</P>
<P>
He projected that the demand for power will grow substantially
with the closure of a large number of thermal power stations built
in the 1950s, and the progress being made in restructuring
state-owned enterprises. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
