<HEADLINE> Major News Items in Leading Israeli Newspapers </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
JERUSALEM, August 25 (Xinhua) -- The following are major news
items in leading Israeli newspapers Tuesday.
</P>
<P>
The Jerusalem Post:
</P>
<P>
-- Sources close to Israeli Prime Minister Benjamin Netanyahu
said on Monday that Netanyahu is prepared for a 13 percent
withdrawal of Israeli troops from the West Bank. Israeli and
Palestinian officials also confirmed that a new, direct
negotiation channel had been opened between Netanyahu's aide
Yitzhak Molcho, and Abu Ala, the speaker of the Palestinian
Legislative Council.
</P>
<P>
Haaretz:
</P>
<P>
-- Israel is reviewing its nuclear weapon policy and whether
its traditional "strategic vagueness" regarding its nuclear
capability is effective. Meanwhile, a top U.S. expert says Israel
is the most vulnerable country in the world to a ballistic
missile attack.
</P>
<P>
Yediot Aharonot:
</P>
<P>
-- Israel's unemployment continued to rise in the second
quarter of 1998, soaring to 9.4 percent of the workforce. It is
considerably higher than the 7.6 percent that was recorded in the
same period of 1997, and is the highest since February
1993. 
</P>
</TEXT>
