<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Backgrounder: China Uses Largest WB Loan for Single Project </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
PANZHIHUA, August 25 (Xinhua) -- The Ertan Hydropower Station
in southwest China is the recipient of the largest single project
loan the World Band has provided since its founding in 1945.
</P>
<P>
The plant, scheduled for completion at a projected cost of
28.55 billion yuan (about 3.449 billion US dollars), entered
partial operations two weeks ago.
</P>
<P>
The project involves World Bank loans of 930 million US dollars
of WB loans, including financing provided by 19 international
banks guaranteed by the World Bank.
</P>
<P>
The bank agreed to grant in July 1991 and the project
construction contract between the Ertan Hydropower Development
Co. Ltd. and overseas developers was signed on August 31, 1991, in
Beijing.
</P>
<P>
Li Peng, the then Chinese premier who attended the ceremony,
announced the Chinese government would continue to pursue its
reform and opening policy, and welcome international organizations
and investors to expand economic exchanges with China.
</P>
<P>
Construction of the project, with a designed capacity of 3.3
million kWh, started on September 14, 1991.
</P>
<P>
The Yalong River facility started partial operations earlier
this month. 
</P>
</TEXT>
