<BODY>
<HEADLINE> 17 Killed in Floods on U.S.-Mexican Border Area </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
LOS ANGELES, August 24 (Xinhua) -- At least 17 people were
killed in flooding that washed away blocks of homes in the
U.S.-Mexican border region, said reports reaching here Monday.
</P>
<P>
People scrambled onto rooftops and trees to escape waters that
rose as high as 2.44 meters in the streets of Del Rio in the Texas
State, and its Mexican sister city Ciudad Acuna.
</P>
<P>
In Del Rio, police said at least four people died. Reports said
that all roads and highways leading to Del Rio were flooded,
leaving the city of about 30,000 people completely isolated.
</P>
<P>
In Ciudad Acuna, the Mexican government said three people were
killed by flooding. Earlier the Mexican news agency had reported
nine deaths in the border town, about 30 percent of which was
flooded.
</P>
<P>
Reports from both sides of the border said that as many as 30
others were missing and 2,500 people had been forced to abandon
their homes.
</P>
<P>
During the past few days, heavy rains from the remnants of
Tropical Storm Charley turned rivers in the U.S.-Mexican border
region into raging torrents which swept houses away.
</P>
<P>
Rescue workers and policemen were brought in to rescue those
stranded by high-rising water on both sides of the border. 
</P>
</TEXT>
