<HEADLINE> Elderly Giant Panda Survives Hot Summer In East China </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
HANGZHOU, August 25 (Xinhua) -- Pei Pei, a 27-year-old giant
panda who has reached an exceptionally advanced age for the
species, has survived the scorching summer in a zoo in Hangzhou,
capital of east China's Zhejiang Province.
</P>
<P>
Pei Pei is housed in a large air conditioned room maintained at
a constant temperature of around 27 degrees centigrade. Zoo keepers
have worked diligently to protect the elderly panda's health.
</P>
<P>
Pei Pei, one of the few giant pandas to live to age 25,
receives a special diet consisting of highly nutritious gruel,
tender bamboo shoot, bread and milk.
</P>
<P>
The giant panda has a good appetite and is full of
vigor. Experts predict she will live beyond the age of 30, a
plateau considered to be extremely rare for the species.
</P>
<P>
Pei Pei, the only giant panda in the province, eats breakfast
and roams about her compound before returning to the enclosure to
await the arrival of visitors to the province.
</P>
<P>
China is home of the only giant pandas, an endanged species,
living in the wild. The giant panda population is estimated at
around 1,000 animals, including 117 housed in zoos around the
world.  
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
