<HEADLINE> Living Buddha Completes Basic Buddhism Studies </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
LHASA, August 25 (Xinhua) -- While most 14-year-old boys would
quite likely consider reciting sutras several hours a day as
somewhat boring, O'kying Chilai, the 17th Garmaba Living Buddha in
the Tibet Autonomous Region, regards the activity as a sacred part
of his life.
</P>
<P>
The young Living Buddha, a member of Kagyudpa School from the
White Sect of Tibetan Buddhism, followed in his predecessors
footsteps and recently completed basic studies of Buddhism in the
Curbo Monastery.
</P>
<P>
The Living Buddha has memorized more than 4,000 sutras and
reached a fourth grade level in mandarin.
</P>
<P>
Senior lamas and laymen language instructors have expressed
great admiration for intelligence and diligence.
</P>
<P>
The lama in charge of the young man's daily life points out
that he arises promptly at 05:00 every morning and immediately
prays and chants scriptures for an hour. He spends most the day
studying sutras, and presides over meetings with followers for an
hour each.
</P>
<P>
He occasionally reads famous literary classics, with King
Gessar, a Tibetan epic containing 10 million characters, purported
to be his favorite.
</P>
<P>
The Living Buddha joins more than 370 lamas living in the
monastery to celebrate a major holiday which falls on June 4th
according to the Tibetan lunar calendar.
</P>
<P>
The activities performances of Tibetan folk art and videotapes
of adapted Chinese classics such as "A Pilgrimage to the West" and
"Outlaws of the Marsh".
</P>
<P>
The Kagyudpa School introduced the reincarnation system for
living Buddhas.
</P>
<P>
Lamas from the Curbo Monastery, located 70 kilometers from
Lhasa in southwestern Tibet, followed instructions in the will
left by the 16th Garmaba Living Buddha and conducted a search for
the reincarnated soul boy.
</P>
<P>
The search led them to eight-year-old O'kying Chilai who lived
on a ranch in eastern Tibet.
</P>
<P>
The young boy became the first reincarnated Living Buddha the
central government approved following the founding of the People's
Republic of China in 1949.  
</P>
</TEXT>
