<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Chickens Control Grasslands Locust Infestation </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
BEIJING, August 25 (Xinhua) -- Some 10,000 chickens and tens of
thousands of starlings have proved to be the most effective means
for controlling locust infesting 174,500 hectares of grasslands in
northwest China's Xinjiang Uygur Autonomous Region.
</P>
<P>
Previous attempts to use manpower and aircraft to curb the
locust infestation failed.
</P>
<P>
The chickens undergo a special 60-day training program shortly
after birth and numerous nests were placed in the area earlier
this year to attract starling, a small migratory bird measuring 20
cm in length.
</P>
<P>
Starlings spend the summer in northern China and migrate to the
south in winter.
</P>
<P>
Today's China Youth Daily quoted an official with the Xinjiang
Pest Control Headquarters as saying that locusts have infested
approximately a fourth of Xinjiang's grassland areas since the
beginning of summer, He cited this year's infestation as the worst
in a decade.
</P>
<P>
Locusts have infested housing complexes, shops and office
buildings in urban areas surrounding Urumqi, the regional capital.
</P>
<P>
The Ministry of Agriculture allocated 3.5 million yuan (422,000
US dollars) to establish a regional locust control headquarters.
</P>
<P>
Experts said the fact that most of the locusts jump rather than
fly has lessened the severity of this summer's infestation.
</P>
<P>
The birds have helped to basically control the infestation
this summer and locust monitoring stations have been set up at the
autonomous regional, prefectural and county levels.  
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
