<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Stone Age Sites Found in Reservoir Area </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
TAIYUAN, August 25 (Xinhua) -- A great number of Stone Age
sites have been found in areas in north China's Shanxi Province
that will be submerged after completion of a reservoir on the
Yellow River.
</P>
<P>
Chinese archaeologists are rescuing the relics in the sites
and moving them to safer places before the inundation.
</P>
<P>
The sites include a pottery kiln from some 4,700 years ago and
the remains of some 300 neolithic dwellings, stoves, and rubbish pits.
</P>
<P>
Chinese archaeologists say that the pottery kiln is one of the
best preserved of its kind, with details that will help recover
the pottery-making procedure used at that remote time.
</P>
<P>
National and local archaeologists have been researching and
excavating the sites since the beginning of this decade when the
country decided to build the Xiaoliangdi Reservoir. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
