<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Ancient Iron Oxen Put in Good Care </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
TAIYUAN, August 25 (Xinhua) -- Nearly six million yuan has been
invested to conserve four huge oxen dating back to the middle Tang
Dynasty (618-907) in Yongji City in north China's Shanxi province.
</P>
<P>
The 1,200-year-old oxen, discovered at Pujindu Harbor, were
found along with figures of iron human figures and an iron model
mountain, in August 1989. The iron objects weigh 146 tons, about
one fourth of the total iron output of the Kaiyuan Period
(713-741).
</P>
<P>
To prevent the oxen from rusting, Chinese experts plan to
elevate the site where the oxen are placed by 12.2 meters and
build a waterproof layer under it. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
