<HEADLINE> Xinhua World Economic News Summary at 0500 GMT, August 25 </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
BANGKOK -- Thailand is going to put on sale stately homes and
mansions once used as ambassadorial residences and commercialize
some embassy premises in prime locations overseas in an effort to
improve the government's shaking fiscal position.
</P>
<P>
The proceeds from the sale and commercial use of former and
existing embassy premises will go to the state coffers to make up
for expected huge shortfalls in tax collection amid the economic
downturn, the newspaper The Nation reported Tuesday, quoting
Foreign Ministry Spokesman Kobsak Chutikul. (Thailand-Properties)
</P>
<P>
- - - -
</P>
<P>
YANGON -- Myanmar leader Lieutenant-General Khin Nyunt has
stressed the need to accelerate the privatization of heavy
industries including small mills and factories.
</P>
<P>
Speaking at a meeting here Monday of the Myanmar Privatization
Commission (MPC), Khin Nyunt, First Secretary of the State Peace
and Development Council, called for giving opportunities to
government employees in the to-be-privatized mills and factories
to have shares in them, the official newspaper The New Light of
Myanmar reported Tuesday. (Myanmar-Privatization)
</P>
<P>
- - - -
</P>
<P>
QUITO -- Ecuadorian trade, with its Andean Community (CAN)
associates, rose 10.39 percent in the first half of 1998, while
its trade with the United States and the European Union decreased
4.28 percent and 13.86 percent respectively.
</P>
<P>
Ecuador's total trade volume amounted to 4.856 billion
U.S. dollars in the first half of 1998, 0.27 percent less than the
same period in 1997. (Ecuador-Trade)
</P>
<P>
- - - -
</P>
<P>
BUCHAREST -- The European Union continued to rank first among
Romania's trade partners, with 59 percent of Romania's total
foreign trade in the first five months of the year, showed the
latest official statistical data.
</P>
<P>
The total volume of foreign trade of Romania amounted to 7.88
billion U.S. dollars, up 3.8 percent compared with the same period
in the previous year. Export volume reached 3.37 billion U.S.
dollars, while import volume was of 4.51 billion U.S. dollars.
Thus, the commercial balance over the mentioned period indicated a
deficit of 1.14 billion U.S. dollars. (Romania-EU-Trade)
</P>
<P>
- - - -
</P>
<P>
OTTAWA -- The Canadian dollar dropped to a new record closing
low of 64.55 U.S. cents Monday, down about a quarter of a cent
from Friday's close.
</P>
<P>
The dollar touched an all-time trading low of 64.50 U.S. cents
during the day. The Bank of Canada intervened at several levels to
shore it up. (Canada-Dollar)
</P>
<P>
- - - -
</P>
<P>
MOSCOW -- Russia's blue chips witnessed their first rally in 10
days Monday amid thin trading as the market awaited the terms of a
conversion plan for the ruble-denominated GKO Treasury bills.
</P>
<P>
A change of government had little effect on the stock market
except that shares of Gazprom shot up 24.2 percent on news that
its former head, Viktor Chernomyrdin, had been reinstated as the
prime minister. (Russia-Shares) 
</P>
</TEXT>
