<HEADLINE> Sri Lankan Government Helps Feed Displaced Families </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
COLOMBO, August 25 (Xinhua) -- The Sri Lankan government has
recently spent about 2 million U.S. dollars in providing food to
displaced families in the country's war-torn north.
</P>
<P>
According to the Commission General of Essential Services
Department, the districts of Jaffna, Kilinochchi, Mullaitivu,
Mannar and Vavuniya in Northern province have 58,000, 8,900,
13,000, 16,000 and 5,500 displaced families respectively at
present, department sources said Tuesday.
</P>
<P>
In addition, the sources said the department maintains 342
welfare centers in 15 districts in the country and the 38,800
families in these centers are also given free meals.
</P>
<P>
Rations are graded according to the size of each family and a
family gets a maximum of 1,260 rupees (some 20 U.S. dollars) worth
of goods per month which include sugar, dhal, wheat, flour and
milk powder.
</P>
<P>
Around 8,000 fishermen who have lost their income due to
restricted fishing because of tight security in the northwestern
coastal area are also issued rations, the sources added.
</P>
<P>
Sri Lanka has long been plagued by problems between the
Sinhalese and Tamil, the major ethnic groups in the country.
</P>
<P>
Tamil rebels have been fighting a war against the government
for a separate state in the north and east of the country since
1983. 55,000 people have been reportedly killed in the war which
has also made some 1 million people refugees. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
