<HEADLINE> Indian Tea Company to Buy Sri Lankan Tea Gardens </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
NEW DELHI, August 25 (Xinhua) -- India's tea major Tata Tea
company is expected to acquire 21 more tea gardens in Sri Lanka in
a bid to globalize its tea production and marketing base, Tata Tea
sources said here Tuesday.
</P>
<P>
The company has already acquired 23 gardens in Sri Lanka and
tea production from these gardens amounts to about 6 million
kilograms. With the proposed acquisition, the number of gardens to
be run by Tata Tea in Sri Lanka would come to 44 and the company's
Sri Lankan ventures would ensure an additional supply of about 12
million kilograms.
</P>
<P>
In the first three months of the current fiscal year, Tata
Tea's exports to Russia was up by 11 million kilograms. India was
in a much more advantageous position vis-a-vis its competitors of
Sri Lanka and Kenya because of a rupee-ruble agreement, Tata Tea
Managing Director S. M. Kidwai said.
</P>
<P>
Once things stabilize, the Russian buyers would tilt toward
India to cash on the rupee-ruble opportunity as Russian buyers
would have to pay hard currency if they import from other
countries, he said. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
