<BODY>
<HEADLINE> California Forbids New Taxes on Internet Activities </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
Los Angeles, August 24 (Xinhua) -- California Governor Pete
Wilson Monday signed a state bill that bans any new taxes on
Internet activities for the next three years, calling on
U.S. Congress and the President to enact a federal version.
</P>
<P>
The new state bill, The California Internet Tax Freedom Act,
imposes a moratorium on taxes for any internet activity, including
online purchases and server accounts. Under the act, Internet
companies that are based in California but do manufacturing in
other states or ship their products to other states will be exempt
from California sales tax.
</P>
<P>
Industry analysts believe that the new measure is intended to
help companies dependent on the Internet create new products,
services and jobs.
</P>
<P>
Representatives of high-tech industries welcomed the new law.
</P>
<P>
"For California's economy and its citizens, growth in electronic
commerce means new jobs," the American Electronics Association said in
a statement. "By prohibiting any new taxes on the Internet, we
encourage the growth of electronic commerce and enhance the
opportunities available for Californians to find work in cyberspace
or related service industries."
</P>
<P>
Larry McCarthy, president of the California Taxpayers' Association,
said the new measure will help California retain its leadership in
high-tech industry.  
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
