<DOCNO> XIE19980825.0276 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1998-08-25 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Foreign Banks Pose Threat to Local Ones: Thai Banker </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
BANGKOK, August 25 (Xinhua) -- Foreign-run banks will be
biggest competitors for local banks in the future, Chartsiri
Sophonpanich, president of Bangkok Bank, said.
</P>
<P>
The Bangkok Post Tuesday quoted the Bangkok Bank president as
saying Thailand's banks are poised to split into three groups
after the recent comprehensive financial reform package.
</P>
<P>
The first group would comprise Thai banks which have raised
capital and would remain under local control.
</P>
<P>
This group includes Bangkok Bank, Thai Farmers Bank, Bank of
Ayudhya, Siam Commercial Bank and Thai Military Bank, all of which
are similar in terms of operational efficiency.
</P>
<P>
The second group would be state-run institutions such as Krung
Thai Bank, Radanasin Bank and Krungthai Thanakit, which would gain
strengths and experience some weaknesses through ties to the
government.
</P>
<P>
Local banks owned by foreign financial institutions will form
the third group, which will pose the largest competitive threat in
the future, Chartsiri said.
</P>
<P>
This group, including Bank of Asia under ABN-Amro and Thai Danu
Bank controlled by the Development Bank of Singapore, would
benefit from information technology and management systems
transferred from their foreign partners.
</P>
<P>
Bangkok Bank, the country's largest commercial bank, plans to
improve efficiency and productivity to meet the challenges ahead,
Chartsiri said.
</P>
<P>
Bangkok Bank may lose its top position in the country's banking
sector after the Krung Thai Bank absorbs assets and good debts of
Bangkok Bank of Commerce and First Bangkok City Bank under the
reform package.
</P>
<P>
However, Chartsiri said the bank has never been concerned about
asset size. Instead quality is of primary concern, he added.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> XIE19980825.0277 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1998-08-25 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> RBI Likely to Announce New Policy Favorable of IT </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
NEW DELHI, August 25 (Xinhua) -- The Reserve Bank of India
(RBI) is expected to announce a new policy soon in favor of the
country's information technology (IT) and software development, a
government official said here Tuesday.
</P>
<P>
The new policy exclusively deals with working capital for
information technology and the software development and service
sector to be provided by scheduled commercial banks. As part of
the proposed policy, the banks would be advised to advance up to
25 percent of the project-wise export or domestic contract value
for a term of 18 months and also treat IT software and services as
a priority sector for the next five years.
</P>
<P>
The scheduled commercial banks lending to infotech software and
services exporters would be made eligible for RBI refinancing with
considerably low interest rates. They would also be allowed to
invest in dedicated capital funds meant for the infotech industry.
</P>
<P>
Under the broad guidelines of the proposed national informatics
policy being formulated by a task force appointed within the Prime
Minister's Office, 1 to 3 percent of every government ministry's
outlay should be earmarked for expenditure on information
technology and every department in the central government and
state governments would have to adopt and implement a five-year IT
action plan, the official said.
</P>
<P>
According to the proposed policy, the basic eligibility and
upper limit for the funding by scheduled commercial banks would be
based on the annual turnover level and export performance of the
applicant companies, the official added. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
