<HEADLINE> US, DPRK to Continue Talks </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
NEW YORK, August 24 (Xinhua) -- Talks between the United States
and the Democratic People's Republic of Korea (DPRK) held here on
Friday and Monday will continue into a third session Tuesday
morning.
</P>
<P>
DPRK chief negotiator Vice Foreign Minister Kim Gye-kwan
affirmed this when he left the U.S. Mission to the U.N. at 8:15
p.m. (local time), after the end of Monday's session which started
at 1:00 p.m.
</P>
<P>
On Friday, Kim and U.S. Deputy Assistant Secretary of State
Charles Kartman met for eight hours at the same venue.
</P>
<P>
Both sides have kept reporters guessing on the topics of the
discussion, except for a brief confirmation made by
U.S. delegation spokesman Richard Scorza who said the Agreed
Framework reached between both sides in 1994 was included in the
agenda.
</P>
<P>
Under the accord, the DPRK will suspend a graphite reactor
program in exchange for the U.S. and others to supply fuel oil for
light water reactors in the DPRK.
</P>
<P>
Pyongyang has been complaining about oil delivery delays as the
U.S. Congress has blocked funds for the oil supplies.
</P>
<P>
"We have sufficient talks between each other, the mood is very
amicable and we are going to meet tomorrow morning," Kim told
reporters waiting outside the Mission building. 
</P>
</TEXT>
