<HEADLINE> Economic News Briefs from Latin America </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
MEXICO CITY, August 24 (Xinhua) -- The following are major
economic news briefs from Latin American countries:
</P>
<P>
SANTIAGO -- Chile's net international reserves have increased
76.2 million U.S. dollars in the first half of August, which is an
upturn in the downward trend occurring since February.
</P>
<P>
The bimonthly report from the Emitting Institute indicates that
Chile's net international reserves reached 14.978 billion
dollars, compared with 14.901 billion dollars by the end of July.
</P>
<P>
Even though there was a recovery in the first half of August,
the net international reserves have decreased 2.863 billion
dollars.
</P>
<P>
BUENOS AIRES -- The price of desktop computers has dropped by
30 percent in the last 12 months in the Argentine Market.
</P>
<P>
According to public sales representatives, the price reduction
is due primarily to the reduction of component costs.
</P>
<P>
SAN JOSE -- The Costa Rican Production National Committee
(CNP) will invest 600,000 dollars this year to raise the
bean yield in northern Costa Rica.
</P>
<P>
According to data given by CNP, which is in charge of
agricultural production in Costa Rica, farming has been greatly
affected by the climate in the past few years.
</P>
<P>
Meanwhile, the country has imported large amounts of grain to
meet the needs of the population. 
</P>
</TEXT>
