<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Thailand to Sell Foreign Property for Funds </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
BANGKOK, August 25 (Xinhua) -- Thailand is going to put on sale
stately homes and mansions once used as ambassadorial residences
and commercialize some embassy premises in prime locations
overseas in an effort to improve the government's shaking fiscal
position.
</P>
<P>
The proceeds from the sale and commercial use of former and
existing embassy premises will go to the state coffers to make up
for expected huge shortfalls in tax collection amid the economic
downturn, the newspaper The Nation reported Tuesday, quoting
Foreign Ministry Spokesman Kobsak Chutikul.
</P>
<P>
Among prime properties to be sold are the Thai ambassador's
former residence outside London worth between 300 million and 400
million baht (7.5 million to 10 million U.S. dollars) and a former
ambassadorial home adjacent to the Vienna Woods in Vienna
estimated at 200 million to 300 million baht (5 million to 7.5
million dollars), he said.
</P>
<P>
The spokesman said embassies will be asked to make calculations
on whether it would be more cost-efficient to consider a long-term
lease for embassies or offices instead of buying new properties or
maintaining existing ones.
</P>
<P>
The ministry has already recalled 30 percent of its overseas
workforce at embassies throughout the world. At present, there are
about 1,600 officials at the Thai Foreign Ministry. Of these only
about 400 Thai diplomats and auxiliary staff are stationed abroad.
 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
