<DOCNO> XIE19980825.0283 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1998-08-25 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> U.S. Presses India, Pakistan to Join Arms Control Treaty </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
WASHINGTON, August 24 (Xinhua) -- The United States tried to
press India and Pakistan into joining the Comprehensive Test Ban
Treaty during a meeting on Monday in Washington between
U.S. Deputy Secretary of State Strobe Talbott and Indian envoy
Jaswant Singh, the State Department said.
</P>
<P>
Talbott will also travel to London on Tuesday to meet Pakistani
Foreign Secretary Shamshad Ahmad for the same purpose.
</P>
<P>
"The goal of the talks with both countries is to explore how
the U.S. and the international community can work with India and
Pakistan to bring them back into the international
nonproliferation consensus, reduce tensions and address their
security concerns," a spokesman said.
</P>
<P>
It was the fourth round of talks the U.S. has held with India
and Pakistan aimed at easing tensions in South Asia since they
conducted nuclear tests in May.
</P>
<P>
The State Department disclosed no details about the talks, but
India still appeared to resist signing the Comprehensive Test Ban
Treaty.
</P>
<P>
"We will not come under any pressure and sign a treaty that is
against the interests of our country," Kushabhau Thakre, president
of India's ruling Bharatiya Janata Party, said on Monday.
</P>
<P>
Pakistan said on Sunday that it would seek to include its
dispute with India over the Jammu and Kashmir region in its talks
with Talbott.
</P>
<P>
"Our position is that this (nuclear) issue cannot be discussed
in isolation. We have to consider peace and security within the
region and within that the core issue of Jammu and Kashmir," a
foreign ministry official said. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
