<DATE_TIME> 1998-08-25 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Profile: Millionaire Yang Professes Investment Enthusiasm </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
By Xinhua Writer Pan Qing
</P>
<P>
SHANGHAI, August 25 (Xinhua) -- "I'll always be an enthusiastic
investor," said Yang Huading, or the legendary Shanghai
Millionaire Yang who has been largely ignored by his friends.
</P>
<P>
The former warehouse gatekeeper quit his government job some 10
years ago and joined the first wave of Chinese investors to enter
the stock market.
</P>
<P>
Yang increased his limited capital by trading government bonds
which China introduced in the early 1980s. Investors at the time
faced difficulty in cashing bonds since only a few outlets in
Shanghai, Yang's home, handled related transactions.
</P>
<P>
Yang and his colleagues paid uniformed investors low prices for
their bonds and in turn sold same to government outlets at a
profit. "I once paid 70 yuan bonds valued at 100 yuan," said Yang.
</P>
<P>
The Shanghai Stock Exchange opened in December 1990 and Yang
became one of the pioneers trading on the nation's first
bourse. Yang earned his nickname by consistently completing deals
worth around one million yuan.
</P>
<P>
The former leader of local stock investors faded from the
limelight as wealthy investors flocked to stocks.
</P>
<P>
Yang currently lives in self-imposed seclusion in a common
apartment. "I haven't been downtown in 10 years and I don't
participate in recreational activities," said Yang.
</P>
<P>
His main activity centers on presenting a weekly lecture to
investors in Nanjing, capital of neighboring Jiangsu Province.
</P>
<P>
Yang works at home and completes transactions via his computer
or telephone everyday between 09:00 and 15:00. The virtual hermit
closely monitors radio and television reports, and reads at least
five newspapers daily. All of his activities center on finances
and investment.
</P>
<P>
His three-line business card reads: Millionaire Wang; common
stock investor in Shanghai; professor at the Shenyang Financial
Institute.
</P>
<P>
"A short 10 years ago, most Chinese were indulged in debates
as to whether stock markets belong to socialism or capitalism. I
opted to take a change and became directly involved in stocks,"
said Yang.
</P>
<P>
"With regard to role I've played in the development of China's
stock market, I quite frankly was 'the first man who dared eat the
crab'," says Yang. The once brilliant young investor appeared much
more mature during a television appearance some two years ago.
</P>
<P>
Many people view Millionaire Yang as simply one of the
country's 34 million stock investors. China is now home to a
number of millionaires and, in fact, a growing number of
billionaires. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> XIE19980825.0286 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1998-08-25 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> URGENT  Myanmar Searches for Missing Airliner </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
YANGON, August 25 (Xinhua) -- The Myanmar authorities are
launching a search operation for a missing airliner of the
state-run Myanmar Airways which was lost on Monday over Tachilek,
eastern Shan state bordering Thailand.
</P>
<P>
According to Tuesday's official newspaper The New Light of
Myanmar, the Fokker XY-AEN with more than 20 local Myanmar
passengers on board was on a domestic flight (UB-635) from Yangon
to Tachilek Monday morning.
</P>
<P>
When reaching Tachilek airspace 3,000 meters above the airport,
the aircraft reported to the airport traffic control tower that it
could not land due to bad weather condition as it was raining in
the area and turned back to a nearby airport, the Heho.
</P>
<P>
Soon afterward, contact was lost with the aircraft, the paper
said.
</P>
<P>
Search operation is under way with the help of other aircraft
and helicopters, it added.
</P>
<P>
The Myanmar Airways is operating its internal flight services
with a fleet of seven Fokker-27 and three Fokker-28 aircraft.
</P>
<P>
Earlier on January 27 this year, a Myanmar Airways' passenger
plane Fokker-27 with 41 passengers and four crew members aboard
crashed at Thandwe, Southwestern Rakhine state of the country,
killing 14 persons including two French and an Italian and
injuring 20 others. 
</P>
