<DATE_TIME> 1998-08-25 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE>   Roundup: Slovak Economy Grows Fast, Problems Loom Large </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
PRAGUE, August 24 (Xinhua) -- With fast growth and low
inflation in recent years, the Slovak economy has become one of
the best in Central and Eastern Europe, but problems are waiting
in the wings.
</P>
<P>
The Slovak economy suffered a serious setback in 1993 when the
country gained independence, with a 3.7 percent decline in the
gross domestic product (GDP).
</P>
<P>
However, the Slovak government took great pains in promoting
market economy, adjusting economic policies, tightening control
over its macro-economy, reshaping industrial structure, slashing
public expenditures, encouraging export and attracting foreign
investment.
</P>
<P>
All these efforts paid off. The Slovak economy started to
recover in 1994. Besides a growth rate of 4.9 percent in 1994,
Slovakia achieved an annual growth of 6.8, 6.9 and 6 percent from
1995 to 1997. The growth for 1998 is estimated at 5 percent.
</P>
<P>
Its industrial production, which has been on the rise over the
recent years, increased by 4 percent in 1997.
</P>
<P>
Foreign trade, which stood at 21.3 billion U.S. dollars last
year, shot up by 76 percent as compared with that of 1993.
</P>
<P>
With the economy on the mend, Slovakia's inflation rate dropped
by a large margin, from 23.2 percent in 1993 to 6 percent in
1997. Inflation is expected to remain at 6 percent this year.
</P>
<P>
The Asian financial turmoil and the Russian financial crisis,
that have sent shockwaves to many countries, have hardly affected
Slovakia. The stock and currency markets stay stable in the
country. The exchange rate between the U.S. dollar and the koruna
has been kept within the range of 1:32 and 1:35 in recent years.
</P>
<P>
And no depreciation is expected of the Slovak currency this
year.
</P>
<P>
But problems loom large.
</P>
<P>
First, budget deficits are expected to rise by 50 percent from
37 billion koruna (more than 1 billion dollars) in 1997 to 51.3
billion koruna (about 1.5 billion dollars) this year.
</P>
<P>
Because of the weak financial system that cannot support a
normal operation of a market economy, Prague has to borrow
money. Its foreign debts have piled up to reach 11.2 billion
dollars, or more than 50 percent of its GDP, far above the warning
level of 40 percent.
</P>
<P>
Second, unemployment is worsening and posing as a growing
obstacle to the economic development. By the end of July, the
jobless population was registered at 389,000, which means an
unemployment rate of 14.1 percent.
</P>
<P>
The problem is even worse in the eastern part of the country
with the unemployment rate getting as high as 30 percent in some
counties.
</P>
<P>
As the economic restructuring deepens, more people would be
laid off, becoming one of the social and economic worries of the
Slovak government.
</P>
<P>
Third, rising trade deficits is another major problem for the
country. Trade deficits soared to 70 billion koruna (about 2
billion dollars) in 1997, 12 times that of 1995.
</P>
<P>
In the first half of this year, trade deficits already amounted
to 38.4 billion koruna (about 1.1 billion dollars), which accounts
for 11 percent of the GDP, one percentage point above the warning
level. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> XIE19980825.0289 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1998-08-25 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Majority Favor Censure or Reprimand for Clinton: Polls </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
WASHINGTON, August 24 (Xinhua) -- Although most Americans
oppose impeaching President Bill Clinton for any inappropriate
actions in the Monica Lewinsky affair, many people say Congress
should censure or officially reprimand him, several recent polls
suggest.
</P>
<P>
An ABC News poll released on Monday shows that 55 percent of
those surveyed thought Clinton should be censured or reprimanded,
while 40 percent opposed it.
</P>
<P>
A CNN/USA Today/Gallup poll said 41 percent favored a
congressional resolution disapproving of the president's behavior,
while 24 percent favored impeachment and 32 percent favored taking
no formal action.
</P>
<P>
In a Newsweek poll taken Thursday and Friday, people were
divided about whether Congress should censure or reprimand the
president, with 45 percent supporting such a step.
</P>
<P>
Clinton's job approval rating remained above 60 percent in all
three polls.
</P>
<P>
The public has two different views of the president, as
reflected in the polls, supporting his job performance but not
finding him trustworthy about personal matters.
</P>
<P>
While two-thirds in the ABC poll said Clinton was not
trustworthy personally, the same number said they trust him to
handle the nation's business. And 65 percent said a president who
does not provide good moral leadership can still be a good
president.
</P>
<P>
The Gallup poll suggested that two-thirds approved of Clinton's
dealings with Congress and on foreign affairs, while four out of
five liked his handling of the economy. Only 50 percent had
confidence in his dealing with issues concerning families. 
</P>
</TEXT>
