<HEADLINE> Albania Pushs Former Senior Officials to Court </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
TIRANA, August 24 (Xinhua) -- Six senior officials of the
former Democratic Party government were sent to court Monday,
accused of "crimes against humanity."
</P>
<P>
Among those arrested late Saturday were Safet Zhulali, former
minister of defense, and Halit Shamata, former minister of the
interior.
</P>
<P>
The court hearing is closed to the public and reporters.
</P>
<P>
The six men "took action, or no action, in league with others,
who were doing great damage to the nation of Albania, bringing
inestimable economic loss and causing the disappearance, death or
injury to thousands of people," according to a communique issued
by the Albania Military Attorney's Office on Monday.
</P>
<P>
They were also charged with "issuing or implementing orders to
use military mass-destruction chemical weapons on civilians in
February, 1997, issuing or implementing orders violating major
constitutional terms and resolutions of the People's Assembly to
take military actions with armed force on civilians, and issuing
orders to equip some people with arms on the basis of political
attitude to fight against their own compatriots."
</P>
<P>
The Democratic Party criticized the event as political action
attacking the opposition party, but the Socialist Party of
Albania, the biggest power in the coalition government, stated it
had not taken part in the action, which was completely an act of
state.
</P>
<P>
The Democratic Party fell out of power in July, 1997, and the
Socialist Party won to lead a five-party coalition government.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
