<HEADLINE> Seminar on Export Market Development Held in Myanmar </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
Yangon, August 25 (Xinhua) -- A Myanmar-Singapore seminar is
being held here to discuss and find means for export market
development as part of their endeavors to recover from the Asian
financial crisis.
</P>
<P>
The 12-day seminar, jointly sponsored by the Myanmar Ministry
of Commerce and Singapore Trade Development Board, is the third of
its kind conducted within the framework of trade development joint
venture initiatives. It is financed by Myanmar Technical
Assistance Fund, under Myanmar-Singapore Economic and Technical
Cooperation Programs signed in June 1995.
</P>
<P>
The international market environment is one of the topics being
discussed at the seminar.
</P>
<P>
At the opening ceremony on Monday, Myanmar Minister of Commerce
Major-General Kyaw Than called for identifying and taking
advantage of trade opportunities, formulating and pursuing
development strategies within the framework of the trading system
and defending the acquired trade rights.
</P>
<P>
He also called for investment in addition to searching for
export market development as the Asian economic boom in the past
couple of decades based substantially on the inflow of foreign
direct investment into the region.
</P>
<P>
Attending the seminar are trainees from Myanmar's nine
ministries, the Chamber of Commerce and Industry and private
firms.
</P>
<P>
The second seminar on export market development, sponsored by
the two parties, was held in March this year.
</P>
<P>
According to official statistics, Myanmar's foreign trade in
the 1997-98 fiscal year which ended in March totaled 3.24 billion
U.S. dollars, of which export amounted to 1 billion dollars,
registering a trade deficit of 1.24 billion dollars.
</P>
<P>
The country mostly traded with Asian countries which accounted
for about 80 percent of its total export value and about 86
percent of its total import value of the year. 
</P>
</TEXT>
