<HEADLINE> Missing Passenger Plane Found Crashed in Nepal </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
KATHMANDU, August 25 (Xinhua) -- The plane missing since last
Friday morning with 18 people aboard was found "crashed and in
pieces" Tuesday morning at an altitude of 12,000 feet (some 4,000
meters), an airport officer said.
</P>
<P>
"The crash site has been located and the rescue team is
expected to arrive there any moment," the officer at the Rescue
and Coordination Center of the capital's Tribhuvan International
Airport told Xinhua, adding that no further information was
available.
</P>
<P>
The ill-fated twin Otter aircraft was spotted on the western
side of Mt. Annapurna I by a helicopter on the search mission.
</P>
<P>
It lost contact five minutes after taking off at 11:10 a.m.
last Friday in Jomsom, western Nepal. It was scheduled to arrive
in Pokhara, just 80 kilometers away, at 11:30.
</P>
<P>
Those on board included three crew members and three Indians.
</P>
<P>
Four helicopters and the army and police have been involved in
the search efforts in the past five days, but their mission was
interrupted time and again by rain and thick fog.
</P>
<P>
The crashed plane belongs to the private-owned Lumbini Airways.
 
</P>
