<HEADLINE> Ecuador Trade Down Slightly in First Half of 1998 </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
QUITO, August 24(xinhua) -- Ecuadorian trade, with its Andean
Community (CAN) associates, rose 10.39 percent in the first half
of 1998, while its trade with the United States and the European
Union decreased 4.28 percent and 13.86 percent respectively.
</P>
<P>
Ecuador's total trade volume amounted to 4.856 billion
U.S. dollars in the first half of 1998, 0.27 percent less than the
same period in 1997.
</P>
<P>
Ecuador's trade with CAN increased to 810 million dollars in
the first half of 1998, a 10.39 percent rise over the same period
in 1997.
</P>
<P>
Though Ecuador's trade with Bolivia, Colombia, and Peru has
been on the rise, trade with Venezuela has decreased 8.87 percent.
</P>
<P>
In the first six months of 1998, Ecuador negotiated with
Bolivia a total of 8.6 million dollars in trade, 196.55 percent
more than 1997. Trade with Peru amounted to 165.4 million dollars,
which represents a 24.08 percent increase.
</P>
<P>
The trade between Ecuador and Colombia was 464 million dollars
in 1998, up from 454 million dollars in 1997.
</P>
<P>
The Venezuelan market is the only one that Ecuador has not been
able to recover. The trade exchange has decreased from 189.2
million dollars in the first half of 1997 to 172.4 million dollars
in the same period of 1998, a difference of 8.87 percent.
</P>
<P>
Ecuadorian exports to Venezuela reached 31.5 million dollars,
while imports reached 140.9 million dollars.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
