<HEADLINE> Myanmar to Accelerate Privatization Process </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
YANGON, August 25 (Xinhua) -- Myanmar leader Lieutenant-General
Khin Nyunt has stressed the need to accelerate the privatization
of heavy industries including small mills and factories.
</P>
<P>
Speaking at a meeting here Monday of the Myanmar Privatization
Commission (MPC), Khin Nyunt, First Secretary of the State Peace
and Development Council, called for giving opportunities to
government employees in the to-be-privatized mills and factories
to have shares in them, the official newspaper The New Light of
Myanmar reported Tuesday.
</P>
<P>
Khin Nyunt, who is also chairman of the MPC, noted that by
providing national entrepreneurs with greater opportunities,
productivity of the state would be enhanced and imports reduced in
the long run. He added that benefits like expansion of business
and creation of jobs would be brought about.
</P>
<P>
He said national progress would be gained only after achieving
success in the private sector.
</P>
<P>
The MPC, formed in January 1995, has announced the first-phase
plan of privatization of 51 state-owned economic enterprises
including processing and manufacturing factories, cinemas and
livestock breeding farms.
</P>
<P>
The privatization process has been under way in various forms
including auctioning and leasing out the enterprises or
establishing joint ventures with local and foreign entrepreneurs
or operating either under buy-back or counter-trade system.
</P>
<P>
In the first seven months of this year, about 140 state-run
cinemas, some 42 factories and two livestock breeding farms in the
country had been designated to be sold through competitive
bidding.
</P>
<P>
So far, more than two dozen state-owned saw mills have been
reportedly privatized.
</P>
<P>
According to official statistics, Myanmar's gross domestic
product in the 1997-98 fiscal year, which ended in March, grew by
4.6 percent over the previous year, in which the private sector
contributed 75.4 percent. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
