<HEADLINE> Pillar Industries Boost Shanghai Economy </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
SHANGHAI, August 25 (Xinhua) -- Six pillar industries accounted
for more than half of Shanghai's industrial sales during the first
half of this year.
</P>
<P>
The automobile manufacturing, electronic information, power
station equipment, petroleum and fine chemicals, iron and steel,
and household appliance sector recorded total sales of 118.5
billion yuan for the January-June period, with the figure rising
by 8.7 percent on the same 1997 period and accounting for 52
percent of the local industrial total.
</P>
<P>
The pillar sectors contributed 56 percent of pretax profits, or
12 billion yuan during the period.
</P>
<P>
The output value generated by the six sectors has jumped by 15
percent annually thanks to the introduction of local preferential
policies, heavy investment and the extensive use of technology.
</P>
<P>
The local industrial output value grew from 107.3 billion yuan
in 1987 to 560.6 billion yuan in 1997, with the significant growth
attributed to a shift in focus from textiles and light industrial
sectors to the six pillar industries.
</P>
<P>
Local industries grew by 15 percent annually between
1992-1996, up substantially from five percent growth in the late
1980s.
</P>
<P>
Shanghai has paid greater attention to the development of the
multimedia technology, bio-pharmaceuticals, new materials,
microelectronic, machinery, shipbuilding and marine engineering
industries, and is attempting to build same into local pillar
sectors for the next century. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
