<DOCNO> XIE19980825.0305 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1998-08-25 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Asia's Largest Marsh Gas Project Launched in Hangzhou </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
HANGZHOU, August 25 (Xinhua)-- Hangzhou, capital of east
China's Zhejiang province, is now building a marsh gas project,
which is claimed to be the largest in Asia.
</P>
<P>
The 10,00-cubic-meter facility, scheduled for completion next
February, is designed to turn 150 million kilograms of pig
droppings a year into methane gas, benefiting both local power
plants and residents.
</P>
<P>
Costing 10 million yuan (1.2 million U.S. dollars), including
two million yuan from the United Nations Food and Agriculture
Organization, the facility is part of an expansion project of the
Hangzhou Municipal Pig Farm which raises 250,000 pigs a year.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
