<DATE_TIME> 1998-08-25 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Oslo Marks 5th Anniversary of PLO-Israeli Peace Accord </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
STOCKHOLM, August 24 (Xinhua) -- Palestinian President Yasser
Arafat and Israeli officials stood side-by-side at ceremonies in
the Norwegian capital of Oslo on Monday to mark the fifth
anniversary of the first peace accord between Israel and the
Palestine Liberation Organization (PLO).
</P>
<P>
The ceremonies, aiming to push forward the stalled Middle East
peace process, were hosted by Norwegian Foreign Minister Knut
Vollebaek and attended by Arafat, former Israeli Prime Minister
Shimone Peres, parliamentary leader of Israel's ruling Likud
coalition Meir Sheetrit, and U.S. Peace Envoy Dennis Ross.
</P>
<P>
Arafat held talks with Peres and Sheetrit on Monday afternoon,
after which they appeared at a joint press conference.
</P>
<P>
Referring to a new stand of Israeli Prime Minister Benjamin
Netanyahu on the Israeli withdrawal from West Bank, Arafat called
it "a beginning" but "not a breakthrough" in the Middle East peace
process.
</P>
<P>
Peres expressed optimism for the survival of the Oslo Peace
Accord, noting that it was in line with the Israeli interests for
the Palestine state to exist and develop as a "partner" of Israel.
</P>
<P>
The Oslo Accord, reached on August 20, 1993, after long-time
secret negotiations between Israel and the PLO in the Norwegian
capital, has played a positive role in promoting the peace
process.
</P>
<P>
However, the process has been bogged down since Netanyahu's
government went into power in May 1996.
</P>
<P>
The commemoration of the peace accord in Oslo is seen as an
opportunity for unofficial contacts between the PLO and Israel to
rekindle the Oslo spirit. 
</P>
</TEXT>
