<HEADLINE> OAS to Send 15 Observers to Supervise Referendum in Panama </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
PANAMA City, August 24 (Xinhua) -- The Organization of American
States (OAS) will send 15 observers Tuesday to supervise Panama's
referendum to be held on August 30, according to a press release
issued by the OAS Monday.
</P>
<P>
A total of 1,718,878 citizens above the age of 18 will attend
the polls to decide whether to have an immediate presidential
reelection.
</P>
<P>
The international team is headed by Santiago Murray, personal
assistant of the General Secretariat of the OAS Cesar Gaviria.
Most of them will go to areas difficult to get access to to watch
over 4,478 voting boots.
</P>
<P>
The 15 OAS representatives will monitor the voting process
along with their European counterparts.
</P>
<P>
Carlos Roberto Reyna from Honduras, Ramiro de Leon from
Guatemala, Rafael Angel Calderon Fournier from Costa Rica, Eduardo
Penate from El Salvador are among the observers.
</P>
<P>
According to an official report, the Panamanian government has
given a budget of 7.9 million U.S. dollars for the referendum.
</P>
