<DATE_TIME> 1998-08-25 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Costa Rican Government Strives to Control Deficit </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
SAN JOSE, August 24 (Xinhua) -- President Miguel Angel
Rodriguez said the Costa Rican government has declared a war on
public deficit which he describes as "the source of all evils."
</P>
<P>
Rodriguez reiterated in an address to the nation Sunday that
his main goal is to reduce the cost of living, and the only way to
succeed is "reducing the tax deficit."
</P>
<P>
His government has adopted some measures to reduce the deficits
since he assumed presidency on May 8. The first measure was to
reduce 20 billion colonos (78 million dollars) in public spendings
since his first day in government.
</P>
<P>
The government strategy is to attract more investments, create
a stable macroeconomic environment, improve the infrastructure,
open the economy and eliminate state monopoly of insurance and
telecommunications businesses.
</P>
<P>
An economist and businessman himself with neo-liberal roots,
the president said the public debts have gone down to 3.7 percent
from 5 percent of the gross domestic product (GDP) and they will
be reduced to 2 percent of the GDP.
</P>
<P>
Inflation will probably be reduced by 14 percent next year, he
said. 
</P>
</TEXT>
