<DATE_TIME> 1998-08-25 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Thailand's Marble, Granite Firms Hit Hard Times </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
BANGKOK, August 25 (Xinhua) -- Almost 20 of Thailand's 106
marble and granite factories have closed because of the economic
slowdown, according to the Thai Marble and Granite Association.
</P>
<P>
More companies will close or cut production if no solutions are
found soon, Pichit Sawangvibulpong, secretary-general of the
association, was quoted Tuesday by the newspaper Bangkok Post as
saying.
</P>
<P>
During the time of economic boom, the industry's output was 8
million cubic meters a year, but plunging demand has reduced the
total to about 2 million cubic meters, he said.
</P>
<P>
The credit squeeze that began in mid-1997 has affected many
producers, making it difficult to run or expand their businesses
while many customers have refused to pay their bills, he said.
</P>
<P>
At the same time, production costs have climbed, especially for
imported equipment such as saws and cutters.
</P>
<P>
Some producers have been looking to overseas markets to offset
low domestic demand, Pichit said.
</P>
<P>
The association will hold a seminar on September 9 in Bangkok
to discuss ways for marble and granite producers to ride out the
economic crisis, Pichit said. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
