<HEADLINE> Highlights of Major Beijing-Based Newspapers </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
BEIJING, August 25 (Xinhua) -- Highlights of today's major
Beijing-based newspapers:
</P>
<P>
 "People's Daily"
</P>
<P>
-- Premier Zhu Rongji says he is concerned about relief
supplies, especially clothing and shelter, for flood-stricken
areas in northeastern China.
</P>
<P>
The premier has told various central departments to deliver the
goods as soon and as efficiently as possible.
</P>
<P>
Heilongjiang and Jilin provinces and the Inner Mongolia
Autonomous Region have been battling severe flooding for the past
several weeks.
</P>
<P>
-- China's highest legislative body plans to discuss a draft of
the first contract law and amendments to the adoption law.
</P>
<P>
The proposed contracts law will combine three existing laws,
parts of which contradict each other in some ways, according to Hu
Kangsheng, deputy-director of the Commission of the Legislative
Affairs of the National People's Congress (NPC) Standing Committee.
</P>
<P>
-- Vice-Premier Li Lanqing met yesterday with Klaus Topfer,
under-secretary-general of the United Nations and executive
director of the UN Environment Program.
</P>
<P>
Li said that China attaches great importance to environmental
protection in the course of expanding its economy. He added that
China is fully prepared to step up cooperation with the UN
Environment Program.
</P>
<P>
 "Xinhua Daily Telegraph"
</P>
<P>
-- Li Ruihuan, chairman of the National Committee of the
Chinese People's Political Consultative Conference (CPPCC),
yesterday thanked the country's Taoists for their donation of a
large amount of money to the victims of the recent floods.
</P>
<P>
Li, a Standing Committee member of the Communist Party of China
Central Committee's Political Bureau, met with Taoists attending
the Sixth Congress of the China Taoist Association that was held
August 20-24 and conveyed the thanks of the CPC Central Committee
and the State Council for Taoists who have been active in the
nationwide campaign to help the flood victims.
</P>
<P>
-- Vice-Premier Li Lanqing told a group of young Chinese
scientists that the government should trust and support young
scientists and help them concentrate on their academic research
and technological development.
</P>
<P>
Li told the young scientists, who were attending the Third
Annual Symposium of Young Scientists, which is sponsored by the
China Association for Science and Technology, that the requisite
conditions and assistance should be available for those who work
abroad but want to help the motherland so that they can serve
China in various ways.
</P>
<P>
 "China Daily"
</P>
<P>
-- Political negotiations between the Chinese mainland and
Taiwan province remain high on the agenda, according to a leading
official from the State Council's Taiwan Affairs Office.
</P>
<P>
Speaking in a recent interview with Xinhua, the official said
the concerted efforts of Chinese people on both sides of the
Taiwan Straits have led to the steady development of economic and
cultural exchanges.
</P>
<P>
-- An official with the Beijing-based Association for Relations
Across Taiwan Straits (Arats) has flown to northwestern Gansu
province to deal with aftermath of last week's traffic accident
that killed seven people, including six Taiwan tourists.
</P>
<P>
-- Floods have reduced the daily crude oil output by 3,000 tons
or two percent in Daqing Oilfield, the largest in China, officials
said yesterday.
</P>
<P>
To date, more than 1,700 oil wells have been inundated by
torrential rains and floods, according to the Daqing Oilfield
Administration Bureau. 
</P>
