<DATE_TIME> 1998-08-25 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Embryo's Defenses May Prevent Miscarriage </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
WASHINGTON, August 24 (Xinhua) -- Researchers from the
University of Georgia have found the secrets why pregnant women's
immune systems don't attack developing babies in their wombs as
they are foreign entities.
</P>
<P>
Researchers have long wondered why pregnant women's immune
systems don't attack fetal in their wombs as they would other
foreign entities like viruses, bacteria or a parasite.
</P>
<P>
A new research, reported by Monday's Washington Post, suggests
that the developing embryo actively defends itself from attack by
sending out a signal that shuts down the mother's natural defenses.
</P>
<P>
The researchers headed by David H. Munn of the University
treated pregnant mice to prevent fetal production of an enzyme
that destroys a substance that triggers key immune system cells
called T cells. Mice carrying genetically foreign embryos had
miscarriages.
</P>
<P>
The researchers say their findings potentially could lead to
new ways to prevent miscarriages in people. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
