<DOCNO> XIE19980825.0346 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1998-08-25 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Italy Anti-doping Head Hopes to Ban Creatine </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
ROME, August 24 (Xinhua) -- Ugo Longo, who heads an Italian
Olympic Committee inqury into doping, called here on Monday that
the rampantly used substance creatine should be banned.
</P>
<P>
Creatine is a naturally-occurring aminoacid, taken onboard
when eating steak or drinking milk. It improves muscles by
speeding the conversion of stored energy to burned energy in
physical exercise.
</P>
<P>
However, Longo has adopted the line taken by many experts who
claim that creatine, when taken in very large doses, can actually
increase an athlete's muscle mass, and therefore his performance.
</P>
<P>
Longo said: "We cannot take decisions, we can only provide
indications -- and those we will give are that the use of this
substance needs clearing up."
</P>
<P>
If creatine can improve a player's performance it needs to be
banned or at least limited in terms of the amount being
administered."
</P>
<P>
The inquiry has attracted world-wide attention following a
warning by AS Roma coach Zdenek Zeman that footballers were
taking dangerous substances, and that the Serie A were facing a
danger similar to the Tour de France. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
