<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Sampras, Hingis Named Top Seed at U.S. Open Tennis </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
WASHINGTON, August 24 (Xinhua) -- World number ones Pete
Sampras of the United States and Martina Hingis of Switzerland
were named the top seeds for next week's U.S. Open, the USTA
announced today in New York.
</P>
<P>
With the lone exception of five-time U.S. Open champion Steffi
Graf of Germany, the USTA seeded players directly according to
the latest ATP and WTA Tour rankings. Currently ranked 38th, Graf
received the eighth seed due to a recommendation from WTA Tour
players. She missed last year's U.S. Open after having
season-ending knee surgery.
</P>
<P>
Sampras, a four-time champion, regained the world No. 1
ranking from Chile's Marcelo Rios for the second time this year
in the latest ATP rankings. But he has not displayed the form
that has seen him finish as the top-ranked player for five
straight years.
</P>
<P>
The 27-year-old Sampras captured his only Grand Slam title of
the year at Wimbledon and has won just three events this year
after going unbeaten in eight finals in 1997. He lost to Petr
Korda of the Czech Republic in the fourth round at last year's
U.S. Open.
</P>
<P>
He was the top seed in 1994, 1996 and 1997 and has won the
annual Grand Slam finale in 1990, 1993, 1995 and 1996. He is tied
with Bjorn Borg of Sweden with 11 Grand Slam titles, one behind
all-time leader Roy Emerson.
</P>
<P>
Last year, Hingis beat Venus Williams in an all-teenage
final,the youngest women's Grand Slam championship in the Open
history, Hingis became the second-youngest Open women's champion.
</P>
<P>
The Australian Open champion, Hingis has won just four events
this year and none since May. In 1997, the Swiss sensation
claimed 12 titles and suffered five losses all year. This season,
she already has lost nine matches.
</P>
<P>
Rios, who won just one match in two brief reigns as the No. 1
players, is the second seed, followed by defending champion
Patrick Rafter of Australia, Australian Open champion Kord and
Richard Krajicek of the Netherlands. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
