<HEADLINE> Cooper, Chancellor Win WNBA Awards </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
WASHINGTON, August 24 (Xinhua) -- The Houston Comets shooting
guard Cynthia Cooper was named the WNBA league's most valuable
player and coach Van Chancellor won coach of the year honors in
Houston on Monday.
</P>
<P>
The defending champions' player and coach repeated as the
award winners in the WNBA's second year of operation.
</P>
<P>
"Without an MVT team, I couldn't be the MVP," cooper said.
"When you have a talented team like ours, it's awesome to think
of the sacrifices each player makes to make the team one."
</P>
<P>
Suzie McConnell Serio of the Cleveland Rockers, who averaged
8.6 points and 6.4 assists per game, was named New comer of the
Year.
</P>
<P>
Cooper led the WNBA in scoring for the second straight year
with a 22.7-point average and fourth in the league in assists and
3-point goals.
</P>
<P>
She won 37 first-place votes and a total of 426 points in
balloting by media. Second behind her was Jennifer Gillom of
Phoenix, who received eight first-place votes and 303 total
points.
</P>
<P>
The Comets won the inaugural WNBA title last season and went
into Monday's first round playoff game with a 1-0 lead against
the Charlotte Sting in their best-of-3 series.
</P>
<P>
Chancellor led the Comets to a 27-3 record that included a
league-best 15-game winning streak. His team set a WNBA record by
scoring 76 points per game and also led the league in defense,
allowing an average of 63.6 points.
</P>
<P>
Chancellor received 26 media votes. Detroit's Nancy
Lieberman-Cline finished second with 11 votes, followed by
Cleveland's Linda Hill-MacDonald with six.  
</P>
</TEXT>
