<DOCNO> XIE19980825.0360 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1998-08-25 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Work on Security Council Reform to Continue </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
UNITED NATIONS, August 24 (Xinhua) -- The current session of
the U.N. General Assembly (GA) ended its consideration of the
Security Council reform without sound results, but the work on the
matter will continue in the next session, it was announced here
Monday.
</P>
<P>
While some progress has been made and new ideas have emerged,
the working group on the question of equitable representation on
and increase in the membership of the Security Council has not
been able to submit substantive recommendations to the GA, said GA
president Hennadiy Udovenko of Ukraine.
</P>
<P>
He made the remarks Monday following the adoption of the report
by the group which decided that its deliberations should continue
and that it should submit another report to the GA by the end of
the 53rd GA session in 1999.
</P>
<P>
Udovenko said stumbling blocks to the group's work include:
opposition to creating new permanent seats, disagreement over the
size of an enlarged council, different approaches to the issue of
rotational arrangements for new permanent seats, and differences
on the veto right for current and prospective permanent members.
</P>
<P>
Currently, the Security Council consists of 15 members, five
permanent ones, that is, China, France, Russia, the U.K. and the
U.S., and 10 non-permanent ones to be elected by the GA for a term
of two years.
</P>
<P>
The working group has met a record number of times, with 56
meetings during the current GA session, said its report.
</P>
<P>
In the current session, it dealt with decision-making in the
Security Council, including the veto, expansion of the council,
including the total size of the enlarged council, increase of
permanent membership and non-permanent membership, periodic review
of the enlarged council and majority required for taking decisions
on council reform.
</P>
<P>
The failure to yield practical results could stem from the
outside world perceiving that the reform exercise merely reflects
conflicting interests between different groups in pursuit of their
own goals, said Udovenko.
</P>
<P>
However, the reform exercise has not been initiated to satisfy
such interests, he said.
</P>
<P>
In deliberating on reforming the council, there should only be
one predominating interest -- to enhance the relevance of the U.N.
to the requirements of a changing world and to ensure that it
could more effectively and efficiently meet the challenges of the
new century, he noted.
</P>
<P>
After five years of discussions, if there is still need for
anything to be explored, it is states' ability to see beyond
national interests, he said.
</P>
<P>
The working group was set up on December 3, 1993 according to
GA resolution 48/26. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> XIE19980825.0361 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1998-08-25 </DATE_TIME>
