<BODY>
<HEADLINE> News Analysis: Serious Talks Crucial to Political </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
UNITED NATIONS, August 24 (Xinhua) -- The United Nations
Security Council Monday adopted a presidential statement, calling
for "an immediate cease-fire" in Kosovo and an early commencement
of substantial talks between conflict parties in the southernmost
province of Serbia.
</P>
<P>
The statement mirrored the grave concerns of the 15-member
Security Council over the recent fighting in Kosovo, which has had
a devastating impact on the civilian population and resulted in a
swollen army of refugees and displaced people.
</P>
<P>
Monday's presidential statement coincided with the approaching
of the Balkan winter, which observers here feared could turn a
humanitarian disaster in the making into a full-scale catastrophe.
</P>
<P>
The same anxiety was echoed by Sadako Ogata, head of the U.N.
refugee agency, who has dispatched Soren Jessen-Petersen, the
United Nations assistant high commissioner for refugees, to Kosovo
for a first-hand picture of what life the refugees and displaced
were leading.
</P>
<P>
Since the conflict escalated in rebel-held areas in late June,
civilians have emptied large sections of Kosovo, where ethnic
Albanians make up a majority of the population.
</P>
<P>
International aid agencies have been unable to keep up with the
flow of civilians fleeing the fighting, and relief workers found
it hard to reach those currently living in forests and mountains.
</P>
<P>
More than 500 people have been killed and some 200,000 people,
about 10 percent of Kosovo's population, displaced since the
security force of the Federal Republic of Yugoslavia fought
against separatist rebels of the ethnic Albanian Kosovo Liberation
Army about six moths ago.
</P>
<P>
"The Council affirms the right of all refugees and displaced
persons to return to their homes," the presidential statement
said.
</P>
<P>
But to ensure such right requires substantial talks between the
conflict parties. U.N. Secretary-General Kofi Annan said in his
latest report that failure to enter into meaningful negotiations
has worsened the situation in Kosovo.
</P>
<P>
Ethnic Albanians have set up a negotiating team to represent
their interests, but they failed to turn up in proposed talks on
August 18, thus making it hard for the international community to
see the scheduled beginning of the long-awaited talks.
</P>
<P>
It is widely accepted that "the Kosovo issue can have no
military solution." Over the past months, the reality in Kosovo
has shown that pushing the peace process forward is no easy work
at all.
</P>
<P>
Observers here say it remains essential that the authorities of
the Federal Republic of Yugoslavia and the Kosovo Albanians accept
their responsibility for ending the bloodshed in Kosovo, for
allowing the people of Kosovo to resume their normal lives and for
moving the peace process forward.
</P>
<P>
Therefore, it is highly hoped that all relevant parties can
take into account the state interests and the worsening physical
conditions of refugees and displaced people, and begin to sit at
the negotiating table at an early date for a peaceful settlement,
including the safe and permanent return of all internally
displaced persons and refugees to their homes. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
