<DOCNO> XIE19980825.0367 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1998-08-25 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> 16 Sentenced to Death in S. Leone Coup Trial </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
LAGOS, August 24 (Xinhua) -- Sixteen civilians, including five
journalists, were sentenced to death in Sierra Leone Monday on
charges of treason for their role in a May 1997 coup in the West
African State, a report reaching here said.
</P>
<P>
Among those condemned is Allieu Kamara, spokesman of the
military junta led by Major Johnny Paul Koroma, who seized power
in the coup from elected President Ahmed Tejan Kabbah.
</P>
<P>
Also sentenced to death are Christian Kargbo, the junta's
central bank governor and Hilton Fyle, a former presenter with
the British Broadcasting Corporation (BBC)'s Africa Service and
owner of an FM radio station in Freetown, the report said.
</P>
<P>
Another prominent journalist among the 16 is Felix George,
former director-general of the Sierra Leone Broadcasting
Corporation.
</P>
<P>
Monday's delivery of sentence is the first since trial started
about four months ago.
</P>
<P>
The conviction was announced by Justice Edmond Cowan in a
courtroom in central Freetown, the capital of Sierra Leone, the
report said.
</P>
<P>
Two other persons were discharged and acquitted by the court.
</P>
<P>
The 16 people were tried on various charges of collaborating
with the military junta, which was driven out of Freetown in
February by the West African peace-keeping force ECOMOG.
</P>
<P>
According to the report, altogether 60 civilians and 38 junta
soldiers were put on trial after President Kabbah resumed office
last March from exile in Guinea. 
</P>
</TEXT>
